{"title_page": "Xuan-Yuan Sword", "text_new": "{{short description|Series of Chinese role-playing video games}}\n{{italic title}}\n'''''Xuan-Yuan Sword''''' ({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d}}, literally \"Sword of the [[Yellow Emperor|Xuan-Yuan]]\")<ref>The official translation about \"\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\" is \"Xuan-Yuan Sword\", instead of \"Xuan-Yuan Jian\". Reference:[http://swd1017.myweb.hinet.net/windheart/news/70/paper62.htm \u6953\u821e\u8ed2\u8f45\u96fb\u5b50\u5831\u7b2c\u516d\u5341\u4e8c\u671f\uff1a\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u7684\u82f1\u6587\u540d\u5b57(The E-Paper of the Maple Dance with Xuan-Yuan Sword, 62nd: The English Name of Xuan-Yuan Sword)]</ref> refers to a series of Taiwanese [[role-playing video game]]s for [[personal computers]] developed by the DOMO Studio (DOMO\u5c0f\u7d44/\u591a\u9b54\u5c0f\u7d44) of [[Softstar Entertainment Inc.]] (\u5927\u5b87\u8cc7\u8a0a) based in [[Taiwan]]. The games incorporate elements of [[Chinese mythology]] as well as historic figures and events.\n\nIn time immemorial, the \"Xuan-Yuan Sword\" was wielded by [[Yellow Emperor]] of ancient China to defend the ancient Chinese against the warlord [[Chi You]] and his aggressive subjects. After Chi You's defeat, the future for the five-thousand-year-old history of China was secured, and the Sword was passed on from Yellow Emperor to future generations to continue to defend the world against evil. Due to its great power, the sword was often sought by treacherous individuals to further their own ends.\n\nA recurring item of the series is the ''Monster Fusion Vessel'' (''Lian Yao Hu'', \u7149\u5996\u58fa), created by the goddess [[N\u00fcwa]] in emulation of the Immortal Creation Ding (\u9020\u7269\u4ed9\u9f0e) to cleanse the world. Within the Vessel resides an immortal entity known as the ''Spirit in the Vessel.'' The Vessel's powers are to absorb nonhuman creatures, and to transmute them into other creatures or items.\n\n== Main series ==\n\n{{VG timeline\n| 1990 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword''\n| 1994 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword 2''\n| 1995 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword: Dance of Maple Banners''\n| 1999 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword 3''\n| 2000 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword 3: The Scar of the Sky''\n| 2002 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword 4''\n| 2004 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Millennial Destiny''\n| 2006 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword 5''\n| 2007 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Han Clouds''\n| 2010 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Clouds Faraway''\n| 2013 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword 6''\n| 2015 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Gate of Firmament''\n| TBA = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword 7''\n}}\n\nThe Xuan-Yuan Sword series is the oldest and longest living Chinese RPG series, totaling 13 RPGs with ancient Chinese-style stories set in ancient Chinese backgrounds. They are:\n* 01 Xuan-Yuan Sword\n* 02 Xuan-Yuan Sword II\n* 03 Xuan-Yuan Sword: Dance of Maple Banners\n* 04 Xuan-Yuan Sword III: Beyond Clouds and Mountains (The story happened around the time of the [[An Lushan Rebellion]]. The protagonist started from Venice, Italy, and crossed the entire Eurasian continent to reach [[Chang'an]], the Capital of the [[Tang Dynasty]] of China)\n* 05 Xuan-Yuan Sword III: Scar of the Sky (The story happened in late [[Sui dynasty|Sui Dynasty]])\n* 06 Xuan-Yuan Sword IV: The Black Dragon Dances as Storm Rages (The story Happened in late [[Qin Dynasty]])\n* 07 Xuan-Yuan Sword IV: The Millennial Destiny (Part of the story happened in the [[Spring and Autumn period]] of China, in the 6th Century BC, and the other part 1000 years later, during the [[Battle of Fei River]], during the [[East Jin Dynasty]])\n* 08 Xuan-Yuan Sword V: A Sword above the Clouds and the Sentiment of [[Shanhai Jing|Shanhai]] (The story happened in an alternate world called the world of Shanhai, or literally the world of the [[Classic of Mountains and Seas]]. The time is equivalent to late [[Three Kingdoms]] period in our world)\n* 09 Xuan-Yuan Sword V: The Clouds of Han (The story happened in the period of Three Kingdoms of China)\n* 10 Xuan-Yuan Sword V: The Clouds Faraway (The game consists of 3 chapters: the main chapter, the chapter of Lan Ying, and the chapter of [[Wuzhang Plains]]. The story happened in the period of Three Kingdoms.)\n* 11 Xuan-Yuan Sword VI: The Phoenix Soars over Millennial Clouds (The story happened in the [[Zhou dynasty|West Zhou dynasty]])\n* 12 Xuan-Yuan Sword VI: The Gate of Firmament (The story happened in the [[Shang dynasty|Shang Dynasty]])\n* 13 Xuan-Yuan Sword VII (The story happened in late [[Han dynasty|West Han Dynasty]])\n\n=== Xuan-Yuan Sword ===\n\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword\")\n\nIn the beginning of the world, the goddess [[N\u00fcwa]] created two kinds of intelligent life: those of men, and those of monsters, who warred among each other all the time. The Sword was created by men in an attempt to end the everlasting war. Led by a single heroic figure, Xuan-yuan Swordsman (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u4fe0) who wielded the Sword, the war between humans and monsters ended with both sides suffering heavy casualties. Seventeen years later, the main character, He Ran (\u4f55\u7136), a young swordsman left his mentor to set off on a journey into the chaotic world to carve his own path.\n\nThe first game in the series, Xuan-Yuan Sword was also Softstar's first RPG product and was released in 1990. The time period the game is set in is ambiguous. The game features a [[Dragon Quest]]-like user interface. Players started the game as a novice adventurer with minimal fighting skills and can gain combat experience through battles to enable progression to other areas and advance the plot. The main characters were named after the characters from [[A Chinese Ghost Story]] in this game, but their names were retconned in the second game.\n\nThe game featured standard VGA 16-colored 640x480 screen, complete with party-members, round-based combat, full-screen sprite animation, various monsters, Chinese-styled AdLb music, sound effects, animated spell effects, as well as full Chinese interface, which was a great hit in Taiwan's computer game market at that period.\n\nReleased on October 13, 1990.\n\n=== Xuan-Yuan Sword 2 ===\n\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u8cb3}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword 2\")\n\nContinuing from where the first game left off, He Ran (\u4f55\u7136), together with the vigilante Yang Kunshuo (\u694a\u5764\u78a9) and the young thaumaturge Jiang Ruhong (\u6c5f\u5982\u7d05), defeated the dreaded incarnation of the Flaming Phoenix (\u706b\u9cf3\u51f0) (the sinister monster who kidnapped Jiang), befriended a benevolent fox spirit Gu Yuesheng (\u53e4\u6708\u8056), and traveled back in time to find He Ran's parents. They sought to bring about the end of the leader of the invasive monsters, known as the Wicked God (\u60e1\u795e), [[Bashe]], and eventually confronted the treacherous Spirit of the Vessel.\n\nReleased on February 8, 1994.\n\n; Features\n: Many key features of the game series were introduced with this game. It was set in 320\u00d7240 256-colored screen (in the once-popular VGA X-mode). In-game artworks such as scenes, monsters, character portraits, items were fashioned in [[Chinese painting]] style.\n\n; Monster Fusion Vessel\n: Another key feature is the Vessel system. Not long after the beginning of the game, the Monster Fusion Vessel can be acquired, and has two main functions:\n# Absorb enemies encountered in battle, with limitations:\n#* Cannot absorb creatures that have higher experience level than player, and those creatures whose levels are close to the players' are more easily captured when wounded.\n#* Bosses creatures and human enemies cannot be absorbed.\n#* Imprisoned monsters are visible in players inventory and can be summoned to assist during battle with a stamina cost.\n# Transmutation. A player can transmute creatures and items to other objects or creatures. The resulting product may be exceedingly powerful or unobtainable otherwise.\n\n; The Sword\n: In the battle against the final boss, the Vessel Spirit, the goddess N\u00fcwa appeared and revealed the truth that Xuan-Yuan Swordsman was He Ran's father whose spirit has fused with the Xuan-Yuan Sword. Receiving the powerful weapon from the goddess, the protagonist and his company went to the World Within the Vessel and defeated the treacherous Vessel Spirit, sealing him by planting the Xuan-Yuan Sword in his head.\n\nThis installment also introduced a recurring element of the series, the DOMO Studio that is present in all future games in vastly different incarnations that players can visit to access humorous fourth wall-breaking dialogue, quests, and items.\n\n=== Xuan-Yuan Sword 3: Beyond the Clouds and Mountains ===\n\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u53c3\uff1a\u96f2\u548c\u5c71\u7684\u5f7c\u7aef}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword 3: Beyond Clouds and Mountains\")\n\nThe story opens in [[Venice]] with Septem (\u8cfd\u7279), a Frankish knight and covert intelligence operative of mixed descent from [[Gaul]] who was the lieutenant to [[Pepin the Younger]]. Septem possessed an heirloom bronze vessel with an eastern design, which was in fact the Monster Fusion Vessel. He had heterochromic pupils of blue and brown, garnering discrimination and distrust from his peers and fellow knights over his somewhat Eastern appearance. Miles (\u9ea5\u723e\u65af) (the reincarnation of Satan whose memories and innate powers had not yet been fully awakened), a knight-commander under the guidance of the cleric Cornelius (\u5eb7\u90a3\u91cc\u58eb) (the Dread Lord of Hell in disguise), was the polar opposite of his rival Septem, enforcing the Church's will without mercy and question, executing those designated as heretics without hesitation, and had the affection of Lilian (\u8389\u84ee), a pure maiden Septem had courted in vain. Pepin himself, however, favored Septem, and gave him a quest of great import. He was to go to the East, and find the way to achieve Absolute Victory/the Way of the King. During the journey, a simpleminded demoness named Nicole (\u59ae\u53ef) joined Septem after being summoned by a strange dying man Septem tried to help, as an agent sent by [[Satan]]. Her mission was to awaken Septem's memory of his past life, in which he was Lucifer's most trusted ally who took part in Lucifer's Rebellion, and to convert him to Satan's cause once more, accompanied with promises of wealth, power, and demonic servants, but she eventually abandoned her mission over the fondness she developed for Septem. Kama, a self-proclaimed spirit of love, and Ankh, a snarky talking flying Egyptian black cat accompanying Kama (both of whom Septem encountered in the [[Palmyra#Site|Tadmor Tombs]]), as well as [[Li Jing (Tang dynasty)|Li Jing]] (\u674e\u9756), a Chinese mortal-turned-deity who oversaw the establishment of the Tang dynasty, whose reincarnated self, Master Huiyan, previously accompanied Septem for a short time before sacrificing himself in an attempt to stop a [[Battle of Talas|war between the Abbasid Caliphate (which recently overthrew Umayyad rule) and Tang]] (which ended in the defeat of the Tang forces led by [[Gao Xianzhi]]), also joined the party. Septem also met his eventual wife, Widad (\u8587\u9054), a military leader who defied Arabian patriarchal traditions and who was the reincarnated spirit twin of Kama, and the young grandson of [[Al-Kindi]], whom Septem studied under for a short time around the time of the [[Abbasid Revolution]], as well as Wang Siyue (\u738b\u601d\u6708), a willful young woman from [[Chang'an]] with feelings for Septem, along his journey. After finally reaching China and encountering a variety of conflicts, including the [[An Lushan Rebellion]], the group discovered Satan's plan to subjugate all worlds by using the Reversal of [[Mandala]] Ritual (\u53cd\u66fc\u9640\u7f85\u9663), which Septem's past incarnation invented and gained time traversal powers from, to modify the natural laws of causality, and managed to foil it with the assistance of The Immortal of Xuan-yuan Sword (the avatar of the Xuan-Yuan Sword who takes on the form of a stern and wise old man). After Satan's defeat, Septem married Widad, returned to assist [[Charlemagne]] with lessons from his journey-that a ruler must rule in the best interests of the commonfolk, and the way to ensure victory lies in the prevention and cessation of conflicts, and later reunited with Nicole, who was reborn once more as a normal girl by the grace of Heaven.\n\nThe game eschews turn-based battles for the [[Active Time Battle]] combat system, an unusual feature in Chinese RPGs. The refining system in the game has two categories of items and creatures, Eastern and Western, which allows for the creation of different items based on altar selection.\n\nThe game was released on December 4, 1999. An iOS port of the game with additional storylines and scenes meant to expand the portion of the game set in China was released on January 17, 2017.\n\n=== Xuan-Yuan Sword 4: The Black Dragon Dances as the Storm Rages ===\n\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u8086\uff1a\u9ed1\u9f8d\u821e\u516e\u96f2\u98db\u63da}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword 4: The Black Dragon Dances! The Clouds Fly)\n\nThis game is the fourth installment of the main series. The game is the first to be presented in 3D, both in environment and in combat.\nThe story starts with an orphaned girl from the late [[Zhao (state)|Zhao state]], Shui Jing (\u6c34\u93e1) and her senior disciple-sister, Qu Xian (\u5c48\u5afb) on the top of a mountain with their seniors from the House of [[Mohism|Mo]], a Mohist clan actively opposing the tyranny of [[Qin dynasty|Qin]] and [[King Zheng of Qin|its leader]], who is often accompanied by a mysterious purple-skinned adviser (later revealed to be the original Vessel Spirit on an ideological mission to create an unified utopia by absorbing the mortal world into the universe created by the Spirit - \"Realm in the Clouds\"). Qu Xian witnessed her companions being murdered by giant mechanical constructs created with the Jiguan technique. Later, Shui Jing meets with Ji Liang (\u59ec\u826f) (later known as [[Zhang Liang (Western Han)|Zhang Liang]] \u5f35\u826f), a well-educated young man from the annihilated [[Han (state)|Han state]] who can utilize the Scroll of Heaven (Tian Shu \u5929\u66f8) in battles after obtaining and deciphering it in an early escapade with Shui Jing, and Ji Peng (\u75be\u9d6c), a humorous talking bird king who employs a humanoid Jiguan body in battle. The three journey across various lands to combat the machinations of the Qin Empire and the Vessel Spirit. Later in the story, Ji Peng is revealed to be the bird owned by the Mo clan leader's husband, Fu Ziche (\u8f14\u5b50\u5fb9) (introduced in Dance of Maple along with the current Mo leader, Lady Wenjin (\u7d0b\u9326), renowned for her eternal youthfulness), who had been sealed in ice in the World Within the Vessel after a battle with the Vessel Spirit during which he averted disaster by preventing the Black Fire the Vessel Spirit unleashed using a purple crystal in desperation from taking form. The trio eventually reconcile their differences with the Spirit, rescued Fu Ziche, and confronted the true threat, battling with all nine portions of Black Fire (with each portion increasing its power and all nine portions 4^128 times as powerful as one portion alone) running amok, which is believed to be the ultimate weapon of the Hell that can take the form of a black dragon, discovered long ago using purple crystals by the ancient Shu kingdom engineer Qi, who caused the destruction of his civilization and was sealed away in a protective cocoon until the events of the game, when he took control of Lady Wenjin (who was created with Black Fire) and Black Fire to go on a rampage to destroy the world (or in his mind, creating a world where hell and the mortal realm co-existed in order to eliminate death) upon awakening.\n\nReleased on the August 4, 2002.\n\n=== Xuan-Yuan Sword 5: A Sword Above the Clouds and the Sentiments of the World of Shanhai ===\n\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u4f0d\uff1a\u4e00\u528d\u51cc\u96f2\u5c71\u6d77\u60c5}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword 5: A Sword Soaring Above Clouds; Shanhai Sentiments\")\n\nThe main character Lu Chengxuan (\u9678\u627f\u8ed2) killed his parents as a result of not being able control his mysterious power, and was about to die in the wilderness as an outcast when he was coincidentally brought to the World of [[Classic of Mountains and Seas|Shanhai]] through a portal created by Huangfu Muyun (\u7687\u752b\u66ae\u96f2), a powerful wielder of sword energy and the avatar of the Xuanyuan Sword, using the Pangu Axe. There, he encounters Xia Rou (\u590f\u67d4), second empress of the Kingdom of Women. The two traveled around the world, meeting with people from other kingdoms, and set out to accomplish a task given to them by the Elder of the Green Dragon Kingdom, leading to a confrontation with the exiled Princess of Heaven, [[N\u00fcba|Qing'er (\u9752\u5152)]], who helped the [[Yellow Emperor]], Ji Xuanyuan (\u59ec\u8ed2\u8f45), claim the mortal world for humans and was banished due to her newly acquired form causing cataclysmic droughts after expending her power in aiding him in reforging the sword that would later be known as the Xuan Yuan Sword.\n\nReleased on August 4, 2006.\n\n=== Xuan-Yuan Sword 6: The Phoenix Soars in the Sky among Millennial Clouds ===\n\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u9678\uff1a\u9cf3\u51cc\u9577\u7a7a\u5343\u8f09\u96f2}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword 6: The Fenghuang Rising High Above the Sky and Thousand-year Clouds\")\n\nIn c. 1046 BCE, the [[Battle of Muye]] erupted. The leader of the Zhou of the west, [[Ji Fa]], took the opportunity presented when [[King Zhou of Shang]] rallied his forces in a southeastern expedition and when the Shang capital of [[Zhaoge]] was undefended to form an alliance with leaders in the west at [[Mengjin]] to perform a swift strike against the capital.\n\nHearing of the impending attack, the Shang king was caught off guard and forced to head to Muye for battle, and ended up burning himself alive on the [[Deer Terrace Pavilion]], thus ending the six-hundred-year reign of the [[Shang Dynasty]] and ushering in the era of the [[Zhou Dynasty]].\n\nAfter the Battle of Muye, the tense atmosphere remained between the Shang and Zhou people. The Shang remnant forces retreated to the largest vassal state in the east, [[Qufu|Yan (\u5944\u570b)]], for a respite until a chance for rebellion arose. King Zhou's son, [[Wu Geng]], was held at Zhaoge.  King Wu of Zhou (formerly known as Ji Fa) assigned land and title to him, but ordered his three younger brothers to keep Wu Geng confined and under surveillance to prevent rebellion. With the passing of King Wu from illness, the [[Duke of Zhou]] who served as a royal advisor was accused of attempting to seize the throne, and had to resign to prove his innocence, causing the kingdom to be leaderless and the political situation to become volatile. The Shang sought to seize this chance to attack [[Haojing]] to reclaim the kingdom. A war between the east and west appears to be imminent, and at the same time, a mysterious force stirs in the dark.\n\nThe game opens with a cinematic of a battle between [[Xia dynasty|Xia]] and Shang forces at the Xia capital [[Zhenxun]] that concludes with the end of the Xia Dynasty and the deaths of two Xia lovers, the warrior Si Tianjia (\u59d2\u5929\u7532) and the priestess Miao Ji (\u82d7\u59ec). The two promise each other to transmigrate as enemies of Shang to oppose it together in their next lives. As they lay dying, a Xia artifact, the Holy Circlet of Tianhuan carried by Miao Ji splits into two halves and merges with Si Tianjia and Miao Ji.\n\nThe story focuses on the conflict among the reigning Zhou and the subordinate Shang states. The main character, Feng Tianling (\u9cf3\u5929\u51cc), is a proud young Shang noble raised in Yan who can see and communicate with spirits and supernatural creatures. A benevolent spirit, Hupo (\u7425\u73c0 Amber), has been his friend and companion since he was young. He sets out on a journey of self-discovery and encounters companions and enemies alike along the way amidst growing omens of [[Rebellion of the Three Guards|war]]. Feng Tianling's companions are Huyue (\u745a\u6708), a beautiful maiden from a [[Huli jing|mysterious tribe]] who is attached to Tianling because of a supposedly destined marriage, Ji Ting (\u59ec\u4ead), the Zhou princess skilled in archery who values bravery and prowess, Jialanduo/Kalandra (\u8fe6\u862d\u591a), a [[Tianzhu (India)|Shendu]] royal with [[chakra]] manipulation skills who is searching for his sister, and Rong Shuang (\u84c9\u971c), a young Black Fire Sect disciple from [[Shu (state)|Shu]] on a mission with her fellows to recover their cultural artifact, Black Fire.\n\nThe DLC Chapter of Zhuo Shanzhu (\u6fc1\u5c71\u9444\u7bc7), released as an free update, features a story involving Zhuo Shanzhu (\u6fc1\u5c71\u9444), the elder brother of Rong Shuang previously presumed to be dead, and his investigation of the nature of Black Fire, the Black Fire Sect, and the history and technology of the lost kingdom of Sanmu.\n\n==Tales ([[Gaiden]]) titles==\n\n===Xuan-Yuan Sword: Dance of the Maple Banners===\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u6953\u4e4b\u821e}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword Legend: Dance of Maple\")\n\nThe first standalone expansion episode in the series, the story of ''Dance of the Maple Banners'' (\u6953\u4e4b\u821e) was based on the [[Warring States period]] in [[Chinese History]]. The Sword fell into the hands of the political radical, ''Shusangzi'' (\u8700\u6851\u5b50 or Sang Jing \u6851\u51c8). The main character Fu Ziche (\u8f14\u5b50\u5fb9) is an eccentric young disciple of [[Mozi]], and is also an expert in mechanical engineering, especially in the creation and manipulation of Jiguan Ren (\u6a5f\u95dc\u4eba), man-sized mechanical golems powered by mystic energy. Jiguan Ren were originally developed for war, but their designs were hidden away for fear of being misused. Shusangzi had re-discovered this technology, and developed a large Jiguan army for his own ends. Upon learning of this, [[Mozi]] sent Fu Ziche to investigate, and if possible, to stop Shusangzi. On his quest, he encountered Wenjin (\u7d0b\u9326), the estranged daughter of Sang created with the aid of the power of the Vessel, and they eventually fell in love.\n\nBeing the first game in the series to have connection with real world history, Dance of the Maple Banners inherited most of the previous game's interface, arts, and battle system, with subtle modifications, and wrapped with new plot. More realistic ancient war machines were made alive, while historical figures such as Mozi, [[Lu Ban]], [[Sun Bin]], could be encountered in the game.\n\nAs were the cases with most other standalone tales titles, players do not have the chance to wield the Sword. In this game the Sword is in Shu Sangzi's possession, and is used against players. In the final battle, Shu uses a move called ''Xuan-Yuan Sword Technique'' (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u6cd5), which inflicts serious damage to the player party.\n\nReleased on January 6, 1995.\n\n===Xuan-Yuan Sword 3: The Scar of the Sky===\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u53c3\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u5929\u4e4b\u75d5}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword 3 Legend: The Scar of the Sky\")\nSet in the era of [[Sui Dynasty]], 150 years prior to the events of Xuan-Yuan Sword 3, this game addressed several loose threads in Xuan-Yuan Sword 3.\n\nThe main character is a young man named Chen Jingchou (\u9673\u9756\u4ec7, meaning \"To pacify the northern foes and to avenge Chen.\"), the only royal descendant remaining from the decimated [[Chen Dynasty]]. The final attempt for counterattack from the Chen family happened several years before Chen Jingchou was born, when the tens-of-thousands-strong remnants of Chen forces were single-handedly decimated by a 10-year-old Sui child, Yang Tuo (\u694a\u62d3) (later known as Yuwen Tuo \u5b87\u6587\u62d3), a student of [[Yang Su]].\n\nHaving lived under the reign of those who destroyed his kingdom, Chen Jingchou had been educated by his mentor, Chen Fu (\u9673\u8f14), to pursue a life of vengeance and of reviving his kingdom. The first step of their journey to restore Chen was to acquire the Mirror of Kunlun, one of the Ten Great Ancient Artifacts.<ref>\u300e\u9418\u528d\u65a7\u58fa\u5854\uff0c\u7434\u9f0e\u5370\u93e1\u77f3\u300f, thus ''Bell, Sword, Axe, Vessel, Tower, Zither, Ding, Seal, Mirror, and Stone.''</ref>\n\nThe ancient monstrosity [[Taotie]] was released from a mirror that was revealed to be a fake. In order to protect Jingchou, Fu trapped himself with Taotie using a potent Silk of Ice spell, and instructed Jingchou to embark at once to find a way to save him, as well as finding information concerning other Artifacts. As he set out on his journey, Jingchou summoned an elemental spirit familiar given to him by his master to accompany him on his journeys.\n\nJingchou later was later joined by Yu Xiaoxue (\u4e8e\u5c0f\u96ea), a white haired girl showing unusual healing magic potential, the honorable half [[G\u00f6kt\u00fcrks]]-blooded hero Zhang Lie (\u5f35\u70c8)<ref>Zhang Lie, \u5f35\u70c8, [[G\u00f6kt\u00fcrks]] blooded warlord of the north from the novel ''\u866f\u9aef\u5ba2\u50b3'', by \u675c\u5149\u5ead.</ref> and Zhang's young sister-in-law Tuoba Yu'er (\u62d3\u62d4\u7389\u5152) of the Tuoba tribe, which kept the Shennong Ding for generations and was subject to indiscriminate slaughter by the Sui emperor's troops. During their expedition in collecting the Artifacts, they encountered several Blood Rituals of Ten Thousand Souls, rites conducted by [[Grand Preceptor]] Yuwen Tuo which involved the killing of ten thousand souls to gather their essences into a single Blood Pearl. The party attempted to intervene with the rituals, but Yuwen Tuo proved to be too formidable a foe. Thus they adopted the strategy of subterfuge, hampering his every effort to collect the Blood Pearls without direct confrontations, and was even helped in secret by a young princess named Dugu Ningke (\u7368\u5b64\u5be7\u73c2), who held tremendous political power due to her relation with her uncle, [[Emperor Yang of Sui|the emperor]], and protested Yuwen's actions.\n\nEventually, their plan failed, and Yu Xiaoxue was held as a hostage by Tuo in exchange for the Artifacts that Jingchou's party had collected, namely the [[Shennong]] [[Ding (vessel)|Ding]], the Seal of Kongtong, the [[Pangu]] Axe, the [[N\u00fcwa]] Stone, and the [[Kunlun Mountain (mythology)|Kunlun]] Mirror. Jingchou complied, yet Tuo discarded the Stone and the mirror as fakes, proclaiming that he himself was actually the human avatar of the Kunlun Mirror. Surprisingly, Yu Xiaoxue refused to leave with Jingchou, stating that she intended to stay and help Tuo's project, and seemingly betrays his trust by repelling his attack on Yuwen's plans wielding the Xuan-Yuan Sword. Losing all hope, Jingchou gave up his quest and opted to travel with his similarly disheartened mentor.\n\nNingke, who was actually a demon general dispatched from the western pantheon of Hell, was displeased with this turn of events. She infiltrated China by possessing the original Princess Dugu who died of illness, and arrived in anticipation of what was calculated to be the time a [[Historical comet observations in China#Comets in Chinese astrology|comet]] named Crimson Piercer (Chi Guan - \u8d64\u8cab) would pass through the sky, opening a rift in the divine protective barrier of the Chinese lands and allowing an opportunity for demons from the West to invade. Tuo learned of the implications of the passage of the comet, and set out to collect five of the Artifacts in order to seal the rift the comet would cause in the Barrier of the Ninth [[Tian|Heaven]] in the firmament above [[Names of China#Shenzhou|Shenzhou]]. However, several of the five Artifacts required for the Ritual of Mending were nowhere to be found. Ningke proposed that he substitute these with Blood Pearls along with the construction of a [[Tower of Babel]], and a [[Pentagram]] ritual formation. In order to save the Chinese world, using his power, his riches and his relation with the [[Emperor Yang of Sui China|Emperor Yang]], Tuo managed to accomplish these despite his moral misgivings. In the process, Tuo also discovered that Xiaoxue was actually the avatar of the Stone of N\u00fcwa, as Artifacts resonate with each other when in close proximity. Consequently, he told her of his plan and convinced her to help him, leading to misunderstandings between her and Jingchou.\n\nNingke could not allow the Ritual to be abandoned and manipulated Jingchou through treachery by murdering Yu'er, who learned the truth behind the situation after going to the Grand Preceptor Residence in secret in an attempt to reconcile Xiaoxue and Jingchou, and framing Xiaoxue and Tuo. Fueled by anger and grief, Jingchou's party managed to reach the top of the Tower of Babel, where they were beaten once again by Tuo. Ningke suddenly appeared in the confusion and seized Xiaoxue as hostage to divert Tuo's attention. Jingchou took the opportunity and severed Tuo's arm. Ningke then revealed her true demon form, imprisoning Tuo with magic. Unable to mend the sky, the Chinese world fell under [[Satan]]'s rule of death and destruction.\n\nDays later, under the instruction of the now immortal He Ran and Gu Yuesheng (last seen in Xuan-Yuan Sword 2), Jingchou's group, which now also includes a young [[Li Shimin]] successfully retrieved the Artifacts from Ningke's handmaidens in the bloodied world, and returned to the Tower. They defeated Ningke with her full unrestricted power, and rescued Tuo. Having the Artifacts at hand, Jingchou and company invoked the Ritual of Reversal (which is also named the Ritual of Loss, \u5931\u537b\u4e4b\u9663) at the top of Tower of Babel, which, utilizing the power of Tuo as the avatar the Mirror of Kunlun at the ritual formation's center, reversed time and brought the party back to the moment prior to the passing of Chi Guan.\n\nThe group invoked the Ritual of Trespass (also called the Ritual of Babel), sending them above the sky, and arrived at Chi Guan itself. Coming across the Heavenly Maiden White Jade Ring (\u5929\u5973\u767d\u7389\u8f2a), an eight trigrams formation used by the deities Fuxi and N\u00fcwa to revive their deceased daughter in ancient times, Jingchou had the choice to bring Yu'er back to life at the cost of expending a great deal of Xiaoxue's power. At the heart of the meteor, where the party prepared to cast the Ritual of Sealing, which caused the non-artifact casters to lose their most precious memories or ideals (with Zhang Lie losing his ambition of unifying the lands, Li Shimin losing his love for his family, and Jingchou losing his memories of Yu'er or his master depending on the ending), Ningke, then still alive and ignorant of the recent events Jingchou and his companions experienced, appeared and attempted to continue her deception, but a fight ensued, and Ningke was vanquished. The party decided to grant her final wishes: to be returned to her homeland, and to become free to love whom she loves. Gu stated that was impossible due to her demonic nature, and placed her soul into the Fuxi [[Guqin|Qin]] (\u4f0f\u7fb2\u7434), which Yuwen Tuo brought with him on his self-imposed exile to the west, Ningke's homeland, after the events of the game for her soul to be cleansed eventually.\n\nChen Fu witnessed what appeared to be Jingchou assisting in the machinations of Yuwen Tuo, their sworn enemy. Ningke exploited this before heading to Chi Guan by giving Chen Fu the Fruit of Satan, a demonic object that grants power in exchange for sanity, deceiving him into battling against his student. Chen Fu soon arrived at the heart of Chi Guan with the intent to destroy it. Jingchou's group was left with no choice but to kill Chen Fu to save the world.\n\nSeveral decades later, Ningke was reborn as Nicole, a demon cleansed of evil, while Septem was born to a descendant of Tuo in western lands.\n\nThe Magic System is revamped in this game. All magics now belong to one of the [[five elements (Chinese philosophy)|five elements of metal, wood, water, fire, and earth (\u91d1\u6728\u6c34\u706b\u571f)]] in Chinese mythology.\n\nThe game was released on December 2, 2000.  A [[Xuan-Yuan Sword: Scar of Sky|television series]] based from the game, produced by Chinese Entertainment Shanghai Limited, starring [[Hu Ge]] and [[Cecilia Liu]], aired in 2012.\n\nAn iOS port of the game was released on April 8, 2014.\n\n===Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Millennial Destiny===\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u84bc\u4e4b\u6fe4}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword Legend: Billows of the Bleak\")\nThe game opens with an alternate version of the [[Battle of Fei River]], a battle between [[Former Qin]] and [[Eastern Jin]]. It concludes with Eastern Jin's surrender to Former Qin. Former Qin merged with Eastern Jin and united the entirety of China.\n\nSet within the [[Spring and Autumn period]], the story is told from the perspective of an orphaned girl, Che Yun (\u8eca\u82b8), whose family was framed by a corrupt official and executed. She was spared from execution due to her age, but her legs were amputated as punishment. Che Yun was talented in the art of Mujia - a technique of creating and manipulating constructs of magnets and wooden machinery, which are lightweight yet powerful, with her late grandfather as her inspiration. She fashioned herself wooden prosthetic legs and managed to craft a lifelike and agile wooden fox that can be used in various tasks such as transportation and battle, Yunhu (\u96f2\u72d0), after much effort and coming across rare materials. She was a close friend with Huan Yuanzhi (\u6853\u9060\u4e4b), whom Che Yun saved from drowning and who assisted her in creating Yunhu with exotic components. Che Yun later encountered Ying Shi (\u5b34\u8a69) (who is [[reincarnation]] of Che Yun except that Ying was from a different era and was named Murong Shi - \u6155\u5bb9\u8a69). With Che Yun as a common link, Huan and Ying formed a grudging alliance and adventured together, coming into conflicts with the Jin Kingdom's Tai Chen Gong, a priest organization focused on increasing its power and influence, and Heralds of the Seven Luminaries (\u4e03\u66dc\u4f7f\u8005 \"Qiyao Shizhe\"), a group of powerful rebels from a bleak future timeline sent back with the help of the student of the then-deceased Spirit of the Vessel. At the culmination of the story, Che, Ying and Huan reached the deepest chamber of the Realm of Haotian containing the wheel that determines the destiny of and relationship between all things, Wheel of [[Chinese theology#Taiyi|Taiyi]] (\u592a\u4e00\u4e4b\u8f2a \"Taiyi Zhi Lun\"). However, Murong and Huan were both duty-bound to set history on diverging courses in favor of their homelands. Che intended to stop Huan from changing the future despite Murong having decided against intervening with history by ordering Yunhu to push Huan away. However, Huan wielded the Xuan-Yuan Sword and injured Che fatally by accident while repelling Yunhu. The gate to the Palace then closed abruptly. Murong, unable to extract her friends was transported out of the gate, leaving Huan and Che in the room where Huan, immortal due to the power of his surroundings, mourned in regret for a thousand years. At the instant of Che Yun's death, Murong realized their link and inherited the knowledge of Mujia. She entered the gate when it next opened in a thousand years after she returned to the future in which Jin overcame Qin to fight for the welfare of the common-folk, encountering a sorrowful aged Huan and offering forgiveness and acceptance as Che Yun would have.\n\nReleased on February 6, 2004.\n\nOn December 3, 2015, an animated series based on the game called ''[[Xuan Yuan Sword Luminary]]'' (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\uff1a\u84bc\u4e4b\u66dc / Ken En Ken: Aoki Kagayaki, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword: Lights of the Bleak\") was announced as a collaborative project with [[TV Tokyo]] and [[Studio Deen]] and began airing on October 2, 2018 in Mainland China, Taiwan, as well as Japan.\n\n===Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Han Clouds===\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u6f22\u4e4b\u96f2}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword Legend: The Clouds of Han\")\nReleased on December 19, 2007.\n\nThe game is set in the era of the [[Three Kingdoms]], [[Wei (state)|Wei]], [[Shu Han|Shu]] and [[Wu (state)|Wu]] and feature famous historic figures. [[Zhuge Liang]], the chancellor of the kingdom of Shu had engaged on [[Zhuge Liang's Northern Expeditions|multiple northward military expeditions]] with little success. On Zhuge Liang's Third Expedition, a secret military group called \"Fei Yu\" (\u98db\u7fbd)(meaning Flying Feather, deriving its name from the two famous generals of Shu kingdom - [[Zhang Fei]] and [[Guan Yu]])carried out various missions in the war to further the interests of Shu. However, on the Fourth Expedition, Thanks to its own group of powerful secret operatives, Wei was able to discover and exploit critical weaknesses of Shu, prompting The Feathers to take action. The game addresses issues of loyalty and duty, as well as the harsh realities of warfare and peace.\n\n[[Xuan-Yuan Sword: Han Cloud|A live-action television series based on the game]] has been released.\n\n===Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Clouds Faraway===\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u96f2\u4e4b\u9059}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword Legend: The Clouds Faraway\")\nReleased on January 12, 2010.\n\nThe Clouds Faraway, also set in the era of the [[Three Kingdoms]], is presented with a contrasting viewpoint to the Han Clouds. The main character, Xu Muyun (\u5f90\u66ae\u96f2), was adopted by [[Xu Shu]] and raised in the Kingdom of [[Cao Wei|Wei]]. Muyun grew up with his childhood friends Lanyin (\u862d\u8335) and Zhang Gao (\u5f35\u8aa5) in the house of [[Zhang He]], and the three youngsters vowed to fight for their homeland and bring about prosperous days together. Through his journey, Muyun came to a new level of maturity, learned of his true identity, realized the meaning of duty and friendship, and witnessed the ruthlessness of war.\n\nThe story is continued after the main game in three DLC chapters, released to enrich the story. These three chapters are: The Chapter of [[Wuzhang Plains]]: Muyun ({{zh|c=\u4e94\u4e08\u539f\u66ae\u96f2\u7bc7}}), The Chapter of Wuzhang Plains: Zhaoyun ({{zh|c=\u4e94\u4e08\u539f\u671d\u96f2\u7bc7}}), and the lengthy and critically acclaimed Chapter of Lan Yin ({{zh|c=\u862d\u8335\u7bc7}}).\n\n===Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Gate of Firmament===\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u7a79\u4e4b\u6249}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword Legend: The Gate of the Heavens\")\nReleased on March 26, 2015.\n\nIn ancient times, the Heavenly Emperor opened the Gate of Firmament, connecting the Heavens and Earth. Mortals could ascend to the Gate to obtain divine power in order to assist in the search for the Emperor's missing daughter. Unscrupulous individuals took advantage of the Emperor's gesture, and caused the mortal world to descend into chaos. The lives of the common folk were filled with anxiety and weariness. The god [[Fuxi]] and the goddess [[N\u00fcwa]] took pity on the people, and along with [[Zhuanxu]], convinced the Queen of Huaxu (\u83ef\u80e5\u4e4b\u4e3b, based on Lady Huaxu \u83ef\u80e5\u6c0f) to close the Gate forcibly with great sacrifice. After this, no one could reach the Heavens through the Gate, and no god could go to the mortal world; thus came about the Isolation of the Heavens and Earth (Jueditiantong \u7d55\u5730\u5929\u901a). Time passed, and the mortal realm suffered due to disasters and endless conflicts over [[Mandate of Heaven|claims to rule]], embroiled in political instability and riotous events. At this time of unrest and warfare, a Heavenly entity descends, adding to the unsolved mysteries of the troubled world.\n\nThe story revolves the journeys and adventures of Sikong Yu (\u53f8\u7a7a\u5b87), a young man whose goal is to protect his nomadic Youxiong village (\u6709\u718a\u6751), which consists of descendants of the Yellow Emperor, Muyue (\u6c90\u6708), a mysterious woman claiming to be from the legendary Kingdom of Huaxu (\u83ef\u80e5) whose distant behavior makes her seem unapproachable, [[Wu Ding|Feng Yu]] (\u9cf3\u715c), a jovial and cunning traveler with ties to royal House of Shang, and [[Fu Hao|Zi Qiao]] (\u5b50\u5de7), a royal high priestess of the Zi Kingdom who is betrothed to the Shang prince and possesses tremendous strength as well as an insatiable appetite. Together, they fight to bring the nefarious plots of a mysterious group of conspirators consisting of the followers of [[Gong Gong]] (\u5171\u5de5), the water god who had been sealed away for his violent actions, led by his second-in-command [[Xiangliu|Xiang Liu]] (\u76f8\u67f3), as well as Qing Yu (\u9752\u6986), the avatar of the [[World Tree]] Jian Mu (\u5efa\u6728) who has been driven by hatred for humans and vengeance against those of the Xuan-Yuan bloodline as well as his former lover Lan Ling (\u85cd\u9234), to an end before ruin befalls the world.\n\nThree free DLC packs have been released as game patches, including the Chapter of the All-encompassing (\u842c\u8c61\u4e4b\u7bc7), the Chapter of Gods and Demons/Chapter of Saviors (\u795e\u9b54\u4e4b\u7bc7), and the Chapter of the Watchful Vigil (\u5b88\u671b\u4e4b\u7bc7), which add side quests, stories, and hidden endings to the game.\n\nOn September 10, 2015 a multi-language version of the game was placed on [[Steam Greenlight]], the game has since been Greenlit and has been released in English, Japanese, simplified Chinese and traditional Chinese. It is the first core title (main and tales) in the series to see an English release.<ref>http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/updates/515663220/1444192239</ref> A [[PlayStation 4]] port as well as a Xbox One version of the game have been released.\n\n==Spin-off titles==\n\n===Xuan-Yuan Demonbane Chronicles===\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u4f0f\u9b54\u9304}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Records of Subduing Demons\")\nReleased on February 10, 2001.\n\nThe humble sword-wielding Mo clan hero defeats demons to bring peace to the world. The Monster Fusion Vessel is an ancient artifact that can seal away monsters.\n\nThe Mo clan is a group of powerful and righteous vigilantes, protecting the Monster Fusion Vessel for generations. The story begins with a resounding wave of panic, with a catastrophe witnessed by the young hero Fu Zixun. With his clan destroyed, the Vessel lost, the common folk imperiled, and his benefactor murdered, the young man never expected a trip down the mountain to turn into a grueling journey to defeat demons. Facing deaths and the seeking vengeance, his youth and naivet\u00e9 are buried only to be replaced by a heavy long sword and revenge weighing upon him. Together with the daughter of his benefactor, he begins his journey with uncertainty. Fortunately, the journey did not prove lonesome and he encountered a pampered daughter of a wealthy family who joined with bandits, a famous transport guard leader, a thief titled Flying on Grass, a legendary swordsman, a fox spirit from a mystic valley, and a simple boy leaving his House consisting of only himself. These people bear resentment, pain, anger, and hatred, yet gather under the common idea of righteousness to travel the world. The future holds many uncertainties, and their opponents have cunning schemes. The group does not even know where their path will end, so can only forge their way ahead little by little, encountering monsters causing disturbances as well as evil government officials mistreating commoners. \u201cJust what kind of world is this?\u201d The group can only ponder in disapproval, yet they share a belief that drives them forward-a belief in a beautiful future. Even though monsters threaten the world and heroes rise in response, but the outcome is still unknown. They can only rely on their companies\u2019 warmth to trudge through hardships together. All, with the appearance of the ancient weapon Xuan-Yuan Sword, shall eventually become clear.\n\nThis is an experimental strategy RPG utilizing 3D environments with 2D character sprites set in an alternate continuity to the core Xuan-Yuan Sword games, but still contains a few elements related to Xuan-Yuan Sword 3. The protagonist Fu Zixun (\u8f14\u5b50\u6d35) is a young man who goes on a journey after of his clan's destruction and the Monster Fusion Vessel's theft caused by Jiutian (\u4e5d\u5929), the malevolent entity the protagonist's younger clan sister Zhu Yuanyuan (\u6731\u5a9b\u6c85) accidentally unleashed. On his journey, he encounters allies including Ding Yun (\u4e01\u82b8), the kind and trusting daughter of a renowned doctor, Jiang Wushuang (\u6c5f\u7121\u96d9), a bossy young girl who ran away from home and leads a group of bandits she defeated, Zuo Zhenhe (\u5de6\u9707\u6cb3), a respected and mighty guard leader for transporting goods, Qiu Qianli (\u88d8\u5343\u91cc), a skilled but kind-hearted thief, Leng Zhongqiu (\u51b7\u4ef2\u79cb), a stoic hero with a dark past, Qise (\u4e03\u8272), a fox spirit with a feminine human form who is the elder sister to Jiutian, and Liang Cuo (\u6881\u932f), a slightly bumbling young man from a secretive family known for skills in engineering and the occult.\n\n==List of titles==\n{{More citations needed|list|date=May 2013}}\n*Main Series:\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d) (1990)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword 2 (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u8cb3) (1994)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword 3: Beyond the Clouds and Mountains (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u53c3\uff1a\u96f2\u548c\u5c71\u7684\u5f7c\u7aef) (1999)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword 4: The Black Dragon Dances as the Storm Rages (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u8086\uff1a\u9ed1\u9f8d\u821e\u516e\u96f2\u98db\u63da) (2002)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword 5: A Sword Above the Clouds and the Sentiments of the World of Shanhai (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u4f0d\uff1a\u4e00\u528d\u51cc\u96f2\u5c71\u6d77\u60c5) (2006)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword 6: The Phoenix Soars Above the Sky among the Millennial Clouds (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u9678\uff1a\u9cf3\u51cc\u9577\u7a7a\u5343\u8f09\u96f2) (2013)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://activity.softstar.com.tw/SWDOL/1010720/index.html|script-title=zh:\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u7cfb\u5217\u5b98\u65b9\u7db2\u7ad9|date=2012-08-09|accessdate=2012-08-10|language=zh }}</ref>\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword 7 (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u67d2) (TBA)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gnn.gamer.com.tw/6/152056.html|script-title=zh:\u300a\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u300b\u7cfb\u5217\u7e8c\u4f5c\u300a\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u67d2\u300b\u66dd\u5149 \u516c\u958b\u6545\u4e8b\u80cc\u666f\u6642\u4ee3\u8a2d\u5b9a\u8207 LOGO \u5f62\u8c61|date=2017-09-05|accessdate=2017-09-05|language=zh }}</ref>\n*Waizhuan (Tales) titles:\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword: Dance of the Maple Banners (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u6953\u4e4b\u821e) (1995)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword 3: The Scar of the Sky (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u53c3\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u5929\u4e4b\u75d5) (2001)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Millennial Destiny (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u84bc\u4e4b\u6fe4) (2004)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Han Clouds (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u6f22\u4e4b\u96f2) (2007)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Clouds Faraway (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u96f2\u4e4b\u9059) (2010)  \n**Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Gate of Firmament (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u7a79\u4e4b\u6249) (2015)\n*Spin-off titles:\n**Xuan-Yuan Demonbane Chronicles/Xuanyuan Fu Mo Lu (\u8ed2\u8f45\u4f0f\u9b54\u9304) (2001)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword Online: Chain of Life (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u7db2\u8def\u7248) (2002)\n**[[Dream of Mirror Online]]/Flying Adventure: Xuan-Yuan Sword Online 2 (\u98db\u5929\u6b77\u96aa\uff1a\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u7db2\u8def\u7248\u4e8c\u4ee3) (2005)\n**The Scar of the Sky Online (\u5929\u4e4b\u75d5 OL) (2010)\n**Flying PuPu (\u98db\u5929\u5657\u5657) (2011)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword Waizhuan Online (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3 Online) (2012)\n**Battle Legends (\u4f0f\u9b54\u50b3\u5947) (2012)\n**Mirror of Sanctity (\u5d11\u5d19\u93e1) (2012)\n**Xuan-Yuan Legends of Gods and Demons/Xuanyuan Shen Mo Zhuan (\u8ed2\u8f45\u795e\u9b54\u50b3) (2013)\n**Spell Card Xuan-Yuan (\u7b26\u5361\u8ed2\u8f45) (2014)\n**Vochord: Xuan-Yuan Sword Rhythm Game (Vochord \u8f69\u8f95\u5929\u7c41) (2017)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Dragon Dances Among Clouds and Mountains (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u9f8d\u821e\u96f2\u5c71) (TBA)\n**Chronicles of Xuan-Yuan Heroes (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u7fa4\u4fe0\u9304) (TBA)\n*Spin-off media:\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Scar of the Sky (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u4e4b\u5929\u4e4b\u75d5)(2012) - A two-volume novel written by Yan Leisheng (\u71d5\u58d8\u751f) based on Xuan-Yuan Sword 3: The Scar of the Sky.\n**The Music of Xuan-Yuan Sword (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u6b77\u4ee3\u97f3\u6a02\u96c6\uff1a\u528d\u8a60\u8ed2\u8f45) (2014) - A collection of music from the series.\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword: Billows of the Bleak (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u84bc\u4e4b\u6fe4) (2016) - A novel adaptation of the game of the same name.\n**[[Xuan Yuan Sword Luminary]] (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\uff1a\u84bc\u4e4b\u66dc) (2018) - An animated television series based on Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Millennial Destiny.\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Xuan-Yuan Sword: Scar of Sky]]''\n* ''[[The Legend of Sword and Fairy]]''\n\n==Notes and references==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080222141842/http://swd.joypark.com.tw/ Official Xuanyuan Sword website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120901015058/http://www.ancientchinese.net/blog/watch-online-xuan-yuan-sword-scar-sky/ Xuan Yuan Sword TV Series Fanpage]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110614224426/http://www.softstar.com.tw/ Softstar's website] {{in lang|zh}}\n*[http://www.mobygames.com/game-group/xuanyuan-jian-series Xuanyuan Sword series] at [[MobyGames]]\n\n[[Category:Action role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language-only video games]]\n[[Category:Role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Xuanyuan Jian]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Imperial China]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 1990]]\n[[Category:Video games adapted into television programs]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Series of Chinese role-playing video games}}\n{{italic title}}\n'''''Xuan-Yuan Sword''''' ({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d}}, literally \"Sword of the [[Yellow Emperor|Xuan-Yuan]]\")<ref>The official translation about \"\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\" is \"Xuan-Yuan Sword\", instead of \"Xuan-Yuan Jian\". Reference:[http://swd1017.myweb.hinet.net/windheart/news/70/paper62.htm \u6953\u821e\u8ed2\u8f45\u96fb\u5b50\u5831\u7b2c\u516d\u5341\u4e8c\u671f\uff1a\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u7684\u82f1\u6587\u540d\u5b57(The E-Paper of the Maple Dance with Xuan-Yuan Sword, 62nd: The English Name of Xuan-Yuan Sword)]</ref> refers to a series of Taiwanese [[role-playing video game]]s for [[personal computers]] developed by the DOMO Studio (DOMO\u5c0f\u7d44/\u591a\u9b54\u5c0f\u7d44) of [[Softstar Entertainment Inc.]] (\u5927\u5b87\u8cc7\u8a0a) based in [[Taiwan]]. The games incorporate elements of [[Chinese mythology]] as well as historic figures and events.\n\nIn time immemorial, the \"Xuan-Yuan Sword\" was wielded by [[Yellow Emperor]] of ancient China to defend the ancient Chinese against the warlord [[Chi You]] and his aggressive subjects. After Chi You's defeat, the future for the five-thousand-year-old history of China was secured, and the Sword was passed on from Yellow Emperor to future generations to continue to defend the world against evil. Due to its great power, the sword was often sought by treacherous individuals to further their own ends.\n\nA recurring item of the series is the ''Monster Fusion Vessel'' (''Lian Yao Hu'', \u7149\u5996\u58fa), created by the goddess [[N\u00fcwa]] in emulation of the Immortal Creation Ding (\u9020\u7269\u4ed9\u9f0e) to cleanse the world. Within the Vessel resides an immortal entity known as the ''Spirit in the Vessel.'' The Vessel's powers are to absorb nonhuman creatures, and to transmute them into other creatures or items.\n\n== Main series ==\n\n{{VG timeline\n| 1990 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword''\n| 1994 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword 2''\n| 1995 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword: Dance of Maple Banners''\n| 1999 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword 3''\n| 2000 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword 3: The Scar of the Sky''\n| 2002 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword 4''\n| 2004 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Millennial Destiny''\n| 2006 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword 5''\n| 2007 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Han Clouds''\n| 2010 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Clouds Faraway''\n| 2013 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword 6''\n| 2015 = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Gate of Firmament''\n| TBA = ''Xuan-Yuan Sword 7''\n}}\n\nThe Xuan-Yuan Sword series is the oldest and longest living Chinese RPG series, totaling 13 RPGs with ancient Chinese-style stories set in ancient Chinese backgrounds. They are:\n* 01 Xuan-Yuan Sword\n* 02 Xuan-Yuan Sword II\n* 03 Xuan-Yuan Sword: Dance of Maple Banners\n* 04 Xuan-Yuan Sword III: Beyond Clouds and Mountains (The story happened around the time of the [[An Lushan Rebellion]]. The protagonist started from Venice, Italy, and crossed the entire Eurasian continent to reach [[Chang'an]], the Capital of the [[Tang Dynasty]] of China)\n* 05 Xuan-Yuan Sword III: Scar of the Sky (The story happened in late [[Sui dynasty|Sui Dynasty]])\n* 06 Xuan-Yuan Sword IV: The Black Dragon Dances as Storm Rages (The story Happened in late [[Qin Dynasty]])\n* 07 Xuan-Yuan Sword IV: The Millennial Destiny (Part of the story happened in the [[Spring and Autumn period]] of China, in the 6th Century BC, and the other part 1000 years later, during the [[Battle of Fei River]], during the [[East Jin Dynasty]])\n* 08 Xuan-Yuan Sword V: A Sword above the Clouds and the Sentiment of [[Shanhai Jing|Shanhai]] (The story happened in an alternate world called the world of Shanhai, or literally the world of the [[Classic of Mountains and Seas]]. The time is equivalent to late [[Three Kingdoms]] period in our world)\n* 09 Xuan-Yuan Sword V: The Clouds of Han (The story happened in the period of Three Kingdoms of China)\n* 10 Xuan-Yuan Sword V: The Clouds Faraway (The game consists of 3 chapters: the main chapter, the chapter of Lan Ying, and the chapter of [[Wuzhang Plains]]. The story happened in the period of Three Kingdoms.)\n* 11 Xuan-Yuan Sword VI: The Phoenix Soars over Millennial Clouds (The story happened in the [[Zhou dynasty|West Zhou dynasty]])\n* 12 Xuan-Yuan Sword VI: The Gate of Firmament (The story happened in the [[Shang dynasty|Shang Dynasty]])\n* 13 Xuan-Yuan Sword VII (The story happened in late [[Han dynasty|West Han Dynasty]])\n\n=== Xuan-Yuan Sword ===\n\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword\")\n\nIn the beginning of the world, the goddess [[N\u00fcwa]] created two kinds of intelligent life: those of men, and those of monsters, who warred among each other all the time. The Sword was created by men in an attempt to end the everlasting war. Led by a single heroic figure, Xuan-yuan Swordsman (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u4fe0) who wielded the Sword, the war between humans and monsters ended with both sides suffering heavy casualties. Seventeen years later, the main character, He Ran (\u4f55\u7136), a young swordsman left his mentor to set off on a journey into the chaotic world to carve his own path.\n\nThe first game in the series, Xuan-Yuan Sword was also Softstar's first RPG product and was released in 1990. The time period the game is set in is ambiguous. The game features a [[Dragon Quest]]-like user interface. Players started the game as a novice adventurer with minimal fighting skills and can gain combat experience through battles to enable progression to other areas and advance the plot. The main characters were named after the characters from [[A Chinese Ghost Story]] in this game, but their names were retconned in the second game.\n\nThe game featured standard VGA 16-colored 640x480 screen, complete with party-members, round-based combat, full-screen sprite animation, various monsters, Chinese-styled AdLb music, sound effects, animated spell effects, as well as full Chinese interface, which was a great hit in Taiwan's computer game market at that period.\n\nReleased on October 13, 1990.\n\n=== Xuan-Yuan Sword 2 ===\n\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u8cb3}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword 2\")\n\nContinuing from where the first game left off, He Ran (\u4f55\u7136), together with the vigilante Yang Kunshuo (\u694a\u5764\u78a9) and the young thaumaturge Jiang Ruhong (\u6c5f\u5982\u7d05), defeated the dreaded incarnation of the Flaming Phoenix (\u706b\u9cf3\u51f0) (the sinister monster who kidnapped Jiang), befriended a benevolent fox spirit Gu Yuesheng (\u53e4\u6708\u8056), and traveled back in time to find He Ran's parents. They sought to bring about the end of the leader of the invasive monsters, known as the Wicked God (\u60e1\u795e), [[Bashe]], and eventually confronted the treacherous Spirit of the Vessel.\n\nReleased on February 8, 1994.\n\n; Features\n: Many key features of the game series were introduced with this game. It was set in 320\u00d7240 256-colored screen (in the once-popular VGA X-mode). In-game artworks such as scenes, monsters, character portraits, items were fashioned in [[Chinese painting]] style.\n\n; Monster Fusion Vessel\n: Another key feature is the Vessel system. Not long after the beginning of the game, the Monster Fusion Vessel can be acquired, and has two main functions:\n# Absorb enemies encountered in battle, with limitations:\n#* Cannot absorb creatures that have higher experience level than player, and those creatures whose levels are close to the players' are more easily captured when wounded.\n#* Bosses creatures and human enemies cannot be absorbed.\n#* Imprisoned monsters are visible in players inventory and can be summoned to assist during battle with a stamina cost.\n# Transmutation. A player can transmute creatures and items to other objects or creatures. The resulting product may be exceedingly powerful or unobtainable otherwise.\n\n; The Sword\n: In the battle against the final boss, the Vessel Spirit, the goddess N\u00fcwa appeared and revealed the truth that Xuan-Yuan Swordsman was He Ran's father whose spirit has fused with the Xuan-Yuan Sword. Receiving the powerful weapon from the goddess, the protagonist and his company went to the World Within the Vessel and defeated the treacherous Vessel Spirit, sealing him by planting the Xuan-Yuan Sword in his head.\n\nThis installment also introduced a recurring element of the series, the DOMO Studio that is present in all future games in vastly different incarnations that players can visit to access humorous fourth wall-breaking dialogue, quests, and items.\n\n=== Xuan-Yuan Sword 3: Beyond the Clouds and Mountains ===\n\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u53c3\uff1a\u96f2\u548c\u5c71\u7684\u5f7c\u7aef}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword 3: Beyond Clouds and Mountains\")\n\nThe story opens in [[Venice]] with Septem (\u8cfd\u7279), a Frankish knight and covert intelligence operative of mixed descent from [[Gaul]] who was the lieutenant to [[Pepin the Younger]]. Septem possessed an heirloom bronze vessel with an eastern design, which was in fact the Monster Fusion Vessel. He had heterochromic pupils of blue and brown, garnering discrimination and distrust from his peers and fellow knights over his somewhat Eastern appearance. Miles (\u9ea5\u723e\u65af) (the reincarnation of Satan whose memories and innate powers had not yet been fully awakened), a knight-commander under the guidance of the cleric Cornelius (\u5eb7\u90a3\u91cc\u58eb) (the Dread Lord of Hell in disguise), was the polar opposite of his rival Septem, enforcing the Church's will without mercy and question, executing those designated as heretics without hesitation, and had the affection of Lilian (\u8389\u84ee), a pure maiden Septem had courted in vain. Pepin himself, however, favored Septem, and gave him a quest of great import. He was to go to the East, and find the way to achieve Absolute Victory/the Way of the King. During the journey, a simpleminded demoness named Nicole (\u59ae\u53ef) joined Septem after being summoned by a strange dying man Septem tried to help, as an agent sent by [[Satan]]. Her mission was to awaken Septem's memory of his past life, in which he was Lucifer's most trusted ally who took part in Lucifer's Rebellion, and to convert him to Satan's cause once more, accompanied with promises of wealth, power, and demonic servants, but she eventually abandoned her mission over the fondness she developed for Septem. Kama, a self-proclaimed spirit of love, and Ankh, a snarky talking flying Egyptian black cat accompanying Kama (both of whom Septem encountered in the [[Palmyra#Site|Tadmor Tombs]]), as well as [[Li Jing (Tang dynasty)|Li Jing]] (\u674e\u9756), a Chinese mortal-turned-deity who oversaw the establishment of the Tang dynasty, whose reincarnated self, Master Huiyan, previously accompanied Septem for a short time before sacrificing himself in an attempt to stop a [[Battle of Talas|war between the Abbasid Caliphate (which recently overthrew Umayyad rule) and Tang]] (which ended in the defeat of the Tang forces led by [[Gao Xianzhi]]), also joined the party. Septem also met his eventual wife, Widad (\u8587\u9054), a military leader who defied Arabian patriarchal traditions and who was the reincarnated spirit twin of Kama, and the young grandson of [[Al-Kindi]], whom Septem studied under for a short time around the time of the [[Abbasid Revolution]], as well as Wang Siyue (\u738b\u601d\u6708), a willful young woman from [[Chang'an]] with feelings for Septem, along his journey. After finally reaching China and encountering a variety of conflicts, including the [[An Lushan Rebellion]], the group discovered Satan's plan to subjugate all worlds by using the Reversal of [[Mandala]] Ritual (\u53cd\u66fc\u9640\u7f85\u9663), which Septem's past incarnation invented and gained time traversal powers from, to modify the natural laws of causality, and managed to foil it with the assistance of The Immortal of Xuan-yuan Sword (the avatar of the Xuan-Yuan Sword who takes on the form of a stern and wise old man). After Satan's defeat, Septem married Widad, returned to assist [[Charlemagne]] with lessons from his journey-that a ruler must rule in the best interests of the commonfolk, and the way to ensure victory lies in the prevention and cessation of conflicts, and later reunited with Nicole, who was reborn once more as a normal girl by the grace of Heaven.\n\nThe game eschews turn-based battles for the [[Active Time Battle]] combat system, an unusual feature in Chinese RPGs. The refining system in the game has two categories of items and creatures, Eastern and Western, which allows for the creation of different items based on altar selection.\n\nThe game was released on December 4, 1999. An iOS port of the game with additional storylines and scenes meant to expand the portion of the game set in China was released on January 17, 2017.\n\n=== Xuan-Yuan Sword 4: The Black Dragon Dances as the Storm Rages ===\n\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u8086\uff1a\u9ed1\u9f8d\u821e\u516e\u96f2\u98db\u63da}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword 4: The Black Dragon Dances! The Clouds Fly)\n\nThis game is the fourth installment of the main series. The game is the first to be presented in 3D, both in environment and in combat.\nThe story starts with an orphaned girl from the late [[Zhao (state)|Zhao state]], Shui Jing (\u6c34\u93e1) and her senior disciple-sister, Qu Xian (\u5c48\u5afb) on the top of a mountain with their seniors from the House of [[Mohism|Mo]], a Mohist clan actively opposing the tyranny of [[Qin dynasty|Qin]] and [[King Zheng of Qin|its leader]], who is often accompanied by a mysterious purple-skinned adviser (later revealed to be the original Vessel Spirit on an ideological mission to create an unified utopia by absorbing the mortal world into the universe created by the Spirit - \"Realm in the Clouds\"). Qu Xian witnessed her companions being murdered by giant mechanical constructs created with the Jiguan technique. Later, Shui Jing meets with Ji Liang (\u59ec\u826f) (later known as [[Zhang Liang (Western Han)|Zhang Liang]] \u5f35\u826f), a well-educated young man from the annihilated [[Han (state)|Han state]] who can utilize the Scroll of Heaven (Tian Shu \u5929\u66f8) in battles after obtaining and deciphering it in an early escapade with Shui Jing, and Ji Peng (\u75be\u9d6c), a humorous talking bird king who employs a humanoid Jiguan body in battle. The three journey across various lands to combat the machinations of the Qin Empire and the Vessel Spirit. Later in the story, Ji Peng is revealed to be the bird owned by the Mo clan leader's husband, Fu Ziche (\u8f14\u5b50\u5fb9) (introduced in Dance of Maple along with the current Mo leader, Lady Wenjin (\u7d0b\u9326), renowned for her eternal youthfulness), who had been sealed in ice in the World Within the Vessel after a battle with the Vessel Spirit during which he averted disaster by preventing the Black Fire the Vessel Spirit unleashed using a purple crystal in desperation from taking form. The trio eventually reconcile their differences with the Spirit, rescued Fu Ziche, and confronted the true threat, battling with all nine portions of Black Fire (with each portion increasing its power and all nine portions 4^128 times as powerful as one portion alone) running amok, which is believed to be the ultimate weapon of the Hell that can take the form of a black dragon, discovered long ago using purple crystals by the ancient Shu kingdom engineer Qi, who caused the destruction of his civilization and was sealed away in a protective cocoon until the events of the game, when he took control of Lady Wenjin (who was created with Black Fire) and Black Fire to go on a rampage to destroy the world (or in his mind, creating a world where hell and the mortal realm co-existed in order to eliminate death) upon awakening.\n\nReleased on the August 4, 2002.\n\n=== Xuan-Yuan Sword 5: A Sword Above the Clouds and the Sentiments of the World of Shanhai ===\n\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u4f0d\uff1a\u4e00\u528d\u51cc\u96f2\u5c71\u6d77\u60c5}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword 5: A Sword Soaring Above Clouds; Shanhai Sentiments\")\n\nThe main character Lu Chengxuan (\u9678\u627f\u8ed2) killed his parents as a result of not being able control his mysterious power, and was about to die in the wilderness as an outcast when he was coincidentally brought to the World of [[Classic of Mountains and Seas|Shanhai]] through a portal created by Huangfu Muyun (\u7687\u752b\u66ae\u96f2), a powerful wielder of sword energy and the avatar of the Xuanyuan Sword, using the Pangu Axe. There, he encounters Xia Rou (\u590f\u67d4), second empress of the Kingdom of Women. The two traveled around the world, meeting with people from other kingdoms, and set out to accomplish a task given to them by the Elder of the Green Dragon Kingdom, leading to a confrontation with the exiled Princess of Heaven, [[N\u00fcba|Qing'er (\u9752\u5152)]], who helped the [[Yellow Emperor]], Ji Xuanyuan (\u59ec\u8ed2\u8f45), claim the mortal world for humans and was banished due to her newly acquired form causing cataclysmic droughts after expending her power in aiding him in reforging the sword that would later be known as the Xuan Yuan Sword.\n\nReleased on August 4, 2006.\n\n=== Xuan-Yuan Sword 6: The Phoenix Soars in the Sky among Millennial Clouds ===\n\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u9678\uff1a\u9cf3\u51cc\u9577\u7a7a\u5343\u8f09\u96f2}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword 6: The Fenghuang Rising High Above the Sky and Thousand-year Clouds\")\n\nIn c. 1046 BCE, the [[Battle of Muye]] erupted. The leader of the Zhou of the west, [[Ji Fa]], took the opportunity presented when [[King Zhou of Shang]] rallied his forces in a southeastern expedition and when the Shang capital of [[Zhaoge]] was undefended to form an alliance with leaders in the west at [[Mengjin]] to perform a swift strike against the capital.\n\nHearing of the impending attack, the Shang king was caught off guard and forced to head to Muye for battle, and ended up burning himself alive on the [[Deer Terrace Pavilion]], thus ending the six-hundred-year reign of the [[Shang Dynasty]] and ushering in the era of the [[Zhou Dynasty]].\n\nAfter the Battle of Muye, the tense atmosphere remained between the Shang and Zhou people. The Shang remnant forces retreated to the largest vassal state in the east, [[Qufu|Yan (\u5944\u570b)]], for a respite until a chance for rebellion arose. King Zhou\u2019s son, [[Wu Geng]], was held at Zhaoge.  King Wu of Zhou (formerly known as Ji Fa) assigned land and title to him, but ordered his three younger brothers to keep Wu Geng confined and under surveillance to prevent rebellion. With the passing of King Wu from illness, the [[Duke of Zhou]] who served as a royal advisor was accused of attempting to seize the throne, and had to resign to prove his innocence, causing the kingdom to be leaderless and the political situation to become volatile. The Shang sought to seize this chance to attack [[Haojing]] to reclaim the kingdom. A war between the east and west appears to be imminent, and at the same time, a mysterious force stirs in the dark.\n\nThe game opens with a cinematic of a battle between [[Xia dynasty|Xia]] and Shang forces at the Xia capital [[Zhenxun]] that concludes with the end of the Xia Dynasty and the deaths of two Xia lovers, the warrior Si Tianjia (\u59d2\u5929\u7532) and the priestess Miao Ji (\u82d7\u59ec). The two promise each other to transmigrate as enemies of Shang to oppose it together in their next lives. As they lay dying, a Xia artifact, the Holy Circlet of Tianhuan carried by Miao Ji splits into two halves and merges with Si Tianjia and Miao Ji.\n\nThe story focuses on the conflict among the reigning Zhou and the subordinate Shang states. The main character, Feng Tianling (\u9cf3\u5929\u51cc), is a proud young Shang noble raised in Yan who can see and communicate with spirits and supernatural creatures. A benevolent spirit, Hupo (\u7425\u73c0 Amber), has been his friend and companion since he was young. He sets out on a journey of self-discovery and encounters companions and enemies alike along the way amidst growing omens of [[Rebellion of the Three Guards|war]]. Feng Tianling's companions are Huyue (\u745a\u6708), a beautiful maiden from a [[Huli jing|mysterious tribe]] who is attached to Tianling because of a supposedly destined marriage, Ji Ting (\u59ec\u4ead), the Zhou princess skilled in archery who values bravery and prowess, Jialanduo/Kalandra (\u8fe6\u862d\u591a), a [[Tianzhu (India)|Shendu]] royal with [[chakra]] manipulation skills who is searching for his sister, and Rong Shuang (\u84c9\u971c), a young Black Fire Sect disciple from [[Shu (state)|Shu]] on a mission with her fellows to recover their cultural artifact, Black Fire.\n\nThe DLC Chapter of Zhuo Shanzhu (\u6fc1\u5c71\u9444\u7bc7), released as an free update, features a story involving Zhuo Shanzhu (\u6fc1\u5c71\u9444), the elder brother of Rong Shuang previously presumed to be dead, and his investigation of the nature of Black Fire, the Black Fire Sect, and the history and technology of the lost kingdom of Sanmu.\n\n==Tales ([[Gaiden]]) titles==\n\n===Xuan-Yuan Sword: Dance of the Maple Banners===\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u6953\u4e4b\u821e}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword Legend: Dance of Maple\")\n\nThe first standalone expansion episode in the series, the story of ''Dance of the Maple Banners'' (\u6953\u4e4b\u821e) was based on the [[Warring States period]] in [[Chinese History]]. The Sword fell into the hands of the political radical, ''Shusangzi'' (\u8700\u6851\u5b50 or Sang Jing \u6851\u51c8). The main character Fu Ziche (\u8f14\u5b50\u5fb9) is an eccentric young disciple of [[Mozi]], and is also an expert in mechanical engineering, especially in the creation and manipulation of Jiguan Ren (\u6a5f\u95dc\u4eba), man-sized mechanical golems powered by mystic energy. Jiguan Ren were originally developed for war, but their designs were hidden away for fear of being misused. Shusangzi had re-discovered this technology, and developed a large Jiguan army for his own ends. Upon learning of this, [[Mozi]] sent Fu Ziche to investigate, and if possible, to stop Shusangzi. On his quest, he encountered Wenjin (\u7d0b\u9326), the estranged daughter of Sang created with the aid of the power of the Vessel, and they eventually fell in love.\n\nBeing the first game in the series to have connection with real world history, Dance of the Maple Banners inherited most of the previous game's interface, arts, and battle system, with subtle modifications, and wrapped with new plot. More realistic ancient war machines were made alive, while historical figures such as Mozi, [[Lu Ban]], [[Sun Bin]], could be encountered in the game.\n\nAs were the cases with most other standalone tales titles, players do not have the chance to wield the Sword. In this game the Sword is in Shu Sangzi's possession, and is used against players. In the final battle, Shu uses a move called ''Xuan-Yuan Sword Technique'' (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u6cd5), which inflicts serious damage to the player party.\n\nReleased on January 6, 1995.\n\n===Xuan-Yuan Sword 3: The Scar of the Sky===\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u53c3\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u5929\u4e4b\u75d5}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword 3 Legend: The Scar of the Sky\")\nSet in the era of [[Sui Dynasty]], 150 years prior to the events of Xuan-Yuan Sword 3, this game addressed several loose threads in Xuan-Yuan Sword 3.\n\nThe main character is a young man named Chen Jingchou (\u9673\u9756\u4ec7, meaning \"To pacify the northern foes and to avenge Chen.\"), the only royal descendant remaining from the decimated [[Chen Dynasty]]. The final attempt for counterattack from the Chen family happened several years before Chen Jingchou was born, when the tens-of-thousands-strong remnants of Chen forces were single-handedly decimated by a 10-year-old Sui child, Yang Tuo (\u694a\u62d3) (later known as Yuwen Tuo \u5b87\u6587\u62d3), a student of [[Yang Su]].\n\nHaving lived under the reign of those who destroyed his kingdom, Chen Jingchou had been educated by his mentor, Chen Fu (\u9673\u8f14), to pursue a life of vengeance and of reviving his kingdom. The first step of their journey to restore Chen was to acquire the Mirror of Kunlun, one of the Ten Great Ancient Artifacts.<ref>\u300e\u9418\u528d\u65a7\u58fa\u5854\uff0c\u7434\u9f0e\u5370\u93e1\u77f3\u300f, thus ''Bell, Sword, Axe, Vessel, Tower, Zither, Ding, Seal, Mirror, and Stone.''</ref>\n\nThe ancient monstrosity [[Taotie]] was released from a mirror that was revealed to be a fake. In order to protect Jingchou, Fu trapped himself with Taotie using a potent Silk of Ice spell, and instructed Jingchou to embark at once to find a way to save him, as well as finding information concerning other Artifacts. As he set out on his journey, Jingchou summoned an elemental spirit familiar given to him by his master to accompany him on his journeys.\n\nJingchou later was later joined by Yu Xiaoxue (\u4e8e\u5c0f\u96ea), a white haired girl showing unusual healing magic potential, the honorable half [[G\u00f6kt\u00fcrks]]-blooded hero Zhang Lie (\u5f35\u70c8)<ref>Zhang Lie, \u5f35\u70c8, [[G\u00f6kt\u00fcrks]] blooded warlord of the north from the novel ''\u866f\u9aef\u5ba2\u50b3'', by \u675c\u5149\u5ead.</ref> and Zhang's young sister-in-law Tuoba Yu'er (\u62d3\u62d4\u7389\u5152) of the Tuoba tribe, which kept the Shennong Ding for generations and was subject to indiscriminate slaughter by the Sui emperor's troops. During their expedition in collecting the Artifacts, they encountered several Blood Rituals of Ten Thousand Souls, rites conducted by [[Grand Preceptor]] Yuwen Tuo which involved the killing of ten thousand souls to gather their essences into a single Blood Pearl. The party attempted to intervene with the rituals, but Yuwen Tuo proved to be too formidable a foe. Thus they adopted the strategy of subterfuge, hampering his every effort to collect the Blood Pearls without direct confrontations, and was even helped in secret by a young princess named Dugu Ningke (\u7368\u5b64\u5be7\u73c2), who held tremendous political power due to her relation with her uncle, [[Emperor Yang of Sui|the emperor]], and protested Yuwen's actions.\n\nEventually, their plan failed, and Yu Xiaoxue was held as a hostage by Tuo in exchange for the Artifacts that Jingchou's party had collected, namely the [[Shennong]] [[Ding (vessel)|Ding]], the Seal of Kongtong, the [[Pangu]] Axe, the [[N\u00fcwa]] Stone, and the [[Kunlun Mountain (mythology)|Kunlun]] Mirror. Jingchou complied, yet Tuo discarded the Stone and the mirror as fakes, proclaiming that he himself was actually the human avatar of the Kunlun Mirror. Surprisingly, Yu Xiaoxue refused to leave with Jingchou, stating that she intended to stay and help Tuo's project, and seemingly betrays his trust by repelling his attack on Yuwen's plans wielding the Xuan-Yuan Sword. Losing all hope, Jingchou gave up his quest and opted to travel with his similarly disheartened mentor.\n\nNingke, who was actually a demon general dispatched from the western pantheon of Hell, was displeased with this turn of events. She infiltrated China by possessing the original Princess Dugu who died of illness, and arrived in anticipation of what was calculated to be the time a [[Historical comet observations in China#Comets in Chinese astrology|comet]] named Crimson Piercer (Chi Guan - \u8d64\u8cab) would pass through the sky, opening a rift in the divine protective barrier of the Chinese lands and allowing an opportunity for demons from the West to invade. Tuo learned of the implications of the passage of the comet, and set out to collect five of the Artifacts in order to seal the rift the comet would cause in the Barrier of the Ninth [[Tian|Heaven]] in the firmament above [[Names of China#Shenzhou|Shenzhou]]. However, several of the five Artifacts required for the Ritual of Mending were nowhere to be found. Ningke proposed that he substitute these with Blood Pearls along with the construction of a [[Tower of Babel]], and a [[Pentagram]] ritual formation. In order to save the Chinese world, using his power, his riches and his relation with the [[Emperor Yang of Sui China|Emperor Yang]], Tuo managed to accomplish these despite his moral misgivings. In the process, Tuo also discovered that Xiaoxue was actually the avatar of the Stone of N\u00fcwa, as Artifacts resonate with each other when in close proximity. Consequently, he told her of his plan and convinced her to help him, leading to misunderstandings between her and Jingchou.\n\nNingke could not allow the Ritual to be abandoned and manipulated Jingchou through treachery by murdering Yu'er, who learned the truth behind the situation after going to the Grand Preceptor Residence in secret in an attempt to reconcile Xiaoxue and Jingchou, and framing Xiaoxue and Tuo. Fueled by anger and grief, Jingchou's party managed to reach the top of the Tower of Babel, where they were beaten once again by Tuo. Ningke suddenly appeared in the confusion and seized Xiaoxue as hostage to divert Tuo's attention. Jingchou took the opportunity and severed Tuo's arm. Ningke then revealed her true demon form, imprisoning Tuo with magic. Unable to mend the sky, the Chinese world fell under [[Satan]]'s rule of death and destruction.\n\nDays later, under the instruction of the now immortal He Ran and Gu Yuesheng (last seen in Xuan-Yuan Sword 2), Jingchou's group, which now also includes a young [[Li Shimin]] successfully retrieved the Artifacts from Ningke's handmaidens in the bloodied world, and returned to the Tower. They defeated Ningke with her full unrestricted power, and rescued Tuo. Having the Artifacts at hand, Jingchou and company invoked the Ritual of Reversal (which is also named the Ritual of Loss, \u5931\u537b\u4e4b\u9663) at the top of Tower of Babel, which, utilizing the power of Tuo as the avatar the Mirror of Kunlun at the ritual formation's center, reversed time and brought the party back to the moment prior to the passing of Chi Guan.\n\nThe group invoked the Ritual of Trespass (also called the Ritual of Babel), sending them above the sky, and arrived at Chi Guan itself. Coming across the Heavenly Maiden White Jade Ring (\u5929\u5973\u767d\u7389\u8f2a), an eight trigrams formation used by the deities Fuxi and N\u00fcwa to revive their deceased daughter in ancient times, Jingchou had the choice to bring Yu'er back to life at the cost of expending a great deal of Xiaoxue's power. At the heart of the meteor, where the party prepared to cast the Ritual of Sealing, which caused the non-artifact casters to lose their most precious memories or ideals (with Zhang Lie losing his ambition of unifying the lands, Li Shimin losing his love for his family, and Jingchou losing his memories of Yu'er or his master depending on the ending), Ningke, then still alive and ignorant of the recent events Jingchou and his companions experienced, appeared and attempted to continue her deception, but a fight ensued, and Ningke was vanquished. The party decided to grant her final wishes: to be returned to her homeland, and to become free to love whom she loves. Gu stated that was impossible due to her demonic nature, and placed her soul into the Fuxi [[Guqin|Qin]] (\u4f0f\u7fb2\u7434), which Yuwen Tuo brought with him on his self-imposed exile to the west, Ningke's homeland, after the events of the game for her soul to be cleansed eventually.\n\nChen Fu witnessed what appeared to be Jingchou assisting in the machinations of Yuwen Tuo, their sworn enemy. Ningke exploited this before heading to Chi Guan by giving Chen Fu the Fruit of Satan, a demonic object that grants power in exchange for sanity, deceiving him into battling against his student. Chen Fu soon arrived at the heart of Chi Guan with the intent to destroy it. Jingchou's group was left with no choice but to kill Chen Fu to save the world.\n\nSeveral decades later, Ningke was reborn as Nicole, a demon cleansed of evil, while Septem was born to a descendant of Tuo in western lands.\n\nThe Magic System is revamped in this game. All magics now belong to one of the [[five elements (Chinese philosophy)|five elements of metal, wood, water, fire, and earth (\u91d1\u6728\u6c34\u706b\u571f)]] in Chinese mythology.\n\nThe game was released on December 2, 2000.  A [[Xuan-Yuan Sword: Scar of Sky|television series]] based from the game, produced by Chinese Entertainment Shanghai Limited, starring [[Hu Ge]] and [[Cecilia Liu]], aired in 2012.\n\nAn iOS port of the game was released on April 8, 2014.\n\n===Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Millennial Destiny===\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u84bc\u4e4b\u6fe4}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword Legend: Billows of the Bleak\")\nThe game opens with an alternate version of the [[Battle of Fei River]], a battle between [[Former Qin]] and [[Eastern Jin]]. It concludes with Eastern Jin's surrender to Former Qin. Former Qin merged with Eastern Jin and united the entirety of China.\n\nSet within the [[Spring and Autumn period]], the story is told from the perspective of an orphaned girl, Che Yun (\u8eca\u82b8), whose family was framed by a corrupt official and executed. She was spared from execution due to her age, but her legs were amputated as punishment. Che Yun was talented in the art of Mujia - a technique of creating and manipulating constructs of magnets and wooden machinery, which are lightweight yet powerful, with her late grandfather as her inspiration. She fashioned herself wooden prosthetic legs and managed to craft a lifelike and agile wooden fox that can be used in various tasks such as transportation and battle, Yunhu (\u96f2\u72d0), after much effort and coming across rare materials. She was a close friend with Huan Yuanzhi (\u6853\u9060\u4e4b), whom Che Yun saved from drowning and who assisted her in creating Yunhu with exotic components. Che Yun later encountered Ying Shi (\u5b34\u8a69) (who is [[reincarnation]] of Che Yun except that Ying was from a different era and was named Murong Shi - \u6155\u5bb9\u8a69). With Che Yun as a common link, Huan and Ying formed a grudging alliance and adventured together, coming into conflicts with the Jin Kingdom's Tai Chen Gong, a priest organization focused on increasing its power and influence, and Heralds of the Seven Luminaries (\u4e03\u66dc\u4f7f\u8005 \"Qiyao Shizhe\"), a group of powerful rebels from a bleak future timeline sent back with the help of the student of the then-deceased Spirit of the Vessel. At the culmination of the story, Che, Ying and Huan reached the deepest chamber of the Realm of Haotian containing the wheel that determines the destiny of and relationship between all things, Wheel of [[Chinese theology#Taiyi|Taiyi]] (\u592a\u4e00\u4e4b\u8f2a \"Taiyi Zhi Lun\"). However, Murong and Huan were both duty-bound to set history on diverging courses in favor of their homelands. Che intended to stop Huan from changing the future despite Murong having decided against intervening with history by ordering Yunhu to push Huan away. However, Huan wielded the Xuan-Yuan Sword and injured Che fatally by accident while repelling Yunhu. The gate to the Palace then closed abruptly. Murong, unable to extract her friends was transported out of the gate, leaving Huan and Che in the room where Huan, immortal due to the power of his surroundings, mourned in regret for a thousand years. At the instant of Che Yun's death, Murong realized their link and inherited the knowledge of Mujia. She entered the gate when it next opened in a thousand years after she returned to the future in which Jin overcame Qin to fight for the welfare of the common-folk, encountering a sorrowful aged Huan and offering forgiveness and acceptance as Che Yun would have.\n\nReleased on February 6, 2004.\n\nOn December 3, 2015, an animated series based on the game called ''[[Xuan Yuan Sword Luminary]]'' (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\uff1a\u84bc\u4e4b\u66dc / Ken En Ken: Aoki Kagayaki, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword: Lights of the Bleak\") was announced as a collaborative project with [[TV Tokyo]] and [[Studio Deen]] and began airing on October 2, 2018 in Mainland China, Taiwan, as well as Japan.\n\n===Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Han Clouds===\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u6f22\u4e4b\u96f2}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword Legend: The Clouds of Han\")\nReleased on December 19, 2007.\n\nThe game is set in the era of the [[Three Kingdoms]], [[Wei (state)|Wei]], [[Shu Han|Shu]] and [[Wu (state)|Wu]] and feature famous historic figures. [[Zhuge Liang]], the chancellor of the kingdom of Shu had engaged on [[Zhuge Liang's Northern Expeditions|multiple northward military expeditions]] with little success. On Zhuge Liang's Third Expedition, a secret military group called \"Fei Yu\" (\u98db\u7fbd)\uff08meaning Flying Feather, deriving its name from the two famous generals of Shu kingdom - [[Zhang Fei]] and [[Guan Yu]])carried out various missions in the war to further the interests of Shu. However, on the Fourth Expedition, Thanks to its own group of powerful secret operatives, Wei was able to discover and exploit critical weaknesses of Shu, prompting The Feathers to take action. The game addresses issues of loyalty and duty, as well as the harsh realities of warfare and peace.\n\n[[Xuan-Yuan Sword: Han Cloud|A live-action television series based on the game]] has been released.\n\n===Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Clouds Faraway===\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u96f2\u4e4b\u9059}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword Legend: The Clouds Faraway\")\nReleased on January 12, 2010.\n\nThe Clouds Faraway, also set in the era of the [[Three Kingdoms]], is presented with a contrasting viewpoint to the Han Clouds. The main character, Xu Muyun (\u5f90\u66ae\u96f2), was adopted by [[Xu Shu]] and raised in the Kingdom of [[Cao Wei|Wei]]. Muyun grew up with his childhood friends Lanyin (\u862d\u8335) and Zhang Gao (\u5f35\u8aa5) in the house of [[Zhang He]], and the three youngsters vowed to fight for their homeland and bring about prosperous days together. Through his journey, Muyun came to a new level of maturity, learned of his true identity, realized the meaning of duty and friendship, and witnessed the ruthlessness of war.\n\nThe story is continued after the main game in three DLC chapters, released to enrich the story. These three chapters are: The Chapter of [[Wuzhang Plains]]: Muyun ({{zh|c=\u4e94\u4e08\u539f\u66ae\u96f2\u7bc7}}), The Chapter of Wuzhang Plains: Zhaoyun ({{zh|c=\u4e94\u4e08\u539f\u671d\u96f2\u7bc7}}), and the lengthy and critically acclaimed Chapter of Lan Yin ({{zh|c=\u862d\u8335\u7bc7}}).\n\n===Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Gate of Firmament===\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u7a79\u4e4b\u6249}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Sword Legend: The Gate of the Heavens\")\nReleased on March 26, 2015.\n\nIn ancient times, the Heavenly Emperor opened the Gate of Firmament, connecting the Heavens and Earth. Mortals could ascend to the Gate to obtain divine power in order to assist in the search for the Emperor's missing daughter. Unscrupulous individuals took advantage of the Emperor's gesture, and caused the mortal world to descend into chaos. The lives of the common folk were filled with anxiety and weariness. The god [[Fuxi]] and the goddess [[N\u00fcwa]] took pity on the people, and along with [[Zhuanxu]], convinced the Queen of Huaxu (\u83ef\u80e5\u4e4b\u4e3b, based on Lady Huaxu \u83ef\u80e5\u6c0f) to close the Gate forcibly with great sacrifice. After this, no one could reach the Heavens through the Gate, and no god could go to the mortal world; thus came about the Isolation of the Heavens and Earth (Jueditiantong \u7d55\u5730\u5929\u901a). Time passed, and the mortal realm suffered due to disasters and endless conflicts over [[Mandate of Heaven|claims to rule]], embroiled in political instability and riotous events. At this time of unrest and warfare, a Heavenly entity descends, adding to the unsolved mysteries of the troubled world.\n\nThe story revolves the journeys and adventures of Sikong Yu (\u53f8\u7a7a\u5b87), a young man whose goal is to protect his nomadic Youxiong village (\u6709\u718a\u6751), which consists of descendants of the Yellow Emperor, Muyue (\u6c90\u6708), a mysterious woman claiming to be from the legendary Kingdom of Huaxu (\u83ef\u80e5) whose distant behavior makes her seem unapproachable, [[Wu Ding|Feng Yu]] (\u9cf3\u715c), a jovial and cunning traveler with ties to royal House of Shang, and [[Fu Hao|Zi Qiao]] (\u5b50\u5de7), a royal high priestess of the Zi Kingdom who is betrothed to the Shang prince and possesses tremendous strength as well as an insatiable appetite. Together, they fight to bring the nefarious plots of a mysterious group of conspirators consisting of the followers of [[Gong Gong]] (\u5171\u5de5), the water god who had been sealed away for his violent actions, led by his second-in-command [[Xiangliu|Xiang Liu]] (\u76f8\u67f3), as well as Qing Yu (\u9752\u6986), the avatar of the [[World Tree]] Jian Mu (\u5efa\u6728) who has been driven by hatred for humans and vengeance against those of the Xuan-Yuan bloodline as well as his former lover Lan Ling (\u85cd\u9234), to an end before ruin befalls the world.\n\nThree free DLC packs have been released as game patches, including the Chapter of the All-encompassing (\u842c\u8c61\u4e4b\u7bc7), the Chapter of Gods and Demons/Chapter of Saviors (\u795e\u9b54\u4e4b\u7bc7), and the Chapter of the Watchful Vigil (\u5b88\u671b\u4e4b\u7bc7), which add side quests, stories, and hidden endings to the game.\n\nOn September 10, 2015 a multi-language version of the game was placed on [[Steam Greenlight]], the game has since been Greenlit and has been released in English, Japanese, simplified Chinese and traditional Chinese. It is the first core title (main and tales) in the series to see an English release.<ref>http://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/updates/515663220/1444192239</ref> A [[PlayStation 4]] port as well as a Xbox One version of the game have been released.\n\n==Spin-off titles==\n\n===Xuan-Yuan Demonbane Chronicles===\n({{zh|c=\u8ed2\u8f45\u4f0f\u9b54\u9304}}, literally \"Xuan-Yuan Records of Subduing Demons\")\nReleased on February 10, 2001.\n\nThe humble sword-wielding Mo clan hero defeats demons to bring peace to the world. The Monster Fusion Vessel is an ancient artifact that can seal away monsters.\n\nThe Mo clan is a group of powerful and righteous vigilantes, protecting the Monster Fusion Vessel for generations. The story begins with a resounding wave of panic, with a catastrophe witnessed by the young hero Fu Zixun. With his clan destroyed, the Vessel lost, the common folk imperiled, and his benefactor murdered, the young man never expected a trip down the mountain to turn into a grueling journey to defeat demons. Facing deaths and the seeking vengeance, his youth and naivet\u00e9 are buried only to be replaced by a heavy long sword and revenge weighing upon him. Together with the daughter of his benefactor, he begins his journey with uncertainty. Fortunately, the journey did not prove lonesome and he encountered a pampered daughter of a wealthy family who joined with bandits, a famous transport guard leader, a thief titled Flying on Grass, a legendary swordsman, a fox spirit from a mystic valley, and a simple boy leaving his House consisting of only himself. These people bear resentment, pain, anger, and hatred, yet gather under the common idea of righteousness to travel the world. The future holds many uncertainties, and their opponents have cunning schemes. The group does not even know where their path will end, so can only forge their way ahead little by little, encountering monsters causing disturbances as well as evil government officials mistreating commoners. \u201cJust what kind of world is this?\u201d The group can only ponder in disapproval, yet they share a belief that drives them forward-a belief in a beautiful future. Even though monsters threaten the world and heroes rise in response, but the outcome is still unknown. They can only rely on their companies\u2019 warmth to trudge through hardships together. All, with the appearance of the ancient weapon Xuan-Yuan Sword, shall eventually become clear.\n\nThis is an experimental strategy RPG utilizing 3D environments with 2D character sprites set in an alternate continuity to the core Xuan-Yuan Sword games, but still contains a few elements related to Xuan-Yuan Sword 3. The protagonist Fu Zixun (\u8f14\u5b50\u6d35) is a young man who goes on a journey after of his clan\u2019s destruction and the Monster Fusion Vessel\u2019s theft caused by Jiutian (\u4e5d\u5929), the malevolent entity the protagonist\u2019s younger clan sister Zhu Yuanyuan (\u6731\u5a9b\u6c85) accidentally unleashed. On his journey, he encounters allies including Ding Yun (\u4e01\u82b8), the kind and trusting daughter of a renowned doctor, Jiang Wushuang (\u6c5f\u7121\u96d9), a bossy young girl who ran away from home and leads a group of bandits she defeated, Zuo Zhenhe (\u5de6\u9707\u6cb3), a respected and mighty guard leader for transporting goods, Qiu Qianli (\u88d8\u5343\u91cc), a skilled but kind-hearted thief, Leng Zhongqiu (\u51b7\u4ef2\u79cb), a stoic hero with a dark past, Qise (\u4e03\u8272), a fox spirit with a feminine human form who is the elder sister to Jiutian, and Liang Cuo (\u6881\u932f), a slightly bumbling young man from a secretive family known for skills in engineering and the occult.\n\n==List of titles==\n{{More citations needed|list|date=May 2013}}\n*Main Series:\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d) (1990)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword 2 (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u8cb3) (1994)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword 3: Beyond the Clouds and Mountains (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u53c3\uff1a\u96f2\u548c\u5c71\u7684\u5f7c\u7aef) (1999)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword 4: The Black Dragon Dances as the Storm Rages (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u8086\uff1a\u9ed1\u9f8d\u821e\u516e\u96f2\u98db\u63da) (2002)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword 5: A Sword Above the Clouds and the Sentiments of the World of Shanhai (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u4f0d\uff1a\u4e00\u528d\u51cc\u96f2\u5c71\u6d77\u60c5) (2006)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword 6: The Phoenix Soars Above the Sky among the Millennial Clouds (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u9678\uff1a\u9cf3\u51cc\u9577\u7a7a\u5343\u8f09\u96f2) (2013)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://activity.softstar.com.tw/SWDOL/1010720/index.html|script-title=zh:\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u7cfb\u5217\u5b98\u65b9\u7db2\u7ad9|date=2012-08-09|accessdate=2012-08-10|language=zh }}</ref>\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword 7 (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u67d2) (TBA)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gnn.gamer.com.tw/6/152056.html|script-title=zh:\u300a\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u300b\u7cfb\u5217\u7e8c\u4f5c\u300a\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u67d2\u300b\u66dd\u5149 \u516c\u958b\u6545\u4e8b\u80cc\u666f\u6642\u4ee3\u8a2d\u5b9a\u8207 LOGO \u5f62\u8c61|date=2017-09-05|accessdate=2017-09-05|language=zh }}</ref>\n*Waizhuan (Tales) titles:\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword: Dance of the Maple Banners (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u6953\u4e4b\u821e) (1995)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword 3: The Scar of the Sky (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u53c3\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u5929\u4e4b\u75d5) (2001)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Millennial Destiny (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u84bc\u4e4b\u6fe4) (2004)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Han Clouds (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u6f22\u4e4b\u96f2) (2007)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Clouds Faraway (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u96f2\u4e4b\u9059) (2010)  \n**Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Gate of Firmament (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u7a79\u4e4b\u6249) (2015)\n*Spin-off titles:\n**Xuan-Yuan Demonbane Chronicles/Xuanyuan Fu Mo Lu (\u8ed2\u8f45\u4f0f\u9b54\u9304) (2001)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword Online: Chain of Life (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u7db2\u8def\u7248) (2002)\n**[[Dream of Mirror Online]]/Flying Adventure: Xuan-Yuan Sword Online 2 (\u98db\u5929\u6b77\u96aa\uff1a\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u7db2\u8def\u7248\u4e8c\u4ee3) (2005)\n**The Scar of the Sky Online (\u5929\u4e4b\u75d5 OL) (2010)\n**Flying PuPu (\u98db\u5929\u5657\u5657) (2011)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword Waizhuan Online (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3 Online) (2012)\n**Battle Legends (\u4f0f\u9b54\u50b3\u5947) (2012)\n**Mirror of Sanctity (\u5d11\u5d19\u93e1) (2012)\n**Xuan-Yuan Legends of Gods and Demons/Xuanyuan Shen Mo Zhuan (\u8ed2\u8f45\u795e\u9b54\u50b3) (2013)\n**Spell Card Xuan-Yuan (\u7b26\u5361\u8ed2\u8f45) (2014)\n**Vochord: Xuan-Yuan Sword Rhythm Game (Vochord \u8f69\u8f95\u5929\u7c41) (2017)\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Dragon Dances Among Clouds and Mountains (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u9f8d\u821e\u96f2\u5c71) (TBA)\n**Chronicles of Xuan-Yuan Heroes (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u7fa4\u4fe0\u9304) (TBA)\n*Spin-off media:\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Scar of the Sky (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u4e4b\u5929\u4e4b\u75d5)(2012) - A two-volume novel written by Yan Leisheng (\u71d5\u58d8\u751f) based on Xuan-Yuan Sword 3: The Scar of the Sky.\n**The Music of Xuan-Yuan Sword (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u6b77\u4ee3\u97f3\u6a02\u96c6\uff1a\u528d\u8a60\u8ed2\u8f45) (2014) - A collection of music from the series.\n**Xuan-Yuan Sword: Billows of the Bleak (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\u5916\u50b3\uff1a\u84bc\u4e4b\u6fe4) (2016) - A novel adaptation of the game of the same name.\n**[[Xuan Yuan Sword Luminary]] (\u8ed2\u8f45\u528d\uff1a\u84bc\u4e4b\u66dc) (2018) - An animated television series based on Xuan-Yuan Sword: The Millennial Destiny.\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Xuan-Yuan Sword: Scar of Sky]]''\n* ''[[The Legend of Sword and Fairy]]''\n\n==Notes and references==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080222141842/http://swd.joypark.com.tw/ Official Xuanyuan Sword website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120901015058/http://www.ancientchinese.net/blog/watch-online-xuan-yuan-sword-scar-sky/ Xuan Yuan Sword TV Series Fanpage]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110614224426/http://www.softstar.com.tw/ Softstar's website] {{in lang|zh}}\n*[http://www.mobygames.com/game-group/xuanyuan-jian-series Xuanyuan Sword series] at [[MobyGames]]\n\n[[Category:Action role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Chinese-language-only video games]]\n[[Category:Role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:Xuanyuan Jian]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Imperial China]]\n[[Category:Video game franchises introduced in 1990]]\n[[Category:Video games adapted into television programs]]\n", "name_user": "Danielt998", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, replaced: \uff08 \u2192 (, ,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xuan-Yuan_Sword"}
{"title_page": "Sailing yacht", "text_new": "{{multiple image|direction=vertical|image1=2013_Ahmanson_Cup_Regatta_yacht_Zapata_II_b_photo_D_Ramey_Logan.jpg|caption1=''Zapata II'', a 50&nbsp;ft cruising yacht|image2=60feet IMOCA SAFRAN 01.JPG|caption2=A 60&nbsp;ft [[IMOCA 60|IMOCA]] ocean racing yacht}}\n[[Image:Aerial view Yacht Harbour Residence Rostock Yachthafenresidenz Hohe D\u00fcne 1.jpg|thumb|upright|View of a yacht club, [[Rostock]]]]\n\nA '''sailing yacht''', or '''sailing vessel''' (US ship prefixes SY, S/Y, SV or S/V), is a leisure craft that uses sails as its primary means of propulsion. Sailing yachts are actively used in sport and are among categories recognized by the governing body of sailing sports, [[World Sailing]].<ref>[http://www.sailing.org/classes/#isaf_sliding_tab_item_classes_index_yacht World Sailing classes of yachts].</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe history of pleasure boats begins with rowed craft in Pharaonic Egyptian times. The history of sailing yachts begins in Europe in the beginning of the 1600s with the building of a pleasure vessel for the son of [[James VI and I|King James I of England]]. Pleasure vessels acquired the name ''yacht'' after the time of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]], who spent time exiled in Europe and visited the Netherlands, where a variety of yachts (''jaghts'' in Dutch) were already well-developed as pleasure boats for the elite classes since the beginning of the 17th century. Upon his restoration to the English crown, Charles commissioned a series of royal yachts, which included at least one experimental [[catamaran]]. The first recorded yacht race between two vessels occurred in 1661, followed by the first open sailing competition in 1663 in English waters.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Herreshoff|first=L. Francis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q4RONp_1mrMC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=history+of+sailing+yachts&hl=en|title=The Golden Age of Yachting|date=2007|publisher=Sheridan House, Inc.|year=|isbn=978-1-57409-251-6|location=|pages=19-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nStarting in 1739, England found itself in a series of wars\u2014a period that saw a decline in yachting. In Ireland, however, the gentry enjoyed yachting and founded the first yacht club in Cork as the Cork Harbor Water Club in 1720. English yacht racing continued among the English gentry who founded England's oldest yacht club in 1775 to support a fleet at [[Cumberland]]. With maritime peace, starting in 1815, came a resurgence of interest in yachting. Boatbuilders, who had been making fast vessels both for smugglers and the government [[Cutter (boat)|revenue cutters]], turned their skills again to yachts.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe fast yachts of the early 19th century were [[Fore-and-aft rig|fore-and-aft]] [[Lugger|luggers]], [[Schooner|schooners]], and [[Sloop|sloops]]. By the 1850s, yachts featured large sail areas, a narrow beam, and a deeper draft than was customary until then. Racing between yachts owned by wealthy patrons was common, with large wagers at stake. The [[America's Cup]] arose out of a contest between the yacht, ''[[America (yacht)|America]]'', and its English competitors. Both countries had rules by which to rate yachts, the English by tonnage and the American by length.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Description==\nThe [[length overall]] of sailing yachts ranges from {{convert|6|m|ft|0}}{{fact|date=March 2016}} to over {{convert|70|m|ft|0}}, with a majority measuring about {{convert|10|m|ft|0}}; The cost of building and keeping a yacht rises quickly as length increases. In the United States, sailors tend to refer to smaller yachts as [[sailboat]]s, while referring to the general sport of sailing as [[yachting]]. Within the limited context of sailboat racing, a yacht is any sailing vessel taking part in a race, regardless of size.\n\nModern yachts have efficient sail-plans like the [[Bermuda rig]], which together with an [[keel|appendage]] providing lateral resistance allow them to sail toward the wind.\n\n==Classes==\nWorld Sailing recognizes nine classes of racing yacht:<ref>[http://www.sailing.org/classes/#isaf_sliding_tab_item_classes_index_yacht World Sailing classes of yachts].</ref>\n#[[Class40]]\n#[[Farr 30]]\n#[[Farr 40]]\n#[[International Maxi Association]]\n#[[J/111]]\n#[[IMOCA 60]]\n#[[Soto 40]]\n#[[Swan 45]]\n#[[Swan 60]]\n#[[TP 52]]\n#[[X-35 (yacht)|X-35]]\n#[[X-41 (yacht)|X-41]]\n\n==See also==\n{{commonscat-inline|Sailing yachts}}\n*[[Dinghy sailing]]\n*[[International class]]\n*[[List of large sailing yachts]]\n*[[Skiff|Sailing skiff]]\n{{International Sailing Federation Classes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:Sailing yachts]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple image|direction=vertical|image1=2013_Ahmanson_Cup_Regatta_yacht_Zapata_II_b_photo_D_Ramey_Logan.jpg|caption1=''Zapata II'', a 50&nbsp;ft cruising yacht|image2=60feet IMOCA SAFRAN 01.JPG|caption2=A 60&nbsp;ft [[IMOCA 60|IMOCA]] ocean racing yacht}}\n[[Image:Aerial view Yacht Harbour Residence Rostock Yachthafenresidenz Hohe D\u00fcne 1.jpg|thumb|upright|View of a yacht club, [[Rostock]]]]\n\nA '''sailing yacht''', or '''sailing vessel''' (US ship prefixes SY, S/Y, SV or S/V), is a leisure craft that uses sails as its primary means of propulsion. Sailing yachts are actively used in sport and are among categories recognized by the governing body of sailing sports, [[World Sailing]].<ref>[http://www.sailing.org/classes/#isaf_sliding_tab_item_classes_index_yacht World Sailing classes of yachts].</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe history of yachting begins with rowed craft in Pharaonic Egyptian times. The history of sailing yachts begins in Europe in the beginning of the 1600s with the building of a pleasure vessel for the son of [[James VI and I|King James I of England]]. Pleasure vessels acquired the name ''yacht'' after the time of [[Charles II of England|Charles II]], who spent time exiled in Europe and visited the Netherlands, where a variety of yachts (''jaghts'' in Dutch) were already well-developed as pleasure boats for the elite classes since the beginning of the 17th century. Upon his restoration to the English crown, Charles commissioned a series of royal yachts, which included at least one experimental [[catamaran]]. The first recorded yacht race between two vessels occurred in 1661, followed by the first open sailing competition in 1663 in English waters.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Herreshoff|first=L. Francis|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q4RONp_1mrMC&newbks=0&printsec=frontcover&dq=history+of+sailing+yachts&hl=en|title=The Golden Age of Yachting|date=2007|publisher=Sheridan House, Inc.|year=|isbn=978-1-57409-251-6|location=|pages=19-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nStarting in 1739, England found itself in a series of wars\u2014a period that saw a decline in yachting. In Ireland, however, the gentry enjoyed yachting and founded the first yacht club in Cork as the Cork Harbor Water Club in 1720. English yacht racing continued among the English gentry who founded England's oldest yacht club in 1775 to support a fleet at [[Cumberland]]. With maritime peace, starting in 1815, came a resurgence of interest in yachting. Boatbuilders, who had been making fast vessels both for smugglers and the government [[Cutter (boat)|revenue cutters]], turned their skills again to yachts.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe fast yachts of the early 19th century were [[Fore-and-aft rig|fore-and-aft]] [[Lugger|luggers]], [[Schooner|schooners]], and [[Sloop|sloops]]. By the 1850s, yachts featured large sail areas, a narrow beam, and a deeper draft than was customary until then. Racing between yachts owned by wealthy patrons was common, with large wagers at stake. The [[America's Cup]] arose out of a contest between the yacht, ''[[America (yacht)|America]]'', and its English competitors. Both countries had rules by which to rate yachts, the English by tonnage and the American by length.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Description==\nThe [[length overall]] of sailing yachts ranges from {{convert|6|m|ft|0}}{{fact|date=March 2016}} to over {{convert|70|m|ft|0}}, with a majority measuring about {{convert|10|m|ft|0}}; The cost of building and keeping a yacht rises quickly as length increases. In the United States, sailors tend to refer to smaller yachts as [[sailboat]]s, while referring to the general sport of sailing as [[yachting]]. Within the limited context of sailboat racing, a yacht is any sailing vessel taking part in a race, regardless of size.\n\nModern yachts have efficient sail-plans like the [[Bermuda rig]], which together with an [[keel|appendage]] providing lateral resistance allow them to sail toward the wind.\n\n==Classes==\nWorld Sailing recognizes nine classes of racing yacht:<ref>[http://www.sailing.org/classes/#isaf_sliding_tab_item_classes_index_yacht World Sailing classes of yachts].</ref>\n#[[Class40]]\n#[[Farr 30]]\n#[[Farr 40]]\n#[[International Maxi Association]]\n#[[J/111]]\n#[[IMOCA 60]]\n#[[Soto 40]]\n#[[Swan 45]]\n#[[Swan 60]]\n#[[TP 52]]\n#[[X-35 (yacht)|X-35]]\n#[[X-41 (yacht)|X-41]]\n\n==See also==\n{{commonscat-inline|Sailing yachts}}\n*[[Dinghy sailing]]\n*[[International class]]\n*[[List of large sailing yachts]]\n*[[Skiff|Sailing skiff]]\n{{International Sailing Federation Classes}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:Sailing yachts]]\n", "name_user": "HopsonRoad", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:CE.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sailing_yacht"}
{"title_page": "Cincinnati", "text_new": "{{About|the city in Ohio}}\n{{Short description|City in Ohio}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name = Cincinnati, Ohio\n|official_name = City of Cincinnati\n|other_name = \n|settlement_type = [[City]]\n|image_skyline = File:Cincinnati Photomontage_V1.jpg\n|imagesize = 280px\n|image_caption = Clockwise, from top: [[Downtown Cincinnati]] skyline, [[Cincinnati Union Terminal]], the [[Over-the-Rhine]] neighborhood, [[Cincinnati Music Hall]], the [[John A. Roebling Suspension Bridge]], and [[Cincinnati City Hall]]\n|image_flag = Flag of Cincinnati.svg\n|image_seal = Seal of the City of Cincinnati (Ohio).png\n|image_blank_emblem = City of Cincinnati logo.png\n|blank_emblem_type = Logo\n|nicknames = Cincy, The Queen City, Porkopolis, Paris of America, The Nati, The \"513\u201d\n|motto = {{nowrap|''Juncta Juvant'' {{smaller|([[Latin]])}}<br />{{smaller|\"Strength in Unity\"}}}}\n|image_map = Hamilton County Ohio Incorporated and Unincorporated areas Cincinnati highlighted.svg\n|map_caption = Location within Hamilton County\n|coordinates = {{coord|39|6|N|84|31|W|region:US-OH_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|subdivision_type = Country\n|subdivision_name = [[United States]]\n|subdivision_type1 = State\n|subdivision_type2 = [[List of counties in Ohio|County]]\n|subdivision_name1 = [[Ohio]]\n|subdivision_name2 = [[Hamilton County, Ohio|Hamilton]]\n|established_title = Settled\n|established_date = 1788\n|established_title2 = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]] (town)\n|established_date2 = January 1, 1802{{sfn|Greve|1904|p=27|ps=: \"The act to incorporate the town of Cincinnati was passed at the first session of the second General Assembly held at Chillicothe and approved by Governor St. Clair on January 1, 1802.\"}}\n|established_title3 = Incorporated (city)\n|established_date3 = March 1, 1819<ref>{{harvnb|Greve|1904|pp=507\u2013508}}: \"This act was passed February 5, 1819, and by virtue of a curative act passed three days later took effect on March 1, of the same year.\"</ref>\n|named_for = [[Society of the Cincinnati]]\n|government_type = [[Mayor\u2013council government|Mayor\u2013council]]\n|leader_title = [[List of mayors of Cincinnati|Mayor]]\n|leader_name = [[John Cranley]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]])\n|leader_title1 = Body\n|leader_name1 = [[Cincinnati City Council]]\n\n|area_footnotes = <ref name=\"Gazetteer files\"/>\n|area_magnitude = 1 E8\n|area_total_km2 = 206.01\n|area_total_sq_mi = 79.54\n|area_land_km2 = 201.86\n|area_land_sq_mi = 77.94\n|area_water_km2 = 4.14\n|area_water_sq_mi = 1.60 \n|elevation_m = 147\n|elevation_ft = 482\n|elevation_max_m = 293\n|elevation_max_ft = 959\n|elevation_max_point =[[Mount Airy, Cincinnati, Ohio|Mount Airy]]\n|population_total = 296,943\n|population_as_of = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_footnotes =<ref name=\"wwwcensusgov\">{{cite web|title=U.S. Census website|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=January 6, 2013}}</ref>\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n|population_est = 302,605\n|pop_est_as_of = 2018 \n|pop_est_footnotes =<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=May 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190816184601/https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|archive-date=August 16, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|population_metro = 2,137,406 (US: [[List of Metropolitan Statistical Areas|28th]])\n|population_rank = US: [[List of United States cities by population|65th]]\n|population_blank1_title = [[Demonym]]\n|population_blank1 = Cincinnatian\n|postal_code_type = [[ZIP Code]]s\n|postal_code = {{collapsible list\n|title = ZIP Codes<ref>{{cite web |url=http://zip4.usps.com/zip4/citytown.jsp |publisher=USPS |title=Zip Code Lookup |accessdate=December 2, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209151401/http://zip4.usps.com/zip4/citytown.jsp |archivedate=February 9, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n|frame_style = border:none; padding: 0;\n|list_style = text-align:center;display:none\n|45201\u201345209, 45211\u201345255, 45258, 45262\u201345264, 45267\u201345271, 45273\u201345275, 45277, 45280, 45296, 45298\u201345299, 45999}}\n|area_code = [[Area code 513|513]], \n[[Area codes 937 and 326|937, 326]]|area_code_type = [[North American Numbering Plan|Area code]]\n|website = {{URL|cincinnati-oh.gov}}\n|footnotes = \n|pushpin_label = Cincinnati\n|timezone = [[Eastern Standard Time Zone|EST]]\n|utc_offset = \u22125\n|timezone_DST = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST = \u22124\n|blank_name = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info = 39-15000<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=January 31, 2008 |title=U.S. Census website |df=mdy }}</ref>\n|blank1_name = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info = 1066650<ref name=\"GR3\">{{cite web|url=http://geonames.usgs.gov|accessdate=January 31, 2008|title=US Board on Geographic Names|publisher=[[United States Geological Survey]]|date=October 25, 2007|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/65jET5cdV?url=http://geonames.usgs.gov/|archive-date=February 26, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| blank2_name = [[GDP]]\n| blank2_info = $119&nbsp;billion [[United States dollar|USD]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/RGMP17140 |title=Total Real Gross Domestic Product for Cincinnati, OH-KY-IN (MSA) |publisher=Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis |accessdate=October 21, 2019 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191021021432/https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/RGMP17140 |archivedate=October 21, 2019 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Cincinnati''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|s|\u026a|n|s|\u1d7b|\u02c8|n|\u00e6|t|i}} {{respell|SIN|sih|NAT|ee}}) is a major city in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Ohio]], and is the government [[county seat|seat]] of [[Hamilton County, Ohio|Hamilton County]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web |url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=June 7, 2011 |title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608061745/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=June 8, 2011 |df=mdy }}</ref> Settled in 1788, the city is located at the northern side of the confluence of the [[Licking River (Kentucky)|Licking]] and [[Ohio River|Ohio]] rivers, the latter of which marks the state line with [[Kentucky]]. The city is the economic and cultural hub of the [[Cincinnati metropolitan area]], the fastest growing economic power in the [[Midwestern United States]] based on increase of economic output,<ref name=\"cincinnati1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/money/2015/09/23/cincinnati-economy-fastest-growing-midwest/72689970/|title=Cincinnati economy fastest-growing in the Midwest|newspaper=Cincinnati.com|access-date=December 1, 2016}}</ref> which had a population of 2,190,209 as of the 2018 census estimates. This makes it Ohio's largest metropolitan area and the nation's 29th-largest.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/stories/2010/06/21/daily22.html | title = Census: Cincinnati 62nd-largest U.S. city | publisher = Business Courier | date = June 22, 2010 | accessdate = June 22, 2010 | first = G. Scott | last = Thomas | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100629002235/http://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/stories/2010/06/21/daily22.html | archive-date = June 29, 2010 | url-status = live }}</ref> With a city population estimated at 302,605, Cincinnati is the [[list of cities in ohio|third-largest city in Ohio]] and [[list of united states cities by population|65th in the United States]]. Cincinnati is within a day's drive of 49.70% of the United States populace, ranking it as fourth in the list of metro areas with the largest population base within one day\u2019s drive time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://info.siteselectiongroup.com/blog/top-20-metros-with-highest-percent-of-us-population-within-one-day-drive|title=Top 20 metro areas with highest % of U.S. population within one day drive, USA|last=|first=|date=2014-11-10|website=siteselectiongroup|access-date=March 3, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306042756/https://info.siteselectiongroup.com/blog/top-20-metros-with-highest-percent-of-us-population-within-one-day-drive|archive-date=March 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the 19th century, Cincinnati was an American [[boomtown]] in the middle of the country. Throughout much of the 19th century, it was listed among the top 10 U.S. cities by population, surpassed only by [[New Orleans]] and the older, established settlements of the United States eastern seaboard, as well as being the [[Largest cities in the United States by population by decade#1840|sixth-biggest city]] for a period spanning 1840 until 1860. Cincinnati was the first city founded after the [[American Revolution]], as well as the first major inland city in the country.\n\nCincinnati developed with fewer immigrants and less influence from Europe than East Coast cities in the same period. However, it received a significant number of German-speaking immigrants, who founded many of the city's cultural institutions.  By the end of the 19th century, with the shift from steamboats to railroads drawing off freight shipping, trade patterns had altered and Cincinnati's growth slowed considerably. The city was surpassed in population by other inland cities, particularly [[Chicago]], which developed based on strong commodity exploitation, economics, and the railroads, and [[St. Louis]], which for decades after the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] served as the gateway to westward migration.\n\nCincinnati is home to three major sports teams: the [[Cincinnati Reds]] of [[Major League Baseball]]; the [[Cincinnati Bengals]] of the [[National Football League]]; and  [[FC Cincinnati]] of [[Major League Soccer]].  The city's largest institution of higher education, the [[University of Cincinnati]], was founded in 1819 as a municipal college and is now ranked as one of the 50 largest in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rieselman|first=Deborah|title=Brief history of University of Cincinnati|url=http://magazine.uc.edu/editors_picks/fun/briefhistory.html|work=UC Magazine|publisher=University of Cincinnati University Relations|accessdate=February 12, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219091343/http://magazine.uc.edu/editors_picks/fun/briefhistory.html|archive-date=February 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Cincinnati is home to historic architecture with many structures in the urban core having remained intact for 200 years. In the late 1800s, Cincinnati was commonly referred to as the \"Paris of America\", due mainly to such ambitious architectural projects as the [[Music Hall (Cincinnati)|Music Hall]], [[Palace Hotel (Cincinnati, Ohio)|Cincinnatian Hotel]], and [[John Shillito Company|Shillito Department Store]].<ref>{{cite web|title=When Cincinnati was 'the Paris of America' |date=April 19, 2010 |work=Building Cincinnati |url=http://www.building-cincinnati.com/2010/04/when-cincinnati-was-paris-of-america.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419145025/http://www.building-cincinnati.com/2010/04/when-cincinnati-was-paris-of-america.html |archivedate=April 19, 2012 |df=mdy }}\n* {{cite book|title=Picturesque Cincinnati|page=[https://archive.org/details/picturesquecinci00daws/page/154 154]|publisher=John Shillito Company|year=1883|oclc=3402849|location=Cincinnati, Ohio|url=https://archive.org/details/picturesquecinci00daws}}\n* {{Cite news|archive-date=February 16, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216112849/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/13/travel/cincinnati-budget-travel.html|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/13/travel/cincinnati-budget-travel.html|date=July 13, 2016|last=Peterson|first=Lucas|work=The New York Times|title=From Chili to the Underground Railroad, Cincinnati on a Budget\n}}\n* {{cite book|title=Over-the-Rhine: When Beer Was King|last=Morgan|first=Michael D.|chapter=Side-Door Sundays in the Paris of America|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-qwjCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT65|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2010}}\n</ref> Cincinnati is the birthplace of [[William Howard Taft]], the [[List of Presidents of the United States|27th]] President of the United States.\n\n==History==\n{{main|History of Cincinnati}}\n{{see also|Timeline of Cincinnati|History of Ohio}}\n[[File:Cincinnati I.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.35|Cincinnati in 1812 with a population of 2,000<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Pictorial Field-Book of the War of 1812|last=Lossing|first=Benson|publisher=Harper & Brothers, Publishers|year=1868|isbn=|location=|page=476}}</ref>|alt=]]\n\nCincinnati began in 1788 when Mathias Denman, [[Colonel Robert Patterson]], and [[Israel Ludlow]] landed at a spot at the northern bank of the Ohio opposite the mouth of the [[Licking River (Kentucky)|Licking]] and decided to settle there. The original surveyor, [[John Filson]], named it \"Losantiville\".<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924032193520|title=History of Cincinnati, Ohio|publisher=Cleveland, O., L.A. Williams & Co.|year=1881|access-date=February 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170522164145/https://archive.org/details/cu31924032193520|archive-date=May 22, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1790, [[Arthur St. Clair]], the governor of the [[Northwest Territory]], changed the name of the settlement to \"Cincinnati\" in honor of the [[Society of the Cincinnati]], made up of Revolutionary War veterans, of which he was a member;<ref name=\"city-ws\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/crc/pages/-5928-/|title=How Cincinnati Became A City|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060928142621/https://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/crc/pages/-5928-/|archivedate=September 28, 2006|url-status=dead|access-date=December 11, 2006}}</ref> which was in turn named for [[Lucius Quinctius Cincinnatus]], a dictator in the early Roman Republic who saved Rome from a crisis, and then retired to farming because he did not want to remain in power.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.factinate.com/interesting/46-interesting-facts-ancient-rome-2/15?fact=1|title=46 Interesting Facts about Ancient Rome \u2013 Page 15 of 44|date=April 6, 2017|publisher=|access-date=November 29, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180623193851/https://www.factinate.com/interesting/46-interesting-facts-ancient-rome-2/15?fact=1|archive-date=June 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe introduction of steamboats on the Ohio River in 1811 opened up the city's trade to more rapid shipping, and the city established commercial ties with [[St. Louis, Missouri]] and [[New Orleans]] downriver. Cincinnati was incorporated as a city on March 1, 1819.{{sfn|Greve|1904|pp=507\u2013508}} Exporting pork products and hay, it became a center of pork processing in the region. From 1810 to 1830 its population nearly tripled, from 9,642 to 24,831.<ref name=\"The United States Census Bureau\">{{cite web |publisher=The United States Census Bureau |url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0027.html |title=Population of the 100 largest cities 1790\u20131990 |accessdate=July 29, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070714032017/http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0027.html |archivedate=July 14, 2007 |df=mdy }}</ref> Completion of the [[Miami and Erie Canal]] in 1827 to [[Middletown, Ohio]] further stimulated businesses, and employers struggled to hire enough people to fill positions. The city had a labor shortage until large waves of immigration by Irish and Germans in the late 1840s. The city grew rapidly over the next two decades, reaching 115,000 people by the year 1850.<ref name=\"city-ws\"/>\n\nConstruction on the Miami and Erie Canal began on July 21, 1825, when it was called the Miami Canal, related to its origin at the [[Great Miami River]]. The first section of the canal was opened for business in 1827.<ref name=\"Condit\">{{cite book|author=Carl W. Condit|title=The Railroad and the City: A Technological and Urbanistic History of Cincinnati|url=https://archive.org/details/railroadcitytech0000cond|url-access=registration}}</ref> In 1827, the canal connected Cincinnati to nearby [[Middletown, Ohio|Middletown]]; by 1840, it had reached [[Toledo, Ohio|Toledo]]. During this period of rapid expansion and prominence, residents of Cincinnati began referring to the city as the Queen City.\n\n===Industrial development and Gilded Age===\nAfter the steamboats, railroads were the next major form of commercial transportation to come to Cincinnati. In 1836, the [[Little Miami Railroad]] was chartered.<ref name=\"Vexler\">{{cite book|author=Robert Vexler|title=Cincinnati: A Chronological & Documentary History}}</ref>{{page needed|date=July 2018}} Construction began soon after, to connect Cincinnati with the Mad River and Lake Erie Railroad, and provide access to the ports of the [[Sandusky Bay]] on [[Lake Erie]].<ref name=\"Condit\" />{{page needed|date=July 2018}}\n\nCincinnati acted as a \"border town\" during the slave-owning period between 1810 and 1863. Its location, on the border between the free state of Ohio and the slave state of Kentucky, made it a prominent location for slaves to escape the slave-owning south. Many prominent abolitionists also called Cincinnati their home during this period, and made it a popular stop on the Underground Railroad.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cincinnatimagazine.com/citywiseblog/lost-city-underground-railroad/|title=Lost City: Underground Railroad Sites - Cincinnati Magazine|date=2017-05-18|work=Cincinnati Magazine|access-date=2018-11-14|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181118012505/http://www.cincinnatimagazine.com/citywiseblog/lost-city-underground-railroad/|archive-date=November 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2004, the [[National Underground Railroad Freedom Center]] was completed along Freedom Way in Downtown, honoring the city's past involvement in the Underground Railroad.\n\n[[File:Cincinnati-in-1841.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|Cincinnati in 1841 with the Miami and Erie Canal in the foreground]]\n\nIn 1859, Cincinnati laid out six streetcar lines; the cars were [[Horsecar|pulled by horses]] and the lines made it easier for people to get around the city.<ref name=\"Vexler\" /> By 1872, Cincinnatians could travel on the streetcars within the city and transfer to rail cars for travel to the hill communities. The Cincinnati Inclined Plane Company began transporting people to the top of Mount Auburn that year.<ref name=\"Condit\" /> In 1889, the [[Streetcars in Cincinnati|Cincinnati streetcar system]] began converting its horse-drawn cars to [[Tram|electric streetcars]].<ref name=\"Exhibit commemorates the streetcar era\">{{cite news |last=O'Neill |first=Tom |title=Exhibit commemorates the streetcar era |newspaper=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]] |date=August 18, 2001 |url=http://www.enquirer.com/editions/2001/08/18/loc_exhibit_commemorates.html |accessdate=January 3, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1880, the city government completed the [[Cincinnati, New Orleans and Texas Pacific Railway|Cincinnati Southern Railway]] to [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]]. It is the only municipally-owned interstate railway in the United States.\n\nIn 1884, outrage over a [[manslaughter]] verdict in what many observers thought was a clear case of murder triggered the [[Cincinnati riots of 1884|Courthouse riots]], one of the most destructive riots in American history. Over the course of three days, 56 people were killed and over 300 were injured.{{sfn|Stradling|2003|p=67}} The riots ended the regime of political bosses [[John Roll McLean]] and [[Thomas C. Campbell]] in Cincinnati.\n\n===During the Great Depression===\nAn early rejuvenation of downtown began in the 1920s and continued into the next decade with the construction of [[Cincinnati Union Terminal|Union Terminal]], the post office, and the large [[Cincinnati and Suburban Telephone Company Building]]. Cincinnati weathered the [[Great Depression]] better than most American cities of its size, largely due to a resurgence in river trade, which was less expensive than transporting goods by rail.  The [[Ohio River flood of 1937|flood in 1937]] was one of the worst in the nation's history and destroyed many areas along the [[Ohio valley]]. Afterward the city built protective flood walls.\n\n===Nicknames===\n\nCincinnati has many [[nickname]]s, including Cincy, The Nati, The Queen City,<ref>''Close to home: Across the region, dozens of sites have historic ties to the Underground Railroad'', ''[[Cincinnati Enquirer]]'', Sunday, August 15, 2004, \"The poet Longfellow, recognizing the town's rising stature, immortalized Cincinnati as the \"Queen City of the West\". [http://www.cincinnati.com/freetime/nurfc/D1_monlede.html] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425102258/http://www2.cincinnati.com/freetime/nurfc/D1_monlede.html |date=April 25, 2016 }} accessed 2008-05-03</ref> The Queen of the West,<ref name=\"Museum FAQ\">{{cite web|url=http://library.cincymuseum.org/cinfaq7menu.htm|title=Frequently Asked Questions about Cincinnati, Ohio|access-date=September 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101211551/http://library.cincymuseum.org/cinfaq7menu.htm|archive-date=November 1, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The Blue Chip City,<ref name=\"Discount Blue Chip\">{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3092/is_n11_v27/ai_6387266|title=Cincinnati: many discounters say it's a 'blue chip' investment|work=Discount Store News|year=1988|access-date=September 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090527091202/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m3092/is_n11_v27/ai_6387266/|archive-date=May 27, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CBC Lawley\">{{cite news|title=Cookie firm swallows parent: The local Blue Chip Cookies franchisee is buying the company's San Francisco franchiser|first=Lauren|last=Lawley|work=[[Cincinnati Business Courier]]|publisher=[[Advance Publications#American City Business Journals|American City Business Journals]]|date=1998-07-17|accessdate=2008-05-03|url=http://cincinnati.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/stories/1998/07/20/story5.html|quote=In 1984, the Greater Cincinnati Chamber of Commerce began its 'Blue Chip City' campaign, a marketing strategy it continued through last year.|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130118052853/http://cincinnati.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/stories/1998/07/20/story5.html|archive-date=January 18, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |date=March 11, 2001 |title=Great cities test: How does Cincinnati stack up to its regional rivals? |url=http://www.enquirer.com/editions/2001/03/11/loc_great_cities.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120729162245/http://www.enquirer.com/editions/2001/03/11/loc_great_cities.html |archive-date=July 29, 2012 |work=[[Cincinnati Enquirer]] |quote=Cincinnati's dated 'Blue Chip City' nickname is being replaced with 'Let the spirit move you.' To where? |access-date=23 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and The City of Seven Hills.<ref name=\"Enquirer Ups downs\">{{cite news |title=Ups and downs: The hills are alive, but don't try counting |url=http://www.cincinnati.com/local/atoz/upsanddowns.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060629225959/http://www.cincinnati.com/local/atoz/upsanddowns.html |archive-date=June 29, 2006 |work=[[Cincinnati Enquirer]] |access-date=23 February 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> These are more typically associated with professional, academic, and public relations references to the city, including restaurant names such as [[Blue Chip Cookies]], and are not commonly used by locals in casual conversation.\n\nThe seven hills are fully described in the June, 1853 edition of the ''West American Review'', \"Article III--Cincinnati: Its Relations to the West and South\". The hills form a crescent from the east bank of the Ohio River to the west bank: Mount Adams, Walnut Hills, Mount Auburn, Vine Street Hill, College Hill, Fairmount, and Mount Harrison.\n\nThe classic nickname \"Queen City\" is taken from an 1819 newspaper article<ref>{{Cite web |title=Letter from Alfred Kleinne-Krautzmann to Robert M. Evanson |url=http://www.church-of-ouzo.com/pdf/public-library-of-cincinnati.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324194347/http://www.church-of-ouzo.com/pdf/public-library-of-cincinnati.pdf |archive-date=24 March 2016 |date=7 May 1990 |access-date=23 February 2019}}</ref> and further immortalized by the 1854 poem \"Catawba Wine\". In it, [[Henry Wadsworth Longfellow]] wrote of the city:\n\n{{poemquote|And this Song of the Vine,\nThis greeting of mine,\nThe winds and the birds shall deliver,\nTo the Queen of the West,\nIn her garlands dressed,\nOn the banks of the Beautiful River.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://library.cincymuseum.org/cinfaq7menu.htm | title=Cincinnati FAQs &#124; Cincinnati History Library and Archives | access-date=September 4, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131101211551/http://library.cincymuseum.org/cinfaq7menu.htm | archive-date=November 1, 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref>}}\n\nFor many years, Cincinnati was known as \"Porkopolis\"; this less desirable nickname came from the city's large pork interests.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-hB6AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA334| title=Cincinnati, the Queen City, 1788\u20131912, Volume 2 | publisher=The S. J. Clarke Publishing Company | year=1912 | accessdate=2013-05-20 | author=Clark, S. J. | pages=334}}</ref>\n\nNewer nicknames such as \"The 'Nati\" are emerging and are attempted to be used in different cultural contexts. For example, a local [[litter]]-prevention campaign uses the slogan \"Don\u2019t Trash the 'Nati.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.keepcincinnatibeautiful.org/Programs/dttn.html |title=Don't Trash the 'Nati |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080926034617/http://www.keepcincinnatibeautiful.org/Programs/dttn.html |archivedate=September 26, 2008 |access-date=September 4, 2018 }}, Keep Cincinnati Beautiful website, accessed May 3, 2008</ref>\n\n\"The City of Seven Hills\" is another name for the city.  When the city was younger and smaller, the June 1853 edition of the ''West American Review'', \"Article III\u2014Cincinnati: Its Relations to the West and South\" described and named seven specific hills.  The hills form a crescent around the city: [[Mount Adams, Ohio|Mount Adams]], [[Walnut Hills, Cincinnati|Walnut Hills]], [[Mount Auburn, Cincinnati, Ohio|Mount Auburn]], Vine Street Hill, College Hill, Fairmont (now rendered Fairmount), and Mount Harrison (now known as Price Hill). The name refers to ancient Rome, reputed to be built on seven hills. A prominent local private K-12 school is named [[Seven Hills School]].\n\n==Society==\n{{Main|Culture of Cincinnati}}\n\nLike all major cities in the United States, Cincinnati was proliferated by [[American ancestry|Americans]], but also [[Ulster Scots people|Ulster Scots]] known as the [[Scotch-Irish Americans|Scots Irish]], [[American frontier|frontiersmen]], and [[keelboat]]ers. Most of Cincinnati's longtime residents have kinships rooted throughout the Ohio-Kentucky-Indiana [[Tri-state area|tristate]] and deeper.  The first [[Methodism|Methodist class]] came about in 1798, city residents for years already inspired by the Methodist circuit preachers; among Methodist institutes were [[The Christ Hospital]] as well as projects of the [[Nast Trinity United Methodist Church|German Methodist Church]].\n\n[[File:The Belle of Louisville docks next to the Natchez in Cincinnati for Tall Stacks 2006.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.35|[[Tall Stacks]], held every three or four years between 1988 and 2006, celebrated the city's [[riverboat]] heritage.]]\n\nCincinnati, being on the heartland plain, depended on trade with the slave states south of the Ohio River at a time when thousands of black people were settling in the free state of Ohio. Most of them came after the Civil War, and were from Kentucky and Virginia with many of them fugitives who had sought freedom and work in the North.  In the antebellum years, the majority of native-born whites in the city came from northern states, primarily [[Pennsylvania]].<ref>Taylor (2005), ''Frontiers of Freedom,'' pp. 20\u201321</ref>   Though 57 percent of whites migrated from free states, 26 percent were from southern states and they retained their cultural support for slavery. This quickly led to tensions between pro-slavery residents and those in favor of [[abolitionism]] and lifting restrictions on [[free people of color]], as codified in the \"Black Code\" of 1804.<ref name=Aaron1992/>\n\nGermans were among the earliest newcomers, migrating from Pennsylvania and the backcountry of Virginia and Tennessee.  General [[David Ziegler]] succeeded General St. Clair in command at [[Fort Washington (Cincinnati, Ohio)|Fort Washington]].  After the conclusion of the [[Northwest Indian War]] and removal of Native Americans to the west, he was elected as Cincinnati's first town president (equivalent to a mayor) in 1802.{{sfn|Greve|1904|p=440|ps=: \"This explains a common confusion of ideas as to the first mayor of Cincinnati. David Ziegler was the first president of the town, [[William Corry (Cincinnati mayor)|William Corry]] the first mayor of the town, and [[Isaac G. Burnet]] the first mayor of the city.\"}}<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-hB6AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA9| title=Cincinnati, the Queen City, 1788\u20131912, Volume 2 | publisher=The S. J. Clarke Publishing Company | year=1912 | accessdate=May 20, 2013 | author=Clark, S. J. | page=9}}</ref> Cincinnati was influenced by [[Ireland|Irishmen]], and [[Prussia]]ns and [[Old Saxony|Saxons]] ([[Northern Germany|northern Germans]]), seeking to emigrate away from crowding and strife.  In 1830 residents with German roots made up 5% of the population, as many had migrated from Pennsylvania; ten years later this had increased to 30%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cincinnati-cityofimmigrants.com/cci/german.htm |title=:: Cincinnati, A City of Immigrants  |publisher=Cincinnati-cityofimmigrants.com |accessdate=July 10, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130724105123/http://www.cincinnati-cityofimmigrants.com/cci/german.htm |archive-date=July 24, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Thousands of Germans entered the city after the [[German revolutions of 1848\u201349|Prussian revolution of 1848]], and by 1900, more than 60 percent of its population was of Prussian background.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hetzer|first=Laura|title=Cincinnati: Our German History|url=http://voices.yahoo.com/cincinnati-our-german-history-327345.html|publisher=Yahoo!|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102191716/http://voices.yahoo.com/cincinnati-our-german-history-327345.html|archivedate=November 2, 2012|df=mdy-all}}{{unreliable source?|date=July 2015}}</ref> The menial-jobbed, aggravated Irish often organized mobs and the Germans, far away from their [[Pennsylvania Dutch]] connections, did the same. Thus, leaders of the city had to use fortifying measures against the arrivals' clashes.\n\n[[File:TylerDavidsonFountainAtNight.jpg|upright|thumb|The [[Tyler Davidson Fountain|Genius of Water]], a symbol of Cincinnati, was dedicated in 1871.]]\n\nVolatile social conditions saw [[Cincinnati riots of 1829|riots in 1829]], when many blacks lost their homes and property.  As the Irish entered the city in the late 1840s, they competed with blacks at the lower levels of the economy. White-led riots against blacks occurred [[Cincinnati Riots of 1836|in 1836]], when an abolitionist press was twice destroyed; and in 1842.<ref name=Aaron1992>{{cite book| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=eCgVN3FKOxQC&pg=PA300| page = 300ff| title = Cincinnati, Queen City of the West: 1819\u20131838| author = Daniel Aaron| publisher = Ohio State University Press| year = 1992| isbn = 978-0-8142-0570-9| accessdate = October 24, 2010| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160113230317/https://books.google.com/books?id=eCgVN3FKOxQC&pg=PA300| archive-date = January 13, 2016| url-status = live}}</ref> More than 1,000 blacks abandoned the city after the 1829 riots. Blacks in Philadelphia and other major cities raised money to help the refugees recover from the destruction. By 1842 blacks had become better established in the city; they defended themselves and their property in the riot, and worked politically as well.<ref>{{cite book|author=Nikki Marie Taylor|title=Frontiers of Freedom: Cincinnati's Black Community, 1802\u20131868|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZC8xDzjUM-cC|year=2005|publisher=Ohio University Press|isbn=978-0-8214-1579-5}}</ref>\n\nThe emigres, while having been widely discussed, never overtook settlers in population. Nearby [[Waynesville, Ohio|Waynesville]] hosts the yearly Ohio Sauerkraut Festival,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.SauerkrautFestival.Com/|title= Ohio Sauerkraut Festival|date= December 16, 2017|work= SauerkrautFestival.Com|access-date= December 6, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180117180858/http://www.sauerkrautfestival.com/|archive-date= January 17, 2018|url-status= live}}</ref> and Cincinnati hosts several big yearly events which commemorate connections to the Old World. [[Oktoberfest Zinzinnati]],<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.cincinnati.com/story/entertainment/2014/09/16/hey-fonzie-welcome-zinzinnati/15718493/|title= Oktoberfest Zinzinnati: Hey, Fonzie: Welcome to town!|date= September 16, 2014|work= Cincinnati.com|access-date= January 22, 2015|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160124145733/http://www.cincinnati.com/story/entertainment/2014/09/16/hey-fonzie-welcome-zinzinnati/15718493/|archive-date= January 24, 2016|url-status= live}}</ref> [[Bockfest]],<ref>[http://www.cincyusa.com/events/popular/] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122034409/http://www.cincyusa.com/events/popular/ |date=January 22, 2015 }}, Cincy USA website</ref> and the [[Taste of Cincinnati]] feature local restaurateurs.\n\n[[History of the Jews in Cincinnati|Cincinnati's Jewish community]] was developed by those from England and Germany. A large segment of the community, led by [[Isaac M. Wise]], developed [[Reform Judaism]] in response to the influences of the Enlightenment and making their new lives in the United States. Rabbi Wise, known as a founding father of the Reform movement, and his contemporaries, bore a great influence on the Jewish faith in Cincinnati, the United States, and worldwide.<ref name=je>{{Jewish Encyclopedia|inline=1|title=WISE, ISAAC MAYER|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/14954-wise-isaac-mayer|last1=Adler|first1=Cyrus|author-link1=Cyrus Adler|last2=Philipson|first2=David|author-link2=David Philipson|accessdate=Dec 3, 2015}}<br/>'''Jewish Encyclopedia bibliography:'''\n*I. M. Wise, ''Reminiscences'', transl. from the German and ed. by David Philipson, Cincinnati, 1901;\n* {{cite book|volume=XXI|last1=Skolnik|first1=Fred|last2=Berenbaum|first2=Michael|publisher=Macmillan|location=New York|page=100|quote=...Wise's foresightedness and tenacity in laying its three institutional cornerstones earned him the title 'founding father' of the indigenous Reform movement in America|title=Encyclopaedia Judaica}}\n*''[[The American Israelite]]'', 1854\u20131900, [[passim]], and the Jubilee number, 30 June 1904.</ref>\n\nThe [[NRHP]]-listed [[Potter Stewart United States Courthouse]] is a [[Federal judiciary of the United States|federal court]], the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit]], one of [[United States courts of appeals#Circuit composition|thirteen United States courts of appeals]]. [[Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland Cincinnati Branch]] is located across the street from the [[East Fourth Street Historic District (Cincinnati, Ohio)|East Fourth Street Historic District]].\n\n===Economy===\n{{See also|List of companies in Greater Cincinnati}}\n[[File:Cincinnati-procter-and-gamble-headquarters.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Procter & Gamble]] headquarters in Cincinnati]]\nMetropolitan Cincinnati has the [[List of U.S. metropolitan areas by GDP|twenty-eighth largest economy]] in the United States and the [[List of U.S. metropolitan areas by GDP|seventh largest in the Midwest]], after [[Chicago]], [[Minneapolis]], [[Detroit]], [[St. Louis]], [[Indianapolis]], and [[Cleveland]]. It currently has the fastest-growing Midwestern economic capital based on percentages.<ref name=\"cincinnati1\"/> The gross domestic product for the region was $127&nbsp;billion as of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/cincinnaticityohio/PST045216|title=U.S. Census Bureau QuickFacts: Cincinnati city, Ohio|website=www.census.gov|language=en|access-date=November 16, 2017}}</ref>  The median home price is $158,200, and the [[cost of living]] in Cincinnati is 8% below national average. The unemployment rate is also below the average at 4.2%.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/places/oh/cincinnati/|title=Cincinnati, OH|newspaper=Forbes|access-date=November 16, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019152714/https://www.forbes.com/places/oh/cincinnati/|archive-date=October 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSeveral Fortune 500 companies are headquartered in Cincinnati, such as [[Procter & Gamble]], [[The Kroger Company]], and [[Macy's, Inc.]]. [[General Electric]] has headquartered their Global Operations<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/money/2016/05/14/ges-big-addition-cincinnati-riverfront/83545678/|title=GE's big addition to the Cincinnati riverfront|newspaper=Cincinnati.com|access-date=December 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213145244/https://www.cincinnati.com/story/money/2016/05/14/ges-big-addition-cincinnati-riverfront/83545678/|archive-date=December 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Center in Cincinnati.  The Kroger Company employs 21,646 people locally, making it the largest employer in the city, and the University of Cincinnati is the second largest at 16,000.<ref>{{cite web|last=McCartney|first=Hannah|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/subscriber-only/2015/07/24/tri-state-employers.html|title=Greater Cincinnati's Largest Employers, 2015|date=July 24, 2015|work=[[Cincinnati Business Courier]]|accessdate=February 5, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170324020345/http://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/subscriber-only/2015/07/24/tri-state-employers.html|archive-date=March 24, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>[[File:Taste-of-Cincinnati-2009.jpg|thumb|upright|Approximately 1 million attend [[Taste of Cincinnati]] yearly, making it one of the largest street festivals in the United States.<ref>Taste of Cincinnati, [http://www.tasteofcincinnati.com/taste.aspx?menu_id=268&id=8780&ekmensel=3ed1b7ac_268_0_8780_2 About Taste] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601075429/http://www.tasteofcincinnati.com/taste.aspx?menu_id=268&id=8780&ekmensel=3ed1b7ac_268_0_8780_2 |date=June 1, 2010 }}. Accessed on December 27, 2009.</ref>]]\n\n===Food===\n====Restaurants====\n[[Frisch's]] Big Boy, [[Graeter's]] Ice Cream, [[Kroger]], [[LaRosa's]], [[Montgomery Inn]], [[Skyline Chili]], [[Gold Star Chili]], and [[United Dairy Farmers]] (UDF/Trauth) are Cincinnati eateries that sell their brand commodities in grocery markets and gas stations. Glier's [[goetta]] is produced in the Cincinnati area and is a popular local food.\n\nCincinnati has many{{quantify|date=July 2016}} gourmet restaurants. [[The Maisonette]] in Cincinnati was [[Mobil]] Travel Guide's longest-running [[Star (classification)|five-star]] restaurant in the United States, holding that distinction for 41 consecutive years until it closed in 2005. Its former head chef, [[Jean-Robert de Cavel]], has opened four new restaurants in the area since 2001.\n\nOne of the United States's oldest<ref name=\"esq13\">{{cite web | url= http://www.esquire.com/food-drink/bars/g1500/best-bars-in-america-2013/?slide=15 | title= The Best Bars in America | work= [[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] | date= June 2013 | accessdate= January 13, 2016 | author= Wondrich, David | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160124145732/http://www.esquire.com/food-drink/bars/g1500/best-bars-in-america-2013/?slide=15 | archive-date= January 24, 2016 | url-status= live }}</ref> and most celebrated<ref name=\"ARNOLDSAWARDS\">{{cite web | url= http://arnoldsbarandgrill.com/awards.htm | title= Arnold's Website Awards Section | work= [[Arnold's Bar and Grill|Arnold's]] | access-date= April 29, 2016 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160410224945/http://arnoldsbarandgrill.com/awards.htm | archive-date= April 10, 2016 | url-status= live }}</ref> bars, [[Arnold's Bar and Grill]] in downtown Cincinnati has won awards from ''Esquire'' magazine's \"Best Bars in America\",<ref name=\"WCPO13\">{{cite web | url= http://www.wcpo.com/news/local-news/downtown-fixture-arnolds-bar-and-grill-voted-among-16-best-bars-in-america-by-esquire-magazine | title= Downtown fixture Arnold's Bar and Grill voted among '16 Best Bars in America' by Esquire Magazine | work= [[WCPO]] | date= May 27, 2013 | accessdate= January 13, 2016 | author= Weldon, Casey | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160602230301/http://www.wcpo.com/news/local-news/downtown-fixture-arnolds-bar-and-grill-voted-among-16-best-bars-in-america-by-esquire-magazine | archive-date= June 2, 2016 | url-status= dead }}</ref> [[Thrillist]]'s \"Most Iconic Bar in Ohio\",<ref name=\"thrillist15\">{{cite web | url= https://www.thrillist.com/drink/nation/the-most-iconic-bar-in-every-state | title= THE MOST ICONIC BAR IN EVERY STATE (AND DC) | work= [[Thrillist]] | date= April 8, 2015 | accessdate= January 13, 2016 | author= Breslour, Lee | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160124145733/https://www.thrillist.com/drink/nation/the-most-iconic-bar-in-every-state | archive-date= January 24, 2016 | url-status= live }}</ref> [[The Daily Meal]]'s \"150 Best bars in America\"<ref name=\"TheDailyMeal15\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/entertainment/2015/04/23/daily-meal-puts-arnolds-best-bars-america/26248217/ | title=THE 150 BEST BARS IN AMERICA | work=[[The Daily Meal]] | date=April 23, 2015 | accessdate=April 29, 2016 | author=Steigerwald, Shauna | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714151220/https://www.cincinnati.com/story/entertainment/2015/04/23/daily-meal-puts-arnolds-best-bars-america/26248217/ | archive-date=July 14, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Serious Eats|Seriouseats.com]]'s \"The Cincinnati 10\".<ref name=\"Serious Eats 16\">{{cite web | url= http://www.seriouseats.com/where-to-eat-in-cincinnati | title= Serious Eats's The Cincinnati 10 | work= [[Serious Eats]] | date= February 29, 2016 | accessdate= April 29, 2016 | author= Pandolfi, Keith | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160509225201/http://www.seriouseats.com/where-to-eat-in-cincinnati | archive-date= May 9, 2016 | url-status= live }}</ref> \u201cIf Arnold\u2019s were in New York, San Francisco, Chicago, or Boston\u2014somewhere, in short, that people actually visit\u2014it would be world-famous,\u201d wrote David Wondrich.<ref name=\"wondrich quote\">{{cite web |title=Arnold's Way |url=http://cincymagazine.com/Main/Articles/Arnolds_Way_4043.aspx |publisher=Cincy Magazine |accessdate=10 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408054252/http://cincymagazine.com/Main/Articles/Arnolds_Way_4043.aspx |archive-date=April 8, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Cincinnati chili====\n{{Main|Cincinnati chili}}\n[[Cincinnati chili]], a spiced sauce served over noodles, usually topped with cheese and often with diced onions and/or beans, is the area's \"best-known regional food.\"<ref name=\"wcpo1508\">{{cite web | url= http://www.wcpo.com/news/insider/how-skyline-chili-became-a-cincinnati-icon | title= How Skyline Chili became a Cincinnati icon | publisher= [[WCPO-TV]] | date= August 27, 2015 | accessdate= August 29, 2015 | author= Coleman, Brent | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150829022545/http://www.wcpo.com/news/insider/how-skyline-chili-became-a-cincinnati-icon | archivedate= August 29, 2015 | df= mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"500things\">{{cite book | title= 500 Things to Eat Before it's Too Late:and the Very Best Places to Eat Them | author= Stern, Jane and Michael | year= 2009 | page= 244| author-link= Jane and Michael Stern }}</ref> A variety of recipes are served by respective parlors, including [[Skyline Chili]], [[Gold Star Chili]], and [[Dixie Chili and Deli]], plus independent chili parlors including [[Camp Washington Chili]], Empress Chili and Moonlight Chili.<ref name=\"woellert\">{{cite book | url= https://books.google.com/books?id=B6mh0iOdtWYC&pg=PA10 | title= The Authentic History of Cincinnati Chili | publisher= The History Press | last= Woellert | first= Dann | year= 2013 | isbn= 978-1-60949-992-1 | access-date= October 16, 2015 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160114110730/https://books.google.com/books?id=B6mh0iOdtWYC&pg=PA10 | archive-date= January 14, 2016 | url-status= live }}</ref> Cincinnati has been called July 2016 the \"Chili Capital of America\" and \"of the World\" because it has more chili restaurants per capita than any other city in the United States or in the world.<ref>MSN, [http://cityguides.msn.com/articles/article.aspx?cp-documentid=19546727 Food Capitals of America] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091009042105/http://cityguides.msn.com/articles/article.aspx?cp-documentid=19546727 |date=October 9, 2009 }}. Accessed on July 23, 2009.</ref>\n\n====Goetta====\n{{Main|Goetta}}\n[[Goetta]] is a meat-and-grain [[sausage]] or mush<ref name=\"citybeat18\">{{cite news |title=Seven Innovative Takes on Cincinnati Goetta to Change Your Mind About the Meat |url=https://www.citybeat.com/food-drink/eats-feature/article/21016807/seven-innovative-takes-on-beloved-cincinnati-goetta |accessdate=27 October 2018 |work=City Beat |date=7 Aug 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027232015/https://www.citybeat.com/food-drink/eats-feature/article/21016807/seven-innovative-takes-on-beloved-cincinnati-goetta |archive-date=October 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> of German inspiration. It is primarily composed of [[ground meat]] (pork, or pork and beef), [[steel-cut oats|pin-head oats]] and spices.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Sh4DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA144| title=Are You Ready For Cincinnati? | publisher=Cincinnati Magazine | work=Cincinnati USA City Guide | year=2007 | accessdate=2013-05-06 | author=Smith, Steve| page=144|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\n===Dialect===\n{{Wiktionary category|category=Cincinnati English}}\n\nThe citizens of Cincinnati speak in a [[General American]] dialect.  Unlike the rest of the Midwest, Southwest Ohio shares some aspects of its vowel system with [[New Jersey English dialects#North Jersey English|northern New Jersey English]].<ref name=\"Labov 2006\">{{cite book|title= The Atlas of North American English: Phonetics, Phonology, and Sound Change|volume= 1|first1= William|last1= Labov|authorlink1= William Labov|first2= Sharon|last2= Ash|first3= Charles|last3= Boberg|publisher= [[Walter de Gruyter]]|year= 2006|page= 276|isbn= 978-3110167467|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=qa4-dFqi6iMC&pg=PA136|access-date= November 13, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161204032952/https://books.google.com/books?id=qa4-dFqi6iMC&pg=PA136|archive-date= December 4, 2016|url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"Labov 2011\">{{cite book|title= Principles of Linguistic Change: Cognitive and Cultural Factors|first= William|last= Labov|location= New York City|publisher= [[John Wiley & Sons]]|date= July 5, 2011|at= 15.6.3|isbn= 978-1444351460|url= https://books.google.com/books?id=uwMTUk4g2IoC&pg=PT371|access-date= November 13, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161204022723/https://books.google.com/books?id=uwMTUk4g2IoC&pg=PT371|archive-date= December 4, 2016|url-status= live}}</ref> Cincinnatians allegedly over-pronounce \"O\" so the affect comes to be heard with a rounded \"w\", perhaps from living on the Ohio whose four-letter name includes two \"o\"s.  Most of the distinctive local features among speakers float as Midland American.<ref name=\"Boberg\">{{cite journal|title= Short-a in Cincinnati: A Change in Progress|first1= Charles|last1= Boberg|first2= Stephanie M.|last2= Strassel|journal= [[Journal of English Linguistics]]|date= June 2000|volume= 28|issue= 2|pages= 108\u2013126|doi= 10.1177/00754240022004929}}</ref> There is also some influence from the [[Southern American English|Southern American]] dialect found in Kentucky.<ref name=\"Ash\">{{cite book|chapter= The North American Midland as a dialect area|first= Sharon|last= Ash|title= Language Variation and Change in the American Midland: A New Look at 'Heartland' English|editor-first1= Thomas Edward|editor-last1= Murray|editor-first2= Beth Lee|editor-last2= Simon|location= Amsterdam|publisher= [[John Benjamins Publishing Company]]|date= January 1, 2006|page= 55|isbn= 978-90-272-4896-1|chapter-url= https://books.google.com/books?id=WxTrasumR18C&pg=PA294}}</ref> A touch of northern German is audible in the local vernacular: some residents use the word ''[[wikt:please#Etymology 3|please]]'' when asking a speaker to repeat a statement. This usage is taken from the German practice, when ''bitte'' (a shortening of the formal, \"Wie bitte?\" or \"How please?\" rendered word-for-word from German into English), was used as shorthand for asking someone to repeat.<ref>{{cite web\n|title= UC Idioms and Jargon\n|url= http://www.uc.edu/ucomm/resources/stylebook/idioms_jargon.html\n|publisher= [[University of Cincinnati]]\n|accessdate= February 13, 2014\n|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140221174125/http://www.uc.edu/ucomm/resources/stylebook/idioms_jargon.html\n|archive-date= February 21, 2014\n|url-status= live\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal\n|title= How To: Speak Cincinnatiese\n|first= Linda\n|last= Vaccariello\n|journal= [[Cincinnati (magazine)|Cincinnati]]\n|date= January 21, 2014\n|accessdate= December 19, 2014\n|url= http://www.cincinnatimagazine.com/article/how-to-speak-cincinnatiese/\n|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141219133853/http://www.cincinnatimagazine.com/article/how-to-speak-cincinnatiese/\n|archive-date= December 19, 2014\n|url-status= live\n}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Main|Demographics of Cincinnati}}\n{{US Census population\n|1800= 850\n|1810= 2540\n|1820= 9642\n|1830= 24831\n|1840= 46338\n|1850= 115435\n|1860= 161044\n|1870= 216239\n|1880= 255139\n|1890= 296908\n|1900= 325902\n|1910= 363591\n|1920= 401247\n|1930= 451160\n|1940= 455610\n|1950= 503998\n|1960= 502550\n|1970= 452525\n|1980= 385460\n|1990= 364040\n|2000= 331285\n|2010= 296945\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=302605\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|footnote=<ref name=\"wwwcensusgov\"/> Population 1810\u20131970.<ref name=\"The United States Census Bureau\"/><br />Population 1980\u20132000.<ref>{{cite web|publisher= The United States Census Bureau|url= https://www.census.gov/population/censusdata/c1008090pc.txt|title= 1980\u20131990 Population of Places With 100,000 or More Inhabitants|accessdate= July 29, 2007|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070808221022/http://www.census.gov/population/censusdata/c1008090pc.txt|archive-date= August 8, 2007|url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher= citypopulation.de|url= http://www.citypopulation.de/USA-Ohio.html|title= 2009 Estimates for Ohio Cities|accessdate= February 26, 2010|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190605143659/http://www.citypopulation.de/USA-Ohio.html|archive-date= June 5, 2019|url-status= live}}</ref><br />Population 2010.<ref>{{cite web|publisher= The United States Census Bureau|url= https://www.census.gov/newsroom/releases/archives/2010_census/cb11-cn72.html|title= U.S. Census Bureau Delivers Ohio's 2010 Census Population Totals, Including First Look at Race and Hispanic Origin Data for Legislative Redistricting|accessdate= March 9, 2011|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110312225853/http://www.census.gov/newsroom/releases/archives/2010_census/cb11-cn72.html|archive-date= March 12, 2011|url-status= live}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n|-\n! Demographic profile !! 2010<ref>{{cite web |url= http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/39/3915000.html |title= Cincinnati (city), Ohio |work= State & County QuickFacts |publisher= U.S. Census Bureau |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150524080818/http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/39/3915000.html |archivedate= May 24, 2015 |df= mdy-all |access-date= May 17, 2015 }}</ref> \n!2000<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/planning/linkservid/B6986A16-90FD-0DDE-CE3F0F7DE86023CB/showMeta/0/|archive-url= https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20171018195153/http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/planning/linkservid/B6986A16-90FD-0DDE-CE3F0F7DE86023CB/showMeta/0/|url-status= dead|archive-date= October 18, 2017|title= Cincinnati Population: Race, Age by Statistical Neighborhoods Census 2000|website= www.cincinnati-oh.gov|df= mdy-all}}</ref>!! 1990<ref name=\"pop\"/> !! 1970<ref name=\"pop\"/>  !! 1950<ref name=\"pop\"/> \n|-\n| [[White American|White]] || 49.3% \n|53.0%|| 60.5% || 71.9% || 84.4%\n|-\n|&nbsp;\u2014[[Non-Hispanic whites|Non-Hispanic]] || 48.1% \n|51.7%|| 60.2% || 71.4%<ref name=\"fifteen\">From 15% sample</ref> || n/a\n|-\n| [[African American|Black or African American]] || 44.8% \n|42.9%|| 37.9% || 27.6% || 15.5% \n|-\n| [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Hispanic or Latino]] (of any race) || 2.8% \n|1.3%|| 0.7% || 0.6% || n/a\n|-\n| [[Asian American|Asian]] || 1.8% \n|1.5%|| 1.1% || 0.2% || 0.1%\n|}\n\nIn 1950, Cincinnati reached its peak population of over 503,000 residents; it has lost population in every census-count since that time. In the late-20th century industrial restructuring caused a loss of jobs. The Census Bureau's 2006 estimates put the population at 332,252, representing a small increase from 331,310 in 2005.<ref name=\"popest\">{{cite web|url= https://www.census.gov/popest/cities/files/SUB-EST2006_39.csv |title= Subcounty population estimates: Ohio 2000\u20132006 |format= [[comma-separated values|CSV]] |publisher= [[United States Census Bureau]], Population Division |date= June 28, 2007 |accessdate= May 28, 2008 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080420141502/http://www.census.gov/popest/cities/files/SUB-EST2006_39.csv |archivedate= April 20, 2008 }}</ref> The city had officially challenged the original census numbers.  Mayor [[Mark Mallory]] repeatedly argued that the city's population was 378,259 after a drill-down study was performed by an independent, non-profit group based in Washington, D.C.<ref name=\"Enquirer Korte\">{{cite news|url= http://news.enquirer.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070627/NEWS01/706270362/1056/COL02 |title= Mayor: Census count low again |first= Gregory |last= Korte |work= The Cincinnati Enquirer |date= June 27, 2007 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://archive.today/20120714031853/http://news.enquirer.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070627/NEWS01/706270362/1056/COL02 |archivedate= July 14, 2012 }}</ref>\n[[File:Race and ethnicity 2010- Cincinnati (5560448832).png|thumb|left |Map of racial distribution in Cincinnati, 2010 U.S. Census. Each dot is 25 people: <span style=\"color:#f00;\">'''White'''</span>, <span style=\"color:#00f;\">'''Black'''</span>, <span style=\"color:#00ff80\">'''Asian'''</span>, <span style=\"color:#ff8000\">'''Hispanic'''</span> or '''Other''' (yellow)]]\n\nAs of the U.S. Census Bureau's July 2018 estimate, the population stood at 302,601, down nearly 5,000 from 2006. The Census Bureau count is officially conducted every new decade. All other population numbers for [[United States|American]] cities released between the official census count are just estimates, which may not be accurate, whether the population shows growth or decline on those estimates.\n\nAs of the official 2010 census, the racial demographics for the city of Cincinnati were: 49.3% white (48.1% non-Hispanic white), 44.8% black or African-American, 0.3% American Indian or Alaskan Native, 1.8% Asian, 0.1% Hawaiian or Pacific Islander, 2.5% two or more races, and 2.8% Hispanic (of any race).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/39/3915000.html|title= Cincinnati (city) QuickFacts from the US Census Bureau|work=census.gov|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150524080818/http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/39/3915000.html|archivedate= May 24, 2015|df= mdy-all|access-date=May 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs of the 2000 census, the Cincinnati-[[Middletown, Ohio|Middletown]]\u2212[[Wilmington, Ohio|Wilmington]] [[Metropolitan Statistical Area]] had a population of 2,155,137 people, making it the 24th-largest metropolitan statistical area in the country. It includes the [[Ohio]] counties of [[Hamilton County, Ohio|Hamilton]], [[Butler County, Ohio|Butler]], [[Warren County, Ohio|Warren]], [[Clermont County, Ohio|Clermont]], Clinton and [[Brown County, Ohio|Brown]], as well as the [[Kentucky]] counties of [[Boone County, Kentucky|Boone]], [[Bracken County, Kentucky|Bracken]], [[Campbell County, Kentucky|Campbell]], [[Gallatin County, Kentucky|Gallatin]], [[Grant County, Kentucky|Grant]], [[Kenton County, Kentucky|Kenton]], and [[Pendleton County, Kentucky|Pendleton]], and the [[Indiana]] counties of [[Dearborn County, Indiana|Dearborn]], [[Franklin County, Indiana|Franklin]], and [[Ohio County, Indiana|Ohio]].\n\n==Cityscape and climate==\n{{Main|Cityscape of Cincinnati}}\n[[File:Cincinnati aerial at night 2017.jpg|thumb|upright=0.85|Aerial view of Cincinnati and Northern Kentucky at twilight]]\nThe city is undergoing significant changes due to [[The cityscape of Cincinnati, Ohio#New development projects|new development]] and private investment.  This includes buildings of the long-stalled [[The Banks|Banks project]] that includes apartments, retail, restaurants, and offices, which will stretch from [[Great American Ball Park]] to [[Paul Brown Stadium]]. Phase 1A is already complete and 100 percent occupied as of early 2013. Smale Riverfront Park is being developed along with The Banks, and is Cincinnati's newest park.  Nearly $3.5&nbsp;billion have been invested in the urban core of Cincinnati (including Northern Kentucky). Much of this development has been undertaken by [[3CDC]].  The [[Cincinnati Bell Connector]] began in September 2016.<ref name=\"WVXU-2016sep9\">{{cite news |last=Rinehart |first=Bill |date=September 9, 2016 |title=Cincinnati's Streetcar Is Open For Business |url=http://wvxu.org/post/cincinnatis-streetcar-open-business |publisher=[[WVXU]] |accessdate=September 10, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910011209/http://wvxu.org/post/cincinnatis-streetcar-open-business |archive-date=September 10, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"cinc-enq-2016sep9\">{{cite news|last1=Coolidge|first1=Sharon|last2=Tweh|first2=Bowdeya|last3=Williams|first3=Jason|title=It's a go: Streetcar finally opens|newspaper=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]|date=September 9, 2016|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/politics/2016/09/09/updates-streetcar-opening-day/90116412/|accessdate=September 10, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190202034403/https://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/politics/2016/09/09/updates-streetcar-opening-day/90116412/|archive-date=February 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:Geographic regions ohio.svg|thumb|upright|right|Cincinnati is in the bluegrass region of [[Ohio]].]]\nCincinnati is midway by river between the cities of [[Pittsburgh]], Pennsylvania and [[Cairo, Illinois]].  The downtown lies near the mouth of the [[Licking River (Kentucky)|Licking]], a confluence where the first settlement occurred.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eJxABLtxX60C&pg=PA13| title=Centennial History of Cincinnati and Representative Citizens, Volume 1 | publisher=Biographical Publishing Company | year=1904 | accessdate=May 22, 2013 | author=Charles Theodore Greve | page=13}}</ref> [[Greater Cincinnati]] spans southern Ohio and Indiana, and northern Kentucky; the [[United States Census Bureau|census bureau]] has measured the city proper at {{convert|79.54|sqmi|km2|2}}, of which {{convert|77.94|sqmi|km2|2}} are land and {{convert|1.60|sqmi|km2|2}} are water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010 |url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] |accessdate=January 6, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/64vfLAeJ2?url=http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt |archivedate=January 24, 2012 |df=mdy }}</ref> The city spreads over a number of hills, bluffs, and low ridges overlooking the Ohio in the [[Bluegrass region]] of the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=Physiographic Regions of Ohio|url=http://www.dnr.state.oh.us/portals/10/pdf/physio.pdf|publisher=Ohio Department of Natural Resources, Division of Geological Survey|author=Ohio Division of Geological Survey|year=1998|accessdate=February 13, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528185532/http://www.dnr.state.oh.us/Portals/10/pdf/physio.pdf|archivedate=May 28, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The tristate is geographically located within the [[Midwest]] and is on the far northern of the [[Upland South]].\n\nThree municipalities are enveloped by the city:  [[Norwood, Ohio|Norwood]], [[Elmwood Place, Ohio|Elmwood Place]], and [[Saint Bernard, Ohio|Saint Bernard]]. Norwood is a business and industrial city, while Elmwood Place and Saint Bernard are small, primarily residential, villages. Cincinnati does not have an exclave, but the city government does own several properties outside the corporation limits: [[French Park (Amberley, Ohio)|French Park]] in [[Amberley, Ohio|Amberley Village]], the disused runway at the former [[Cincinnati\u2013Blue Ash Airport|Blue Ash Airport]] in [[Blue Ash, Ohio|Blue Ash]], and the {{convert|337|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[Cincinnati, New Orleans and Texas Pacific Railway|Cincinnati Southern Railway]], which runs between Cincinnati and [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]].[[File:Downtown Cincy.jpg|center|thumb|upright=2.75|Downtown Cincinnati]]\n\n===Landscape===\n{{See also|List of tallest buildings in Cincinnati}}\nCincinnati is home to numerous embankments that are noteworthy due to their architectural characteristics or historic associations, as well as the [[Carew Tower]], the Scripps Center, the [[Ingalls Building]], [[Cincinnati Union Terminal]], and the [[Isaac M. Wise Temple]].<ref>wisetemple.org</ref>\n\n[[Great American Insurance Building at Queen City Square|Queen City Square]] opened in January 2011. The building is the tallest in Cincinnati (surpassing the Carew Tower), and is the third tallest in Ohio, reaching a height of 665 feet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.enquirer.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071221/BIZ01/712210351|title=Sights in Cincinnati, Ohio| archiveurl=https://archive.today/20071230101731/http://news.enquirer.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071221/BIZ01/712210351|archivedate=December 30, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe mile-long [[Cincinnati Skywalk]], completed in 1997, was shortened to bring more commerce, yet remains the viable way to walk downtown during poor weather.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/blog/2012/02/the-story-behind-cincinnatis-slowly.html?page=all|title = The story behind Cincinnati's slowly disappearing skywalk system|date = February 24, 2012|accessdate = |website = Cincinnati Business Courier|publisher = |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150402163826/http://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/blog/2012/02/the-story-behind-cincinnatis-slowly.html?page=all|archive-date = April 2, 2015|url-status = live}}</ref> The [[Cincinnati Zoo & Botanical Garden]] in [[Avondale, Cincinnati|Avondale]] is the second oldest zoo in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cincinnatizoo.org/about-us/history-and-vision/|title=History, Mission and Vision \u2013 The Cincinnati Zoo & Botanical Garden|publisher=|access-date=July 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110502052422/http://cincinnatizoo.org/about-us/history-and-vision/|archive-date=May 2, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"160px\">\nFile:Fountain Square.jpg|Macy's Jazz Festival, held in Fountain Square\nFile:PNC Tower.jpg|The [[PNC Tower]], with the [[Carew Tower]] in the background\n</gallery>\n\n===Waterscape===\n[[File:Flood in East end of Cincinnati - 1913 (LOC).jpg|left|thumb|upright=0.85|Cincinnati's [[East End, Cincinnati|East End]] neighborhood during the [[Great Flood of 1913]]]]\n\n[[Downtown Cincinnati]] towers about [[Fountain Square, Cincinnati|Fountain Square]], the public square and event locale. Fountain Square was renovated in 2006.<ref>The Fountain. 2016. {{cite web |url=https://myfountainsquare.com/history/|title=Fountain Square|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref> Cincinnati rests along {{convert|22|mi}} of riverfront about northern banks of the Ohio, stretching from [[California, Cincinnati|California]] to [[Sayler Park, Cincinnati|Sayler Park]], giving the mighty Ohio and its movements a prominent place in the life of the city.<ref>{{cite news|title=Odds & Ends: Riverfront plan, food and disease, easy governing|department=Editorial|work=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|date=November 4, 1981|page=A6|url=http://cincinnati.newspapers.com/newspage/103177479/|url-access=subscription |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Frequent flooding has hampered the growth of Cincinnati's municipal airport at [[Cincinnati Municipal Lunken Airport|Lunken Field]] and the [[Coney Island (Cincinnati, Ohio)|Coney Island]] amusement park.<ref>{{cite web|title=History |publisher=[[Coney Island (Cincinnati, Ohio)|Coney Island]] |accessdate=October 20, 2015 |url=http://coneyislandpark.com/history |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151009055225/http://coneyislandpark.com/history |archivedate=October 9, 2015 }}</ref> Downtown Cincinnati is protected from flooding by the Serpentine Wall at [[Sawyer Point Park & Yeatman's Cove|Yeatman's Cove]] and another flood wall built into [[Fort Washington Way]].<ref name=\"Enquirer Pilcher expands\">{{cite news|title=Flood expands, but impact not yet as bad as in past|first=James|last=Pilcher|work=The Cincinnati Enquirer|publisher=Gannett Company|date=March 14, 2015|accessdate=October 20, 2015|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/2015/03/14/flood-expands-impact-yet-bad-past/24774885/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124145733/http://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/2015/03/14/flood-expands-impact-yet-bad-past/24774885/|archive-date=January 24, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Parts of Cincinnati also experience flooding from the [[Little Miami River]] and [[Mill Creek (Ohio)|Mill Creek]].\n\nSince April 1, 1922, the Ohio [[flood stage]] at Cincinnati has officially been set at {{convert|52|ft}}, as measured from the [[John A. Roebling Suspension Bridge]]. At this depth, the [[pumping station]] at the mouth of Mill Creek is activated.<ref name=\"Post Van Sant\">{{cite news|title=Flooding by the Numbers|first=Rick|last=Van Sant|work=[[The Cincinnati Post]]|publisher=[[E. W. Scripps Company]]|date=January 23, 1996|accessdate=October 20, 2015|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-72845614.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124145733/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-72845614.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 24, 2016|url-access=subscription|via=HighBeam Research}}</ref><ref name=\"Banks history\">{{cite web|title=History of Riverfront Development|publisher=[[The Banks]] Public Partnership|accessdate=October 20, 2015|url=http://www.thebankspublicpartnership.com/history|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160124145734/http://www.thebankspublicpartnership.com/history|archive-date=January 24, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> From 1873 to 1898, the flood stage was {{convert|45|ft}}. From 1899 to March 31, 1922, it was {{convert|50|ft}}.<ref name=\"Banks history\" /> The Ohio reached its lowest level, less than {{convert|2|ft}}, in 1881; conversely, its all-time [[high water mark]] is {{convert|79|ft|11+7/8|in}}, having crested January 26, 1937.<ref name=\"Post Van Sant\" /><ref name=\"Singer\">{{cite book|title=Cincinnati on the Go: History of Mass Transit|first=Allen J.|last=Singer|series=Images of America|location=Charleston, South Carolina|publisher=[[Arcadia Publishing]]|date=October 20, 2004|page=24|isbn=9781439615119|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AZ1fC_nxmYMC&pg=PT24|via=Google Books|access-date=November 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161203222332/https://books.google.com/books?id=AZ1fC_nxmYMC&pg=PT24|archive-date=December 3, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Various parts of Cincinnati flood at different points: [[Riverbend Music Center]] in the California neighborhood floods at {{convert|42|ft}}, while Sayler Park floods at {{convert|71|ft}} and the Freeman Avenue flood gate closes at {{convert|75|ft}}.<ref name=\"Post Van Sant\" />\n\n===Climate===\nCincinnati is at the southern limit of the [[humid continental climate]] zone ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: ''Dfa''), bordering the [[humid subtropical climate]] zone.<ref>[//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/57/Climatemapusa2.PNG US Map of the K\u00f6ppen climate classification system]</ref> Summers are warm to hot and humid, with significant rainfall in each month and highs reaching {{convert|90|\u00b0F|0}} or above on 21 days per year, often with high dew points and humidity. July is the warmest month, with a daily average temperature of {{convert|75.9|\u00b0F|1}}.<ref name = \"NOAA txt\"/>\n\nWinters tend to be cold and snowy, with January, the coldest month, averaging at {{convert|30.8|\u00b0F|1}}.<ref name = \"NOAA txt\"/> Lows reach {{convert|0|\u00b0F|0}} on an average 2.6 nights yearly.<ref name = \"NOAA txt\"/> An average winter will see around {{convert|22.1|in|cm}} of snowfall, contributing to the yearly {{convert|42.5|in|sigfig=3}} of precipitation, with rainfall peaking in spring.<ref name = NOAA /> Extremes range from {{convert|\u221225|\u00b0F|0}} on January 18, 1977 up to {{convert|108|\u00b0F|0}} on July 21 and 22, 1934.<ref name = NWS /> Severe [[thunderstorms]] are common in the warmer months, and [[tornadoes]], while infrequent, are not unknown, with such events striking the Greater Cincinnati area most recently in 1974, 1999, 2012, and 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=National Weather Service: 5 tornadoes hit Tri-State on Wednesday|url=http://www.wcpo.com/news/local-news/hamilton-county/cincinnati/wednesdays-storms-leave-damage-scattered-around-tri-state|website=WCPO|accessdate=September 29, 2017|date=March 3, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929044808/http://www.wcpo.com/news/local-news/hamilton-county/cincinnati/wednesdays-storms-leave-damage-scattered-around-tri-state|archive-date=September 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{{Cincinnati weatherbox}}\n\n==Sports==\n{{Main|Sports in Cincinnati}}\n[[File:Downtown cincinnati 2010 kdh.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|View of downtown Cincinnati in 2010, showing city arenas]]\n[[File:Cincinnati Cyclones Game - US Bank Arena.jpg|thumb|A Cyclones home game at US Bank Arena]]\n\nCincinnati has three major league teams, seven minor league teams, five college institutions with sports teams, and seven major sports venues. Cincinnati's three major league teams are Major League Baseball's [[Cincinnati Reds|Reds]], who were named for America's first professional baseball team, the [[Cincinnati Red Stockings]];<ref>[http://www.redshistory.com/Timeline/1866-1875.htm 1866 to 1875] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080217030812/http://www.redshistory.com/Timeline/1866-1875.htm |date=February 17, 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.redshistory.com/Timeline/1876-1881.htm 1876 to 1881] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080420090148/http://www.redshistory.com/Timeline/1876-1881.htm |date=April 20, 2008 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.redshistory.com/Timeline/1882-1889.htm 1882 to 1889] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080419104122/http://www.redshistory.com/Timeline/1882-1889.htm |date=April 19, 2008 }}</ref>  the [[Cincinnati Bengals|Bengals]] of the [[National Football League]]; and [[FC Cincinnati]], promoted to [[Major League Soccer]] in 2019.\n\nOn Major League Baseball [[Opening Day]], Cincinnati has the distinction of holding the \"traditional opener\" in baseball each year, due to its baseball history. Children have been known to skip school on [[Opening Day]], and it is commonly thought of as a holiday.<ref name=\"Sarasota HT Opening Day\">{{cite news|title=Today, dads let kids skip school|work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]]|location=Sarasota, Florida|date=April 3, 2000|page=5C|accessdate=May 30, 2010|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1755&dat=20000403&id=LyAiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=u34EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6569,5394898|quote='We'd skip school,' [[Ken Griffey, Jr.|[Ken Griffey] Junior]] said Sunday, when asked for his favorite opening day memory. 'My son's skipping school on opening day. It's a tradition. Cincinnati expects that a lot of kids are not going to be there.'|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131208115155/http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1755&dat=20000403&id=LyAiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=u34EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6569,5394898|archive-date=December 8, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Flying Pig Marathon]] is a yearly event attracting many runners and so is the [[Western & Southern Open|Cincinnati Masters Western & Southern tennis tournament]].\n\nThe Cincinnati Reds have won five World Series titles and had one of the most successful baseball teams of all time in the mid-1970s, known as The Big Red Machine. The Bengals have made two Super Bowl appearances since its founding, in 1981 and 1988, but have yet to win a championship. As of 2016, the Bengals have the longest active playoff win drought (26 years) despite making five straight playoff appearances from 2011 to 2015. Whenever the Bengals and [[Carolina Panthers]] play against each other (an interconference matchup that occurs every four years), their games are dubbed the \"Queen City Bowl\", as [[Charlotte, North Carolina|Charlotte]], North Carolina, the home city of the Panthers, is also known as the Queen City.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mayors want 'Queen City' debate settled in Carolina-Cincy game |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=October 7, 2014 |accessdate=December 10, 2019 |url=https://www.si.com/mayors-fighting-Queen-City-nickname-Panthers-Bengals}}</ref> The Bengals enjoy strong rivalries with the [[Cleveland Browns]] and [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] (both of whom are also members of the [[AFC North]]).\n\nCincinnati is also home to two men's college basketball teams: The [[Cincinnati Bearcats]] and [[Xavier Musketeers]]. These two teams face off as one of college basketball's rivalries known as the [[Crosstown Shootout]]. In [[2011\u201312 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2011]], the rivalry game erupted in [[2011 Crosstown Shootout brawl|an on-court brawl]] at the end of the game that saw multiple suspensions follow. The Musketeers have made 10 of the last 11 [[NCAA]] tournaments while the Bearcats have made six consecutive appearances. Previously, the [[Cincinnati Royals]] competed in the [[National Basketball Association]] from 1957 to 1972; they are now known as the [[Sacramento Kings]].\n\n[[FC Cincinnati]] is a soccer team that plays in the [[Major League Soccer|MLS]]. FC Cincinnati made its home debut in the [[USL Championship|USL]] on April 9, 2016, before a crowd of more than 14,000 fans.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2016/04/18/monday-kickaround-andy-najar-acl-injury-mls-refs-nwsl-and-usl-crowds/|title=Monday kickaround: Andy Najar ACL injury, MLS refs, NWSL and USL crowds|publisher=|access-date=April 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508194308/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/soccer-insider/wp/2016/04/18/monday-kickaround-andy-najar-acl-injury-mls-refs-nwsl-and-usl-crowds/|archive-date=May 8, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> On their next home game vs [[Louisville City FC]], FC Cincinnati broke the all-time USL attendance record with a crowd of 20,497; on May 14, 2016, it broke its own record, bringing in an audience of 23,375 on its 1\u20130 victory against the [[Pittsburgh Riverhounds]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/sports/soccer/fc-cincinnati/2016/05/14/mclaughlins-goal-gives-fc-cincy-1-0-lead-half/84382158/|title=Another record crowd turns out to watch FC Cincy win|last=Brennan|first=Patrick|date=May 14, 2016|work=[[Cincinnati Enquirer]]|accessdate=October 7, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327102830/https://www.cincinnati.com/story/sports/soccer/fc-cincinnati/2016/05/14/mclaughlins-goal-gives-fc-cincy-1-0-lead-half/84382158/|archive-date=March 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> FC Cincinnati has since broken the USL attendance record on several additional occasions, and moved to [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS) for the 2019 season.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2018/05/29/fc-cincinnati-named-26th-mls-team-starting-play-2019 |title=Cincinnati awarded MLS expansion club, will start play in 2019 |publisher=Major League Soccer |date=May 29, 2018 |accessdate=May 31, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612112808/https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2018/05/29/fc-cincinnati-named-26th-mls-team-starting-play-2019 |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> FC Cincinnati was awarded an MLS bid on May 29, 2018, and will open a [[FC Cincinnati stadium|new stadium]] in the West End neighborhood just northwest of downtown by 2021.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2018/05/29/mls-expansion-cincinnati-team-don-garber |title=Cincinnati Follows Nashville With Winning MLS Expansion Bid in Growth to 28 Teams |last=Creditor |first=Avi |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |language=en |access-date=2019-12-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329230959/https://www.si.com/soccer/2018/05/29/mls-expansion-cincinnati-team-don-garber |archive-date=March 29, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe table below shows sports teams in the Cincinnati area that average more than 5,000 fans per game:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n|+ Cincinnati Teams (yearly attendance > 5,000)\n|-\n! Club\n! Sport\n! Founded\n! League\n! Venue\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" | {{tooltip|Avg|Average}} {{tooltip|attend|Attendance}}\n! Ref\n|-\n| [[Cincinnati Reds]]\n| Baseball\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1882\n| [[Major League Baseball]]\n| [[Great American Ball Park]]\n| align=center | 23,383\n| align=center |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/attendance/_/year/2016|title=2016 Major League Baseball Attendance|year=2016|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=June 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170719130212/http://www.espn.com/mlb/attendance/_/year/2016|archive-date=July 19, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati Bearcats]]\n| Football\n| align=center | 1885\n| [[NCAA Division I]]\n| [[Nippert Stadium]]\n| align=center | 33,871\n| align=center |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/football_records/Attendance/2016.pdf|title=2016 National College Football Attendance|date=April 19, 2017|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|accessdate=June 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605041022/http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/football_records/Attendance/2016.pdf|archive-date=June 5, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Cincinnati Bearcats men's basketball|Cincinnati Bearcats]]\n| Basketball\n| align=center | 1901\n| [[NCAA Division I]]\n| [[Fifth Third Arena]]\n| align=center | 9,415\n| align=center |<ref name=\"2016NCAAMBAttendance\"/>\n|-\n| [[Xavier Musketeers men's basketball|Xavier Musketeers]]\n| [[Basketball]]\n| align=center | 1920\n| [[NCAA Division I]]\n| [[Cintas Center]]\n| align=center | 10,281\n| align=center |<ref name=\"2016NCAAMBAttendance\">{{cite web|url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/m_basketball_RB/Reports/attend/2016.pdf|title=2016 NCAA Men's Basketball Attendance|date=April 19, 2017|publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]|accessdate=June 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517015329/http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/m_basketball_RB/Reports/attend/2016.pdf|archive-date=May 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Cincinnati Bengals]]\n| [[American Football|Football]]\n| align=center | 1968\n| [[National Football League]]\n| [[Paul Brown Stadium]]\n| align=center | 60,511\n| align=center |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/attendance/_/year/2016|title=2016 NFL Football Attendance|year=2016|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=June 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629015831/http://www.espn.com/nfl/attendance/_/year/2016|archive-date=June 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[FC Cincinnati]]\n| Soccer\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2015\n| [[Major League Soccer]]\n| [[Nippert Stadium]]\n| align=center | 21,199\n| align=center |<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uslsoccer.com/news_article/show/703007|title=USL Total Attendance Soars by 33 Percent in 2016|date=September 28, 2016|publisher=[[United Soccer League]]|accessdate=June 28, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708210310/http://www.uslsoccer.com/news_article/show/703007|archive-date=July 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\nThe [[Cincinnati Masters]], an historic international men's and women's tennis tournament that is part of the [[ATP Tour Masters 1000]] Series and the [[WTA Premier tournaments|WTA Tour Premier 5]], was established in the city in 1899, and has been held in suburban [[Mason, Ohio|Mason]] since 1979.\n\nThe [[Cincinnati Sizzle]] is a women's minor professional tackle football team that plays in the [[Women's Football Alliance]]. The team was established in 2003, by former [[Cincinnati Bengals]] running back [[Ickey Woods]]. In 2016 the team claimed their first National Championship Title in the United States Women's Football League.\n\nThe [[Cincinnati Cyclones]] are a minor league AA-level professional hockey team playing in the [[ECHL]]. Founded in 1990, the team play at [[U.S. Bank Arena]]. They won the 2010 Kelly Cup Finals, their 2nd championship in three seasons. Cincinnati is also home to the first American based Australian rules football team, The Cincinnati Dockers, established in 1996.{{citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n==Police and fire services==\n{{See also|Crime in Cincinnati}}\n[[File:Cincinnati-Part-1-Crimes.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|[[Crime in Cincinnati]] increased after the 2001 riots, but has been decreasing since.]]\nThe city of Cincinnati's emergency services for fire, rescue, EMS, hazardous materials and explosive ordnance disposal is handled by the [[Cincinnati Fire Department]]. On April 1, 1853, the Cincinnati Fire Department became the first paid professional fire department in United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/fire/|title=Home \u2013 Fire|publisher=|accessdate=September 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129041340/http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/fire/|archive-date=November 29, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The Cincinnati Fire Department operates out of 26 fire stations, located throughout the city in 4 districts, each commanded by a district chief.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/fire/about-fire/|title=About The Cincinnati Fire Department \u2013 Fire|publisher=|accessdate=September 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025183031/http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/fire/about-fire/|archive-date=October 25, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"cincinnati-oh.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/fire/about-fire/operations-bureau/|title=Operations Bureau \u2013 Fire|work=cincinnati-oh.gov|access-date=November 24, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203081408/http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/fire/about-fire/operations-bureau/|archive-date=December 3, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfdhistory.com/index.php|title=Cincinnati Fire Department History and Photos|publisher=|accessdate=September 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129021402/http://www.cfdhistory.com/index.php|archive-date=November 29, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Cincinnati Fire Department is organized into 4 bureaus: Operations,<ref name=\"cincinnati-oh.gov\"/> Personnel and Training,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/fire/about-fire/personnel-training/|title=Personnel & Training \u2013 Fire|publisher=|accessdate=September 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129042054/http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/fire/about-fire/personnel-training/|archive-date=November 29, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Administrative Services,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/fire/about-fire/administrative-services/|title=Administrative Services Bureau \u2013 Fire|publisher=|accessdate=September 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129042052/http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/fire/about-fire/administrative-services/|archive-date=November 29, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and Fire Prevention.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/fire/about-fire/fire-prevention/|title=Fire Prevention Bureau \u2013 Fire|publisher=|accessdate=September 25, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141030084754/http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/fire/about-fire/fire-prevention/|archive-date=October 30, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Each bureau is commanded by an assistant chief, who in turn reports to the chief of department.\n\nThe [[Cincinnati Police Department]] has more than 1,000 sworn officers. Before the [[Cincinnati riots of 2001|riots of 2001]], Cincinnati's overall crime rate had been dropping steadily and by 1995 had reached its lowest point since 1992 but with more murders and rapes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-72823886.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110827024007/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-72823886.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 27, 2011|title=Crime Rate Dropping Slightly Murders, Rapes Up, Says New FBI Study|access-date=December 11, 2006}}</ref> After the riot, violent crime increased, but crime has been on the decline since.<ref>{{cite news|title=How to Fix a Broken Police Department|first=Alana|last=Semuels|date=May 29, 2015|work=Route Fifty|publisher=[[Atlantic Media]]|url=http://www.routefifty.com/2015/05/fix-broken-police-department/114028/|access-date=June 1, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905212959/http://www.routefifty.com/2015/05/fix-broken-police-department/114028/|archive-date=September 5, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2015, there were 71 homicides.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/2016/01/04/cincy-shootings-up-nearly-28-percent-2015/78262914/|title=Here's where city's shootings occur|publisher=|access-date=January 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310104313/http://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/2016/01/04/cincy-shootings-up-nearly-28-percent-2015/78262914/|archive-date=March 10, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Cincinnati Police Department was featured on [[TLC (TV channel)|TLC]]'s ''[[Police Women of Cincinnati]]'' and on A&E's reality show ''The First 48''.\n\n==Politics==\n[[File:Logo for the City of Cincinnati.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|The logo for the City of Cincinnati]]\n\nThe city proper operates with a [[Election Results, City Council of Cincinnati, Ohio|nine-member city council]], whose members are elected [[at-large]]. Prior to 1924, City council members were elected through a system of [[Ward (politics)|wards]].  The ward system was subject to corruption due to partisan rule. From the 1880s to the 1920s, the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] dominated city politics, with the [[political machine]] of  George B. [[George B. Cox|\"Boss\" Cox]] exerting control.\n\nA reform movement arose in 1923, led by another Republican, [[Murray Seasongood]]. Seasongood founded the Charter Committee, which used ballot initiatives in 1924 to replace the ward system with the current at-large system. They gained approval by voters for a [[council\u2013manager government]] form of government, in which the smaller council (compared to the number of previous ward representatives) hires a professional manager to operate daily affairs of the city.  From 1924 to 1957, the council was elected by [[proportional representation]] and single transfer voting (STV). Starting with Ashtabula in 1915, several major cities in Ohio adopted this electoral system, which had the practical effect of reducing ward boss and political party power. For that reason, such groups opposed it.\n\nIn an effort to overturn the charter that provided for proportional representation, opponents in 1957 fanned fears of black political power, at a time of increasing civil rights activism.<ref name=\"amy\">[https://www.mtholyoke.edu/acad/polit/damy/articles/Brief%20History%20of%20PR.htm Douglas J. Amy, \"A Brief History of Proportional Representation in the United States\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140916114636/https://www.mtholyoke.edu/acad/polit/damy/articles/Brief%20History%20of%20PR.htm |date=September 16, 2014 }}, revised version of \"The Forgotten History of the Single Transferable Vote in the United States\", in ''Representation'' 34, number 1 (Winter 1996/7), accessed March 30, 2015</ref> The PR/STV system had enabled minorities to enter local politics and gain seats on the city council more than they had before, in proportion to their share of the population. This made the government more representative of the residents of the city.<ref name=\"pr\">[https://www.mtholyoke.edu/acad/polit/damy/OrderDesk/barber.htm Kathleen L. Barber, ''PROPORTIONAL REPRESENTATION AND ELECTION REFORM IN OHIO'' (excerpt)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150502102136/https://www.mtholyoke.edu/acad/polit/damy/OrderDesk/barber.htm |date=May 2, 2015 }}, Columbus: Ohio State University Press, 1995, pp. Introduction</ref>  Overturning that charter, in 1957, all candidates had to run in a single race for the nine city council positions.  The top nine vote-getters were elected (the \"9-X system\"), which favored candidates who could appeal to the entire geographic area of the city and reach its residents with campaign materials. The mayor was elected by the council.  In 1977, 33-year-old [[Jerry Springer]], later a notable television talk show host, was chosen to serve one year as mayor.\n\nResidents continued to work to improve their system.{{Citation needed|date=August 2015}} To have their votes count more, starting in 1987, the top vote-getter in the city council election was automatically selected as mayor. Starting in 1999, the [[List of mayors of Cincinnati, Ohio|mayor]] was elected separately in a general at-large election for the first time. The city manager's role in government was reduced.{{Citation needed|date=August 2015}} These reforms were referred to as the \"[[Mayor-council government|strong mayor]]\" reforms, to make the publicate accountable to voters.  Cincinnati politics include the participation of the [[Charter Party of Cincinnati, Ohio|Charter Party]], the political party with the third-longest history of winning in local elections.{{Citation needed|date=August 2015}} On October 5, 2011, the Council became the first local government in the United States to adopt a resolution recognizing freedom from domestic violence as a fundamental human right.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://city-egov.cincinnati-oh.gov/Webtop/ws/council/public/child/Blob/33497.pdf?rpp=-10&m=2&w=doc_no%3D%27201101139%2|title=City of Cincinnati Council, Resolution No. 47-2011|last=|first=|date=October 5, 2011|website=|access-date=}}{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On January 30, 2017, Cincinnati's mayor declared the city a [[sanctuary city]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/politics/2017/01/30/cranley-announce-cincinnati-sanctuary-city/97240174/|title=Cincinnati now a 'sanctuary city.' What's that mean?|newspaper=Cincinnati.com|language=en|date=January 30, 2017|access-date=September 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831062419/https://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/politics/2017/01/30/cranley-announce-cincinnati-sanctuary-city/97240174/|archive-date=August 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Race relations===\n{{Main|Race relations of Cincinnati}}\n[[File:National underground railroad freedom center main entrance 2006.jpg|thumb|upright|right|The [[National Underground Railroad Freedom Center]] has exhibits on the [[Underground Railroad]].]]\n\nDue to its location on the Ohio River, Cincinnati was a border town in a free state, across from Kentucky, which was a slave state. Residents of Cincinnati played a major role in [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionism]]. Many [[fugitive slave]]s used the Ohio at Cincinnati to escape to the North. Cincinnati had numerous stations on the Underground Railroad, but there were also runaway slave catchers active in the city, who put escaping slaves at risk of recapture.\n\nGiven its southern Ohio location, Cincinnati had also attracted settlers from the Upper South, who traveled along the Ohio River into the territory. Tensions between abolitionists and slavery supporters broke out in repeated violence, with whites attacking blacks in 1829. Anti-abolitionists attacked blacks in the city in a wave of destruction that resulted in 1,200 blacks leaving the city and the country; they resettled in Canada.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/negroinourhisto01woodgoog|title=The Negro in Our History|authors=Carter G. Woodson, Charles Harris Wesley|publisher=Associated Publishers (digitized from original at University of Michigan Library)|page=[https://archive.org/details/negroinourhisto01woodgoog/page/n162 140]|year=1922|accessdate=October 1, 2013}}</ref> The riot and its refugees were topics of discussion throughout the country, and blacks organized the first Negro Convention in 1830 in [[Philadelphia]] to discuss these events.\n\nWhite riots against blacks took place again in Cincinnati in 1836 and 1842.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> In 1836, a mob of 700 pro-slavery men attacked black neighborhoods, as well as a press run by [[James M. Birney]], publisher of the anti-slavery weekly ''The Philanthropist''.<ref>[http://www.iath.virginia.edu/utc/abolitn/mobhp.html \"The Pro-Slavery Riot in Cincinnati\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080918235047/http://www.iath.virginia.edu/utc/abolitn/mobhp.html |date=September 18, 2008 }}, Abolitionism 1830\u20131850, ''Uncle Tom's Cabin and American Culture'', University of Virginia, 1998\u20132007, accessed January 14, 2009</ref> Tensions increased after congressional passage in 1850 of the [[Fugitive Slave Act]], which required cooperation by citizens in free states and increased penalties for failing to try to recapture escaped slaves.\n\n[[Levi Coffin]] made the Cincinnati area the center of his anti-slavery efforts in 1847.<ref>Levi Coffin, ''Reminiscences of Levi Coffin, the reputed president of the underground railroad: being a brief history of the labors of a lifetime in behalf of the slave, with the stories of numerous fugitives, who gained their freedom through his instrumentality, and many other incidents'', Cincinnati: Western Tract Society, University of Michigan Library</ref> [[Harriet Beecher Stowe]] lived in Cincinnati for a time, met escaped slaves, and used their stories as a basis for her novel ''[[Uncle Tom's Cabin]]'' (1852). The [[National Underground Railroad Freedom Center]], which opened in 2004 on the Cincinnati riverfront in the middle of \"[[The Banks]]\" area between [[Great American Ballpark]] and [[Paul Brown Stadium]], commemorates the volunteers who aided refugee slaves and their drive for freedom, as well as others who have been leaders for social justice.\n\n[[File:Findlay Market Cincinnati.JPG|thumb|left|upright=1.15|[[Findlay Market]], Ohio's oldest operating market]]\n\nLocated in a free state and attracting many European immigrants, Cincinnati has historically had a predominantly white population.<ref name=\"pop\"/> By 1940, the Census Bureau reported the city's population as 87.8 percent white and 12.2 percent black.<ref name=\"pop\">{{cite web|title=Ohio&nbsp;\u2013 Race and Hispanic Origin for Selected Cities and Other Places: Earliest Census to 1990 |publisher=U.S. Census Bureau |url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0076/twps0076.html |accessdate=April 16, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69hd5KAIE?url=http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0076/twps0076.html |archivedate=August 6, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn the second half of the 20th century, Cincinnati, along with other [[rust belt]] cities, underwent a vast demographic transformation. By the early 21st century, the city's population was 40% black. Predominantly white, working-class families who constituted the urban core during the European immigration boom in the 19th and early 20th centuries, moved to newly constructed suburbs before and after World War II. Blacks, fleeing the oppression of the [[Jim Crow]] South in hopes of better socioeconomic opportunity, had moved to these older city neighborhoods in their [[Great Migration (African American)|Great Migration]] to the industrial North. The downturn in industry in the late 20th century caused a loss of many jobs, leaving many people in poverty. In 1968, passage of national civil rights legislation had raised hopes for positive change, but the assassination of national leader [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] resulted in riots in many black neighborhoods in Cincinnati; unrest occurred in black communities in nearly every major U.S. city after King's murder.\n\nMore than three decades later, in April 2001, racially charged [[Cincinnati riots of 2001|riots]] occurred after police fatally shot a young unarmed black man, [[Cincinnati riots of 2001#Incident|Timothy Thomas]], during a foot pursuit to arrest him, mostly for outstanding traffic warrants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/unrest/|title=Cincinnati.Com \u2013 Your Key to the City|work=cincinnati.com|access-date=June 27, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100706105950/http://cincinnati.com/unrest/|archive-date=July 6, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> After the 2001 riots, the ACLU, Cincinnati Black United Front, the city and its police union agreed upon a community-oriented policing strategy. The agreement has been used as a model across the country for building relationships between police and local communities.<ref name=\"collaborative\">{{cite web|title=Ohio&nbsp;\u2013 2001 riots led to top-down change for Cincinnati police|publisher=USA Today|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2011-04-03-cincinnati-riots-anniversary_N.htm|accessdate=January 29, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150306044158/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/2011-04-03-cincinnati-riots-anniversary_N.htm|archive-date=March 6, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn July 19, 2015, [[Shooting of Samuel DuBose|Samuel DuBose]], an unarmed black motorist, was fatally shot by white University of Cincinnati Police Officer Ray Tensing after a routine traffic stop for a missing front license plate. The resulting legal proceedings in late 2016<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wlwt.com/article/everything-you-should-know-about-the-ray-tensing-murder-trial/7146075|title=Everything you should know about the Ray Tensing murder mistrial|last=Ferrell|first=Nikki|date=November 28, 2016|newspaper=WLWT|access-date=December 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202035118/http://www.wlwt.com/article/everything-you-should-know-about-the-ray-tensing-murder-trial/7146075|archive-date=December 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> have been a recurring focus of national news media.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/11/01/us/ray-tensing-trial/index.html|title=Ray Tensing trial explained: What to know|author=Max Blau|website=CNN|access-date=December 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202041534/http://www.cnn.com/2016/11/01/us/ray-tensing-trial/index.html|archive-date=December 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Several peaceful protests involving the [[Black Lives Matter]] movement have been carried out.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cincinnati.com/story/news/2016/11/12/protesters-demand-tensing-retrial/93719058/|title=Black Lives Matter finds allies to protest Tensing decision|newspaper=Cincinnati.com|access-date=December 1, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wlwt.com/article/black-lives-matter-holds-rally-on-uc-campus-for-sam-dubose/3556439|title=Black Lives Matter holds rally on UC campus for Sam Dubose|last=Hamrick|first=Brian|date=July 27, 2015|newspaper=WLWT|access-date=December 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202035531/http://www.wlwt.com/article/black-lives-matter-holds-rally-on-uc-campus-for-sam-dubose/3556439|archive-date=December 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Tensing was indicted on charges of murder and [[voluntary manslaughter]], but a November 2016 trial ended in [[Mistrial (law)|mistrial]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/11/12/us/cincinnati-ray-tensing-verdict/index.html|title=Mistrial in murder trial of Ex-University of Cincinnati cop|author=Ray Sanchez|website=CNN|access-date=December 1, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202100928/http://www.cnn.com/2016/11/12/us/cincinnati-ray-tensing-verdict/index.html|archive-date=December 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> after the jury became [[Hung jury|deadlocked]]. A retrial began in May 2017, which also ended in mistrial after deadlock. The prosecution then announced they did not plan to try Tensing a third time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wcpo.com/news/crime/prosecutor-joe-deters-decides-not-to-try-ray-tensing-third-time-in-killing-of-sam-dubose|website=WCPO|last=Noble|first=Greg|title=Prosecutor Joe Deters decides not to try Ray Tensing third time in killing of Sam DuBose|access-date=July 24, 2017|date=2017-07-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721235711/http://www.wcpo.com/news/crime/prosecutor-joe-deters-decides-not-to-try-ray-tensing-third-time-in-killing-of-sam-dubose|archive-date=July 21, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> The University of Cincinnati has [[Settlement (litigation)|settled]] with the DuBose family for $4.8&nbsp;million<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wcpo.com/news/local-news/hamilton-county/cincinnati/family-of-sam-dubose-settles-with-uc-for-48m-plus-free-tuition-for-12-children|title=Family of Sam DuBose settles with UC for $4.8M plus free tuition for 12 children|last=McKee|first=Marais Jacon-Duffy, Pat LaFleur, Tom|date=October 25, 2016|newspaper=WCPO|language=en-US|access-date=December 1, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202101219/http://www.wcpo.com/news/local-news/hamilton-county/cincinnati/family-of-sam-dubose-settles-with-uc-for-48m-plus-free-tuition-for-12-children|archivedate=December 2, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and free tuition for each of the 12 children.\n\n===Present officeholders===\nThe present Mayor of Cincinnati is [[John Cranley]]. The nine-member city council is composed of Vice Mayor [[Christopher Smitherman]] and Councilmembers [[Jan-Michele Lemon Kearney]]<ref>https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/ohio/articles/2020-03-14/ohio-newspaper-publisher-to-take-vacated-city-council-seat</ref>, [[David S. Mann|David Mann]], Amy Murray, [[Chris Seelbach (politician)|Chris Seelbach]], [[P.G. Sittenfeld]], [[Greg Landsman]], [[Jeff Pastor]], and Wendell Young.<ref>City of Cincinnati website, http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/council/council-members/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214095842/http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/council/council-members/ |date=December 14, 2013 }}</ref>  The city manager is Patrick Duhaney,<ref>[https://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/manager/ City Manager of Cincinnati], ''[[City of Cincinnati]]''</ref> and the manager maintains three assistant city managers.\n\n==Schools==\n{{Main|Education in Cincinnati}} \n[[File:050819 036 Univ Cincy.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|The [[University of Cincinnati]]'s McMicken Hall]]\n\nThe city has an extensive library system, both the city's public one and university facilities. [[The Public Library of Cincinnati and Hamilton County]] was the third-largest public library nationally in 1998.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.libraryspot.com/lists/listlargestlibs.htm | title = Nation's Largest Libraries | work = LibrarySpot | accessdate = October 21, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070529215517/http://www.libraryspot.com/lists/listlargestlibs.htm | archive-date = May 29, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[University of Cincinnati]], called Cincinnati or nicknamed UC, is a public university.  The University is renowned in architecture and engineering, [[liberal arts]], music, nursing, and [[social science]]. The [[Art Academy of Cincinnati]], nicknamed AAC was founded as the '''McMicken School of Design''' in 1869. The [[University of Cincinnati Medical Center]] is the leading institute for community health in Ohio.  The [[College Conservatory of Music]] taught [[Kathleen Battle]], [[Al Hirt]] and [[Faith Prince]].  The [[Cincinnati Public Schools]] (CPS) include sixteen high schools all with citywide acceptance.  CPS, third-largest school cluster by student population, was the biggest one to have an overall 'effective' rating from the State.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/pages/data/school-education/school-rankings/school-district-rankings.html|title=Ohio school district rankings|work=The Columbus Dispatch|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211100717/http://www.dispatch.com/content/pages/data/school-education/school-rankings/school-district-rankings.html|archivedate=February 11, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The district currently includes public [[Montessori method|Montessori school]]s, including the first public Montessori high school established in the United States, [[Clark Montessori High School|Clark Montessori]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://clark.cps-k12.org/ |title=Clark Montessori |publisher=Clark.cps-k12.org |date= |accessdate=October 1, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005000302/http://clark.cps-k12.org/ |archive-date=October 5, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Cincinnati Public Schools' top-rated school is [[Walnut Hills High School]], ranked 34th on the national list of best public schools by ''Newsweek''. Walnut Hills offers 28 [[Advanced Placement]] courses. Cincinnati is also home to the first Kindergarten \u2013 12th grade Arts School in the country, the [[School for Creative and Performing Arts]].  [[Cincinnati State]] is a small college that includes the Midwest Culinary School.  Also located in Cincinnati is [[Cincinnati Christian University]].  Five hundred years since [[the Reformation]] Cincinnati provided a global distinguished lecture marking the layout of books and research for stirred city goers<ref>{{cite web|url=https://libapps.libraries.uc.edu/liblog/2017/09/langsam-library-exhibit-marks-the-500th-anniversary-of-the-reformation/|title=Langsam Library Exhibit Marks the 500th Anniversary of the Reformation|publisher=The University of Cincinnati|accessdate=December 26, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171225044857/https://libapps.libraries.uc.edu/liblog/2017/09/langsam-library-exhibit-marks-the-500th-anniversary-of-the-reformation/|archive-date=December 25, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> and the [[Cincinnati Art Museum]] staff built ''Albrecht Durer:  The Age of Reformation and Renaissance'',<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.CincinnatiArtMuseum.Org/Durer//|title= Albrecht D\u00fcrer: The Age of Reformation and Renaissance|publisher= The Cincinnati Art Museum|accessdate= December 26, 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171227061916/http://www.cincinnatiartmuseum.org/Durer//|archive-date= December 27, 2017|url-status= live}}</ref> with more crafting by the University design, art, and architecture program given for the City.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://libapps.libraries.uc.edu/liblog/2017/11/albrecht-durer-a-reformation-era-artist-daap-library/|title= Albrecht D\u00fcrer: A Reformation-Era Artist @ DAAP Library|publisher= The University of Cincinnati|accessdate= December 26, 2017|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171227122005/https://libapps.libraries.uc.edu/liblog/2017/11/albrecht-durer-a-reformation-era-artist-daap-library/|archive-date= December 27, 2017|url-status= live}}</ref> Most of the work explores social ontology of the birth of mainline beliefs and propriety, woven with scripture and pamphlets which launched a widespread [[Religion in Europe|European]] grooming.\n\nThe Jewish community has several schools, including the all-girl RITSS (Regional Institute for Torah and Secular Studies) high school,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rabbihorowitz.com/PYes/SchoolDetails.cfm?School_ID=649|title=RabbiHorowitz.com|publisher=|access-date=January 20, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402105428/http://www.rabbihorowitz.com/PYes/SchoolDetails.cfm?School_ID=649|archive-date=April 2, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> and the all-boy Yeshivas Lubavitch High School.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ylcincinnati.com/sites/default/files/doc/YLCBrochure.pdf |title=Brochure |website=ylcincinnati.com |access-date=January 20, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121035116/http://www.ylcincinnati.com/sites/default/files/doc/YLCBrochure.pdf |archive-date=January 21, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Hebrew Union College]]- Jewish Institute of Religion (HUC-JIR), founded by Isaac Mayer Wise, is a seminary for training of Reform rabbis and others religious.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishcincinnati.com/ir_listing.html?ID=33307 |title=Jewish Federation of Cincinnati, Community Directory |publisher=Jewishcincinnati.com |date= |accessdate=October 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Xavier University (Cincinnati)|Xavier University]], one of three [[Roman Catholic]] colleges along with [[Chatfield College]] and [[Mount St. Joseph University]], was at one time affiliated with [[The Athenaeum of Ohio]], the seminary of the Cincinnati Archdiocese.  The Roman Catholic [[Archdiocese of Cincinnati]] operates 16 [[Diocese of Cincinnati#Schools|high schools]] in Cincinnati, ten of which are [[Single-sex school|single-sex]]. There are six all-female high schools<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lPj0H3b5JQgC&pg=PA112|title=A League of Their Own|author=Aiesha D Little|publisher=Cincinnati Magazine (Aug 2007)|quote=...girls get the extra leadership and academic push they need to get on to the path to success in college and in life... [[Mother of Mercy High School (Cincinnati, Ohio)|Mother of Mercy High School]]... [[Mount Notre Dame High School|Mt Notre Dame High School]]...  Notre Dame Academy... [[St. Ursula Academy (Cincinnati, Ohio)|St Ursula Academy]]... [[McAuley High School (Cincinnati, Ohio)|McAuley High School]]... [[Ursuline Academy (Cincinnati, Ohio)|Ursuline Academy of Cincinnati]]...|date=August 2007}}</ref> and four all-male high schools in the city, with additional schools in the metro areas.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lPj0H3b5JQgC&pg=PA113\n|publisher=Cincinnati Magazine (Aug 2007)\n|title=No Girls Allowed\n|author=Katherine L Sontag\n|quote=The all-male prep schools in the share similar traits-- faith-based service opportunities, strong sports programs, tradition, and lots of testosterone...[[Covington Catholic High School]]...[[Elder High School]]... [[La Salle High School (Cincinnati, Ohio)|La Salle High School]]... Archbishop [[Moeller High School]]...[[Father Stephen T. Badin High School|Stephen T Badin High School]]... [[St. Xavier High School (Cincinnati)|St Xavier High School]]|date=August 2007\n}}</ref>\n\n[[Antonelli College]], a career training school, is based in Cincinnati with several satellite campuses in [[Ohio]] and [[Mississippi]].\n\n==Theater and music==\n[[File:Photo Collage, USITT 2015.jpg|thumb|A photo collage of some of the views of the USITT Conference and Stage Expo in Cincinnati, 2015]]\nProfessional theatre has operated in Cincinnati since at least as early as the 1800s.{{Citation needed|date=August 2015}} Among the professional companies based in the city are [[Ensemble Theatre Cincinnati]], [[Cincinnati Shakespeare Company]], the [[Know Theatre of Cincinnati]], [[Stage First Cincinnati]], [[Cincinnati Public Theatre]], [[Cincinnati Opera]], [[The Performance Gallery]] and [[Clear Stage Cincinnati]]. The city is also home to [[Cincinnati Playhouse in the Park]], which hosts regional premieres, and the [[Aronoff Center]], which hosts touring Broadway shows each year via [[Broadway Across America]]. The city has community theatres, such as the [[Cincinnati Young People's Theatre]], the [[Showboat Majestic]] (which is the last surviving showboat in the United States and possibly{{original research inline|date=November 2014}} the world), and the [[Mariemont Players]].\n\nSince 2011, [[Cincinnati Opera]] and the [[University of Cincinnati College-Conservatory of Music]] have partnered to sponsor the [[Opera Fusion: New Works]] project. The [[Opera Fusion: New Works]] project acts as a program for composers or librettists to workshop an opera in a 10-day residency. This program is headed by the Director of Artistic Operations at Cincinnati Opera, Marcus K\u00fcchle, and the Head of Opera at [[University of Cincinnati \u2013 College-Conservatory of Music|CCM]], [[Robin Guarino]].\n\nMusic-related events include the [[Cincinnati May Festival]], [[Bunbury Music Festival]], and [[Cincinnati Bell/WEBN Riverfest]].  Cincinnati has hosted the World Choir Games with the catchy mantra \"Cincinnati, the City that Sings!\"\n\nIn 2015, Cincinnati held the USITT 2015 Conference and Stage Expo at the [[Duke Energy]] Convention Center, bringing 5,000+ students, university educators, theatrical designers and performers, and other personnel to the city.{{Citation needed|date=August 2015}} The USITT Conference is considered the main conference for Theatre, Opera, and Dance in the United States.{{Citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\n''[[A Rage in Harlem]]'' was filmed entirely in the Cincinnati neighborhood of Over the Rhine because of its similarity to 1950s Harlem. Movies that were filmed in part in Cincinnati include ''[[The Best Years of Our Lives]]'' (aerial footage early in the film), ''[[The Ides of March (2011 film)|Ides of March]]'', ''[[Fresh Horses (film)|Fresh Horses]]'', ''[[The Asphalt Jungle]]'' (the opening is shot from the [[Public Landing, Cincinnati|Public Landing]] and takes place in Cincinnati although only Boone County, Kentucky is mentioned), ''[[Rain Man]]'', ''[[Miles Ahead (film)|Miles Ahead]]'', ''[[Airborne (1993 film)|Airborne]]'', ''[[Grimm Reality]]'', ''[[Little Man Tate]]'', ''[[City of Hope (film)|City of Hope]]'', ''[[An Innocent Man (film)|An Innocent Man]]'', ''[[Tango & Cash]]'', ''[[A Mom for Christmas]]'', ''[[Lost in Yonkers (film)|Lost in Yonkers]]'', ''[[Summer Catch]]'', ''[[Artworks]]'', ''[[Dreamer (2005 film)|Dreamer]]'', ''[[Elizabethtown (film)|Elizabethtown]]'', ''[[Jimmy and Judy]]'', ''[[Eight Men Out]]'', ''[[Milk Money (film)|Milk Money]]'',''[[Traffic (2000 film)|Traffic]]'', ''[[The Pride of Jesse Hallam]]'', ''[[The Great Buck Howard]]'', ''[[In Too Deep (1999 film)|In Too Deep]]'', ''[[Seven Below]]'', ''[[Carol (film)|Carol]]'', ''[[The Public Eye (film)|Public Eye]]'', ''The Last Late Night'',<ref name=\"FilmCincinnati\">{{cite web|title=Shot Here|url=http://www.filmcincinnati.com/Shot_Here/|publisher=Greater Cincinnati & Northern Kentucky Film Commission|accessdate=February 13, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220065822/http://www.filmcincinnati.com/Shot_Here|archivedate=February 20, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and ''[[The Mighty]]''.<ref name=\"IMDb The Mighty\">{{IMDb title|0119670|The Mighty}}</ref> In addition, ''[[Wild Hogs]]'' is set, though not filmed, in Cincinnati.<ref name=\"Wild Hogs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wildaboutmovies.com/movies/WildHogsMovieTrailerPosterJohnTravoltaTimAllen.php|title=Wild About Moves|accessdate=October 21, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071018041138/http://www.wildaboutmovies.com/movies/WildHogsMovieTrailerPosterJohnTravoltaTimAllen.php|archive-date=October 18, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Shiny And The Spoon at the zoo.jpg|upright|thumb|left|Local folk band [[Shiny and the Spoon]] perform at the [[Cincinnati Zoo and Botanical Garden]].]]\n\nThe Cincinnati skyline was prominently featured in the opening and closing sequences of the [[CBS]]/ABC daytime drama ''[[The Edge of Night]]'' from its start in 1956 until 1980, when it was replaced by the Los Angeles skyline; the cityscape was the stand-in for the show's setting, Monticello. Procter & Gamble, the show's producer, is based in Cincinnati. The sitcom ''[[WKRP in Cincinnati]]'' and its sequel/spin-off ''[[The New WKRP in Cincinnati]]'' featured the city's skyline and other exterior shots in its credits, although was not filmed in Cincinnati. The city's skyline has also appeared in an [[April Fool's]] episode of ''[[The Drew Carey Show]]'', which was set in Carey's hometown of [[Cleveland]]. [[3 Doors Down]]'s music video \"It's Not My Time\" was filmed in Cincinnati, and features the skyline and Fountain Square. Also, ''[[Harry's Law]]'', the [[NBC]] legal dramedy created by [[David E. Kelley]] and starring [[Kathy Bates]], was set in Cincinnati.<ref>{{cite web|last=Campbell|first=Polly|title=Cincinnati will get more airtime on 'Harry's Law'|url=http://news.cincinnati.com/article/20110718/ENT11/107190316/Arnold-s-gets-starring-role-TV-show|publisher=The Cincinnati Enquirer|accessdate=July 18, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722145029/http://news.cincinnati.com/article/20110718/ENT11/107190316/Arnold-s-gets-starring-role-TV-show|archive-date=July 22, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCincinnati has given rise or been home to popular musicians and singers [[Kole Black]], [[Lonnie Mack]], [[Doris Day]], [[Odd Nosdam]], [[Dinah Shore]], [[Fats Waller]], [[Rosemary Clooney]], [[Bootsy Collins]], [[The Isley Brothers]], [[Merle Travis]], [[Hank Ballard]], [[Otis Williams]], [[Mood (band)|Mood]], [[Midnight Star]], [[Calloway (band)|Calloway]], [[The Afghan Whigs]], [[Over the Rhine (band)|Over the Rhine]], [[Blessid Union of Souls]], [[Freddie Meyer]], [[98 Degrees]], [[The Greenhornes]], [[The Deele]], [[Enduser]], [[Heartless Bastards]], [[The Dopamines]], [[Adrian Belew]], [[The National (band)|The National]], [[Foxy Shazam]], [[Why? (American band)|Why?]], [[Wussy]], [[H-Bomb Ferguson]] and [[Walk the Moon]], and alternative hip hop producer [[Hi-Tek]] calls the [[Cincinnati&nbsp;\u2013 Northern Kentucky metropolitan area|Greater Cincinnati]] region home. [[Andy Biersack]], the lead vocalist for the rock band [[Black Veil Brides]], was born in Cincinnati.\n\nThe [[Cincinnati May Festival]] Chorus is an amateur choir that has been in existence since 1880.  The city is home to the [[Cincinnati Symphony Orchestra]], [[Cincinnati Opera]], Cincinnati Boychoir and [[Cincinnati Ballet]]. The Greater Cincinnati area is also home to several regional orchestras and youth orchestras, including the Starling Chamber Orchestra and the Cincinnati Symphony Youth Orchestra.  Music Director [[James Conlon]] and Chorus Director [[Robert Porco]] lead the Chorus through an extensive repertoire of classical music.  The May Festival Chorus is the mainstay of the oldest continuous choral festival in the Western Hemisphere.  [[Music Hall (Cincinnati)|Cincinnati Music Hall]] was built to house the May Festival.\n\nThe [[Hollows (series)|Hollows series]] of books by [[Kim Harrison]] is an [[urban fantasy]] that takes place in Cincinnati. [[American Girl]]'s ''[[Kit Kittredge]]'' sub-series also took place in the city, although the [[Kit Kittredge: An American Girl|film based on it]] was shot in Toronto.\n\nCincinnati also has its own chapter (or \"Tent\") of ''[[The Sons of the Desert]] (The Laurel and Hardy Appreciation Society)'', which meets several times per year.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Laurel and Hardy Appreciation Society of Cincinnati, Ohio|url=http://www.thechimptent.com|accessdate=November 29, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716225223/http://www.thechimptent.com/|archive-date=July 16, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCincinnati is the subject of a [[Connie Smith]] song written by [[Bill Anderson (singer)|Bill Anderson]], called [[Cincinnati, Ohio (song)|Cincinnati, Ohio]].\n\nCincinnati is the main scenario for the international music production of Italian artist and songwriter [[Veronica Vitale]] called \"Inside the Outsider\".  She embedded the sounds of the trains at [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] [[Downtown Cincinnati]], filmed her music single \"Mi Sono innamorato di Te\" at the [[American Sign Museum]] and recorded her heartbeat sound at [[Cincinnati Children's Hospital]] replacing it to the drums for her song \"The Pulse of Light\" during the broadcasting at [[Ryan Seacrest]]'s studio. Furthermore, she released the music single \"Nobody is Perfect\" featuring legendary Cincinnati's bass player [[Bootsy Collins]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1mzcWWydbGQ|title=Fox News presents Veronica Vitale working in Cincinnati|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=October 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\nCincinnati was a major early music recording center, and was home to [[King Records (United States)|King Records]], which helped launch the career of [[James Brown]], who often recorded there, as well as [[Jewel Records (Cincinnati record label)|Jewel Records]], which helped launch Lonnie Mack's career, and [[Fraternity Records]].\n\nCincinnati had a vibrant jazz scene from the 1920s to today. [[Louis Armstrong]]'s first recordings were done in the Cincinnati area, at [[Gennett Records]], as were [[Jelly Roll Morton]]'s, [[Hoagy Carmichael]]'s, and [[Bix Beiderbecke]], who took up residency in Cincinnati for a time. [[Fats Waller]] was on staff at [[WLW]] in the 1930s.\n\n==Media==\n{{Main|Media in Cincinnati}}\n\n===Newspapers===\nCincinnati's daily newspaper is ''[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]'', which was established in 1841. The city is home to several alternative, weekly, and monthly publications, among which are free weekly print magazine publications including ''[[Cincinnati CityBeat|CityBeat]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://citybeat.com/ |title=City Beat |publisher=City Beat |date= |accessdate=October 1, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513213336/http://www.citybeat.com/ |archive-date=May 13, 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> and ''[[TSJ Media|La Jornada Latina]]''.\n\n===Television===\nAccording to [[Nielsen Media Research]], Cincinnati is the 36th largest [[Media market|television market]] in the United States as of the 2016\u20132017 television season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lyonspr.com/latest-nielsen-dma-rankings/|title=2017 Nielsen DMA Rankings \u2013 Full List \u2013 Lyons Broadcast PR|publisher=|date=2017-01-19|access-date=January 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412071947/https://www.lyonspr.com/latest-nielsen-dma-rankings/|archive-date=April 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Twelve television stations broadcast from Cincinnati. Major commercial stations in the area include [[WLWT]] 5 ([[NBC]]), [[WCPO-TV]] 9 ([[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]), [[WKRC-TV]] 12 ([[CBS]], with [[The CW|CW]] on DT2), [[WXIX-TV]] 19 ([[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]), and [[WSTR-TV]] 64 ([[MyNetworkTV]]). In addition, locally owned Block Broadcasting has a presence with two [[Low-power broadcasting|low-power]] outlets: [[WOTH-CD]] 20 (shutting down January 23, 2018) and [[WBQC-LD]] 25. [[WCET (TV)|WCET]] channel 48, now known as CET, is the United States' oldest licensed public television station (License #1, issued in 1951).<ref>{{cite journal|author=Virginia Watson-Rouslin|title=Channel 48: A Muttering Voice in the T.V. Wilderness|journal=[[Cincinnati Magazine]]|date=February 1978|page=53|accessdate=November 17, 2009|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JQsDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA53|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130603023613/http://books.google.com/books?id=JQsDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA53|archive-date=June 3, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> It is now co-owned with [[WPTD|WPTO]] 14, a satellite of [[WPTD]] in nearby [[Dayton, Ohio|Dayton]].\n\n===Radio===\n{{See|Category:Radio stations in Cincinnati}}\nAs of December 2017, Cincinnati is the 30th largest [[Media market|radio market]] in the United States, with an estimated 1.8&nbsp;million listeners aged 12 and above.<ref>{{cite web|title=#30 Cincinnati|work=Radio Online|date=December 2017|accessdate=January 10, 2018|url=http://ratings.radio-online.com/cgi-bin/rol.exe/arb031|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180111202041/https://ratings.radio-online.com/cgi-bin/rol.exe/arb031|archive-date=January 11, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Major radio station operators include [[iHeartMedia]] and [[Cumulus Media]]. [[WLW]] and [[WCKY (AM)|WCKY]], both owned by iHeartMedia, are both [[clear-channel station]]s that broadcast at 50,000 watts, covering most of the eastern United States at night.\n\n==Transportation==\n{{Main|Transportation in Cincinnati}}\n[[File:Cincinnati Union Terminal, Queensgate, Cincinnati, OH (46807669624).jpg|thumb|[[Cincinnati Union Terminal]] serves Amtrak's ''[[Cardinal (train)|Cardinal]]'' line and houses several museums.]]\nThe city of Cincinnati has a higher than average percentage of households without a car. In 2015, 19.3 percent of Cincinnati households lacked a car, and increased slightly to 21.2 percent in 2016. The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016. Cincinnati averaged 1.3 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Car Ownership in U.S. Cities Data and Map|journal=Governing|url=http://www.governing.com/gov-data/car-ownership-numbers-of-vehicles-by-city-map.html|accessdate=May 4, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511162014/http://www.governing.com/gov-data/car-ownership-numbers-of-vehicles-by-city-map.html|archive-date=May 11, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe development of a [[light rail]] system has long been a goal for Cincinnati, with several proposals emerging over many decades. The city grew rapidly during [[Streetcars in Cincinnati|its streetcar era]] of the late 19th century and early 1900s. Public transit ridership has been in decline for several decades and bicycles and walking has accounted for a relatively small portion of all trips in the past.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}} Like many other midwestern cities, however, bicycle use is growing fairly rapidly in the 2000s and 2010s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citylab.com/commute/2011/09/substantial-increases-bike-ridership-across-nation/161/|title=Is Bicycle Commuting Really Catching On? And if So, Where?|publisher=|access-date=February 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131105808/http://www.citylab.com/commute/2011/09/substantial-increases-bike-ridership-across-nation/161/|archive-date=January 31, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1916 the Mayor and citizens voted to spend $6&nbsp;million to build the [[Cincinnati Subway]]. The subway was planned to be a 16-mile loop from Downtown to [[Norwood, Ohio|Norwood]] to Oakley and back to the east side of Downtown. [[World War I]] delayed the construction in 1920 and inflation raised the costs causing the Oakley portion never to be built.  Mayor Seasongood who took office later on argued it would cost too much money to finish the system.{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}  A century later, the [[Cincinnati Bell Connector]] streetcar line, which opened for service on September 9, 2016,<ref name=\"WVXU-2016sep9\"/><ref name=\"cinc-enq-2016sep9\"/> crosses directly above the unfinished subway on Central Parkway downtown.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecincinnatisubway.com|title=Cincinnati's Abandoned Subway|publisher=|access-date=December 6, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727041551/http://www.thecincinnatisubway.com/|archive-date=July 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cincinnati-transit.net/subway.html|title=CINCINNATI SUBWAY|publisher=|access-date=February 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160217185715/http://www.cincinnati-transit.net/subway.html|archive-date=February 17, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Cincinnati is served by [[Amtrak]]'s [[Cardinal (train)|Cardinal]], an intercity passenger train which makes three weekly trips in each direction between Chicago and New York City through [[Cincinnati Union Terminal]].  Cincinnati is served by the [[Southwest Ohio Regional Transit Authority]] (SORTA), the [[Transit Authority of Northern Kentucky]] (TANK) and the [[Clermont Transportation Connection]].  SORTA and TANK primarily operate 40-foot diesel buses, though some lines are served by longer articulated or hybrid-engine buses. In 2012\u201316, Cincinnati constructed a [[Cincinnati Bell Connector|streetcar]] line in Downtown and [[Over-the-Rhine]]. This modern version of the streetcar opened in September 2016.<ref name=\"WVXU-2016sep9\"/> The [[Cincinnati Streetcar]] project experienced railcar-manufacturing delays and initial funding issues, but was completed on-time and within its budget in mid-2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wlwt.com/news/supplier-issues-may-delay-cincinnati-streetcar-delivery/34525774|title=Report: Supplier issues may delay Cincinnati streetcar delivery|date=August 4, 2015|publisher=|access-date=February 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160223052949/http://www.wlwt.com/news/supplier-issues-may-delay-cincinnati-streetcar-delivery/34525774|archive-date=February 23, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://citybeat.com/cincinnati/article-28129-top_10_misrepresentations_of_the_cincinnati_streetcar_project.html|title=Top 10 Misrepresentations of the Cincinnati Streetcar Project|publisher=|access-date=February 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130716001911/http://www.citybeat.com/cincinnati/article-28129-top_10_misrepresentations_of_the_cincinnati_streetcar_project.html|archive-date=July 16, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/news/2016/08/03/it-s-official-streetcar-is-under-budget.html|title=It's official: Cincinnati Streetcar is under budget \u2013 Cincinnati Business Courier|access-date=August 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911200443/http://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/news/2016/08/03/it-s-official-streetcar-is-under-budget.html|archive-date=September 11, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA system of public staircases known as the [[Steps of Cincinnati]] guides pedestrians up and down the many hills in the city.  In addition to practical use linking hillside neighborhoods, the 400 stairways provide visitors scenic views of the Cincinnati area.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/dote/dote-programs/hillside-steps/ |title=Hillside Steps \u2013 Transportation & Engineering |publisher=Cincinnati-oh.gov |accessdate=July 10, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524113925/http://www.cincinnati-oh.gov/dote/dote-programs/hillside-steps/ |archivedate=May 24, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe city is served by [[Cincinnati/Northern Kentucky International Airport]] ([[IATA]]: '''CVG''') which is actually located in [[Hebron, Kentucky]]. The airport is a focus city for [[Delta Air Lines]] as well as low-cost carriers [[Allegiant Air]] and [[Frontier Airlines]]. In addition, the airport is the largest global hub for both [[Amazon Air]] and [[DHL Aviation]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Domestic Hubs |url=http://news.delta.com/index.php?s=20309&cat=3191 |publisher=[[Delta Air Lines]] |year=2015 |accessdate=January 25, 2015 |work=Delta.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140721104514/http://news.delta.com/index.php?s=20309&cat=3191 |archive-date=July 21, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=DHL opens super-hub at CVG |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/news/2013/06/13/dhl-opens-super-hub-at-cvg.html |date=June 13, 2013 |author=Wetterich, Chris |work=Cincinnati Business Courier |accessdate=January 25, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205005754/http://www.bizjournals.com/cincinnati/news/2013/06/13/dhl-opens-super-hub-at-cvg.html |archive-date=December 5, 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Cincinnati Municipal Lunken Airport]] ([[IATA]]: LUK), has daily service on commercial charter flights, and is located in [[Ohio]]. The airport serves as hub for [[Ultimate Air Shuttle]] and Flamingo Air.\n\nBus traffic is heavy in Cincinnati. [[Megabus (North America)|Megabus]] and [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound]] as well as several other, smaller motor coach companies operate out of Cincinnati, making trips within the midwest or beyond.  The city has an [[Orbital road|outer-belt]], [[Interstate 275 (Ohio)|Interstate 275]] (which is the longest circle highway in the country at 85 miles) and a spur, [[Interstate 471]], to [[Kentucky]]. It is also served by [[Interstate 71 (Ohio)|Interstate 71]], [[Interstate 74 (Ohio)|Interstate 74]], [[Interstate 75 (Ohio)|Interstate 75]] and numerous U.S. highways: [[U.S. Highway 22 (Ohio)|US 22]], [[U.S. Highway 25 (Ohio)|US 25]], [[U.S. Highway 27 (Ohio)|US 27]], [[U.S. Highway 42 (Ohio)|US 42]], [[U.S. Route 50 in Ohio|US 50]], [[U.S. Highway 52 (Ohio)|US 52]], and [[U.S. Highway 127 (Ohio)|US 127]].  The [[Riverfront Transit Center]], built under 2nd Street, is about the size of eight football fields. It is only used for sports games and school field trips.  When it was built, it was designed for public transit buses, charter buses, school buses, city coach buses, light rail, and possibly commuter rail.  On days it is not in use for sports games, it is closed off and rented to a private parking vendor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.go-metro.com/about-metro/about2/doingbusiness/doingbusinesswithmetro/riverfront-transit-center |title=Riverfront Transit Center|accessdate=February 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wcpo.com/news/local-news/i-team/i-team-48-million-transit-station-sits-empty|title=I-Team: $48 million transit station sits empty|first=Brendan|last=Keefe|date=October 31, 2011|publisher=|access-date=February 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160216100317/http://www.wcpo.com/news/local-news/i-team/i-team-48-million-transit-station-sits-empty|archive-date=February 16, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetransportpolitic.com/2009/07/07/cincinnatis-riverfront-transit-center-attracts-criticism/|title=Cincinnati's Riverfront Transit Center Attracts Criticism|date=July 7, 2009|publisher=|access-date=February 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112215226/http://www.thetransportpolitic.com/2009/07/07/cincinnatis-riverfront-transit-center-attracts-criticism/|archive-date=November 12, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{clr}}\n\n==Notable people==\n{{main|List of people from Cincinnati}}\n\n==Sister cities==\nCincinnati has ten [[town twinning|sister cities]].<ref name=\"sisters\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cincinnatisistercity.org/ | publisher=Cincinnati Sister City Association | title=Cincinnati Sister Cities | accessdate=February 5, 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218203503/http://www.cincinnatisistercity.org/ | archive-date=December 18, 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n\n* {{flagdeco|JOR}} \u2013 [[Amman]], Jordan\n* {{flagdeco|JPN}} \u2013 [[Gifu, Gifu|Gifu City]], Japan\n* {{flagdeco|ZWE}} \u2013 [[Harare]], Zimbabwe\n* {{flagdeco|UKR}} \u2013 [[Kharkiv]], Ukraine\n* {{flagdeco|PRC}} \u2013 [[Liuzhou]], [[Guangxi]], People's Republic of China <!--PRC must be spelled in full-->\n* {{flagdeco|DEU}} \u2013 [[Munich]], Germany\n* {{flagdeco|IND}} \u2013 [[Mysore]], [[Karnataka]], India\n* {{flagdeco|FRA}} \u2013 [[Nancy, France|Nancy]], [[Meurthe-et-Moselle]], France\n* {{flagdeco|ROC}} \u2013 [[New Taipei]], [[Taiwan]], Republic of China\n* {{flagdeco|HUN}} \u2013 [[Szeged]], Hungary\n\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|